<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-State Dept. Employee Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A former coordinator for State Department  
efforts to remove land and sea mines pleaded guilty Monday to a 
misdemeanor conflict of interest and agreed to pay a $20,000 fine, 
the Justice Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthew E.A. Lorin, 33, of New York, admitted to participating  
personally as a federal employee in a business matter in which he 
and his outside employer had a financial interest. As part of a 
plea bargain, a single count was filed against him in U.S. District 
Court here. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, Lorin was a special government employee of the State  
Department serving as special coordinator for the Public and 
Private Partnerships for President Clinton's 2010 Initiative of 
Demining in the Office of Humanitarian Demining. His job was to 
coordinate State's efforts to help remove land and sea mines 
worldwide with similar efforts by private groups. 
</P>
<P>
	During this period, Lorin was paid $20,000 by Americas Partners,  
a private, for-profit business, which was participating in a joint 
venture to develop a theme park, known as the Grand Oasis, in 
Israel and Jordan, the department said. Construction of the Grand 
Oasis required removal of land mines, and Americas Partners gave 
Lorin a 1 percent equity interest in the project. 
</P>
<P>
	In September 1998, Lorin telephoned Ambassador Dennis B. Ross,  
who was the State Department's special Middle East coordinator, 
identified himself as a State Department employee, described Grand 
Oasis and recommended that State support it, the Justice Department 
said. Lorin then sought permission from his government ethics 
adviser to send Ross a memo recommending the project for State 
Department support. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Justice Department said that, the next day without  
waiting for the ethics adviser's approval, Lorin sent the memo to 
Ross and others in the State Department. Subsequently, the ethics 
adviser told Ross to cease all activity at State on behalf of 
Americas Partners. 
</P>
<P>
	But Lorin took no action to withdraw his memo or advise any  
recipient that he was prohibited from sending it, the Justice 
Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	A plea agreement said Lorin has admitted his offense and agreed  
to pay a $20,000 fine. Magistrate Judge Deborah A. Robinson set 
sentencing for July 7. 

</P>
<P>
	sni  
</P>
</TEXT>
