<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TV's Boys in Blue Need Police OK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Standing in a makeshift New York police squad  
room, Larry Gregory and Dennis Higgins look every bit the cop. 
</P>
<P>
	Gregory rests his hands comfortably on his gun belt; Higgins  
folds his arms authoritatively across his chest. Their uniforms, 
complete with rank and insignia, have that been-around-the-block 
look. 
</P>
<P>
	But these boys in blue are not officers.  
</P>
<P>
	They are three of about 200 actors who make a living playing  
cops in New York-based movies and television shows. Their uniforms 
look worn because any actor playing a New York cop needs his own -- 
and a police permit to buy one. 
</P>
<P>
	``It costs less to hire a few actors with their own police  
uniforms than to pay an actor and rent a uniform,'' said Greg 
White, an assistant producer on NBC's ``Law &AMP; Order,'' which uses a 
handful of the actors in every episode. 
</P>
<P>
	In cities with fewer police dramas -- San Francisco, home to CBS'  
``Nash Bridges,'' and Baltimore, where NBC's ``Homicide'' is filmed 
-- uniforms are either rented or purchased by production companies. 
</P>
<P>
	But New York has always been a magnet for police dramas, from TV  
shows like the 1960s' ``Naked City'' and the '70s series ``Kojak,'' 
to movies, such as ``Dog Day Afternoon'' and ``Serpico.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, shows such as ``New York Undercover'' on Fox  
and ``Law &AMP; Order'' have set up shop in the city, increasing 
interest by actors in making a steady living playing police. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, would-be actors of police roles must fill out an  
application with the Mayor's Office of Film and Television for 
permission to buy an NYPD uniform, which costs about $800 from a 
certified retailer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We forward it on to the police department, which then does a  
background check to make sure the applicant has no criminal 
background,'' said Julienne Cho, spokeswoman for the mayor's film 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	Then they are told the rules: Do not wear the whole uniform in  
public and do not pass yourself off as a police officer. Both are 
punishable by jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Once approved, most register with casting agents who handle  
actors with ``special skills,'' such as those who own everything 
from police uniforms to antique cars, said Fleet Emerson of Sylvia 
Faye Casting. 
</P>
<P>
	The actors get paid $115 a day -- plus $18 for their uniform -- to  
work as police extras. 
</P>
<P>
	Gregory, 49, started playing cops 15 years ago as a struggling  
actor when he was told that actors with uniforms work more often. 
Since then, he's parlayed it into a regular income. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want no part of real danger. I'm only brave when the  
camera's rolling,'' joked the 49-year-old Gregory, who has been 
acting for nearly 25 years. ``But I take everything I do seriously. 
If I can put a human face on a police uniform, then I've done my 
job as an actor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Higgins, 56, started as a professional dancer in off-Broadway  
productions, but he switched to police work 10 years ago because 
``all dancers have to eventually move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both have studied police officers' mannerisms and picked up cop  
talk to help them with their portrayals, but they say they are 
careful not to act like police officers in public. 
</P>
<P>
	``At no point do I ever think I'm a police officer,'' Gregory  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of my pet peeves is when newer actors ... play with their  
guns on the set, not realizing how dangerous it is,'' he added. 
Blanks that the guns fire can cause harm. In 1984, actor Jon-Erik 
Hexum was fatally injured when he put a gun loaded with blanks to 
his head and pulled the trigger on the set of ``Cover Up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Gregory and Higgins say they have been approached, while on  
location around the city, by people asking for their assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tell them I'm an actor and point them to a real police  
officer,'' Higgins said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes that might be Lt. Dennis Cirillo, an NYPD veteran who  
acts in his spare time. ``The difference between them and me,'' he 
said, ``is that if I see something happen, I have to either take 
action or report it. This job never really stops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	MARY WITH `THE KING': Mary Tyler Moore turns up the heat when  
she makes a guest voice appearance on this week's ``King of the 
Hill.'' In its ``Revenge of the Lukefish'' episode, the Rev. Karen 
Stroup (Moore) comes to Arlen, Texas, and the congregation throws a 
potluck dinner to celebrate. But when Bobby binges on the new 
minister's Scandinavian lukefish dish, he ends up in the bathroom 
during her sermon and inadvertently sends the church up in smoke 
and the parish up in arms. ``King of the Hill'' airs Tuesday at 8 
p.m. EDT on Fox. 
</P>
</TEXT>
