<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italian, German Telecoms To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Telecom Italia SpA and Germany's Deutsche Telekom  
AG are expected to announce Tuesday that they are merging in a 
mega-deal that would create a new global competitor to U.S. giants 
such as AT&AMP;T. 
</P>
<P>
	The two firms' chief executives -- Franco Bernabe and Ron Sommer  
-- will outline the merger agreement at a news conference in London, 
said an official at Telecom Italia who spoke on condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The planned announcement ends days of frenzied speculation about  
such a move. A Telecom Italia-Deutsche Telekom combination would 
dwarf its competitors in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the deal could be upstaged by yet another that is  
reportedly in the works. The German business weekly Manager Magazin 
issued a news release Monday saying that Deutsche Telekom is also 
negotiating a takeover of U.S. telecommunications company Sprint 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a report to be published Friday in the magazine,  
Telekom boss Sommer has been negotiating a deal with Sprint Corp.'s 
Chief Executive William Esrey for several weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia confirmed late Sunday that it was examining the  
possibility of an industrial alliance with Deutsche Telekom. 
Telecom Italia is known to be seeking a white knight to save it 
from a hostile takeover bid by its smaller Italian rival, Olivetti 
SpA. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom and Telecom Italia have refused to say how they  
might share ownership in a combined company and have declined to 
say how they might calculate their respective values in any merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom has a market capitalization of about $117  
billion while Telecom Italia is at about $77 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema said today that any merger  
between Telecom Italia and Deutsche Telekom would require a 
privatization of the German company. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot imagine that a privatized Telecom Italia may merge  
with a company whose main shareholder is the German state,'' 
D'Alema told reporters. Deutsche Telecom is 72 percent-owned by the 
German government. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian government owns 3.4 percent of Telecom Italia, but  
it has veto power over the acquisition of more than 3 percent of 
the shares of the telecommunications company. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti has offered $12.31 a share for Telecom Italia. Olivetti  
plans to proceed with its tender offer despite the German-Italian 
merger talks, company spokesman Ugo Panerai said today. Olivetti 
has already filed a prospectus with the Italian regulatory body 
Consob. 
</P>
<P>
	In sheer size, merger between the German and Italian companies  
would rival the pending oil industry linkup between Exxon Corp. and 
Mobil Corp., now the largest in history. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia's board was meeting specifically today to address  
issues related to such a merger, the company official said from 
Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	A Deutsche Telekom spokesman in Bonn refused to say whether the  
German company's directors were planning a meeting of their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``Deutsche Telekom is examining Telecom Italia's potential in an  
industry alliance, but the elements of such an alliance are still 
under evaluation,'' Stephan Althoff said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Althoff declined to comment on newspaper reports that the two  
companies planned to fold their stock into a new telecommunications 
holding company on a 60-40 percent basis. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian prime minister's office has said that any accord  
must be on an equal footing, underlining fears in Italy of foreign 
ownership of the strategic telecommunications industry. 
</P>
<P>
	A merger also would raise a rash of regulatory issues. Deutsche  
Telekom has close financial and operational ties with another major 
telecommunications company, France Telecom. In addition, Deutsche 
Telekom is still majority owned by the German government, which 
would have to divest in order to gain approval of the deal from 
Italian regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	In Paris, France Telecom said today that Deutsche Telekom can't  
withdraw unilaterally from its strategic agreements with the French 
telecommunications group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our agreements with Deutsche Telekom are clear and  
incompatible with a unilateral strategic turnaround,'' France 
Telecom said. The companies own 2 percent of one another's stock. 

</P>
</TEXT>
