<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 15:05:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Explosion on USS Iowa Marked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- A former commander of the USS Iowa  
criticized the Navy for failing to apologize today for the way it 
handled a probe into an explosion aboard the battleship in which 47 
men died. 
</P>
<P>
	Retired Capt. Larry Seaquist said the Navy, which initially  
blamed a sailor for the blast, misled families about the nature of 
its investigation and harassed family members. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would have been very nice if the leadership of the Navy  
would have been here to say something simple to you, like `We 
apologize,''' Seaquist, the Iowa's skipper a year before the 
explosion, said during a service at the Norfolk Naval Base marking 
the 10th anniversary of the disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	Norfolk Naval Base spokesman Cmdr. Mike Andrews said, ``What  
Capt. Seaquist says is his opinion; that's his right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The World War II-era warship was conducting exercises in the  
Caribbean on April 19, 1989, when an explosion ripped through the 
turret of one of the ship's 16-inch guns. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy initially said the blast was caused by Clayton Hartwig,  
who they said committed suicide over a homosexual affair by 
deliberately detonating gunpowder. It later admitted there was no 
proof of that. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrews noted that Adm. Frank B. Kelso III, then the chief of  
naval operations, publicly apologized in 1991 to Hartwig's family. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hartwig's sister, Kathy Hartwig-Kubicina of Cleveland, said  
she and other Iowa families were grateful to Seaquist for his 
remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	``All we've ever asked for is somebody to stick up for us,''  
Mrs. Hartwig-Kubicina said. 
</P>
<P>
	The family's $12 million defamation suit is pending in federal  
court in Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	About 300 veterans and relatives of the victims attended  
Monday's ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
