<HEADLINE> Dow Industrials Up Nearly 200 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average was soaring  
this morning and on track for a sixth straight record close, as 
blue-chips were helped by strong earnings reports and merger news. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow was up 189.00 at 10.682.89,  
and its gains later rose to more than 200 points. On Friday, the 
Dow posted its fifth consecutive closing high, rising 31.17 to 
10,493.89. The record for consecutive records is 12, set in early 
1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also were rising, with the Nasdaq  
composite up 0.53 at 2,484.57, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 
composite up 15.54 at 1,334.54. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a pretty impressive array of companies that are  
doing better right now,'' said Ned Collins, a trader at Daiwa 
Securities. ``It includes all segments. All in all, the market is 
giving a pretty good performance, it looks like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the earnings front, Citigroup was up 2 5/8 at 74 1/4 and  
BankAmerica was up 2 3/4 at 75 3/4, after both posted strong earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	BellSouth's shares were up 1 at 42 3/16, after the company  
announced it will buy a 10 percent stake in Qwest Communications 
for $3.5 billion, increasing its presence in fiber optics. Qwest's 
shares were up 2 7/8 at 84 7/8 in Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq, which stunned Wall Street with dismal earnings  
projections earlier this month, disclosed on Sunday that chief 
executive Eckhard Pfeiffer had been ousted and its chief financial 
officer was leaving. The company's shares were up 5/16 at 23 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	But other computer-related shares were lower. IBM was off 1/4 at  
170 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a better than 3 to 1  
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 351.93 million 
shares, up from Friday's pace hectic pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Asian markets were mixed overnight, with Hong Kong's Hang Seng  
Index up 2.2 percent amid very strong foreign buying interest, but 
the Nikkei stock average in Tokyo down 1.05 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	European stock markets were mixed this afternoon. Germany's DAX  
index was up 1.24 percent, but Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.71 
percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.92 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
