<HEADLINE> California Patrol Tests Volvos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO (AP) -- The car of choice for soccer moms and yuppies  
is about to be put to the test by the California Highway Patrol. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past two years, the CHP has been quietly testing Volvos  
on its high-speed tracks at its academy in West Sacramento. 
</P>
<P>
	Next month, it plans to start deploying the imports for patrol  
duty and more testing on roads and highways throughout the state. 
</P>
<P>
	CHP Commissioner D.O. ``Spike'' Helmick said the department  
currently uses Fords. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no problem with continuing to buy Fords,'' Helmick  
said Sunday. ``But the concern is that if for some reason Ford got 
out of the business or the price went astronomically high, we've 
got to be prepared to go alternative ways.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A potential problem might be the cost. Now, the patrol pays  
$22,200 for a Crown Victoria compared with $27,500 for each Volvo 
test car. 
</P>
</TEXT>
