<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> RealNetworks Signs Broadcast Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Audio and video software developer RealNetworks  
Inc. has reached agreements with AT&AMP;T Corp. and other major 
telecommunications companies that provide backbone for the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The deals, announced Monday, are designed to boost the quality  
of video and audio broadcasts delivered over the net. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreements -- with Sprint Corp., GTE Corp. and other  
companies as well as AT&AMP;T -- will cut down on congestion by allowing 
RealNetworks to install sophisticated computer servers throughout 
the Internet network. 
</P>
<P>
	Those servers, connected to the company's RealBroadcast Network  
in Seattle via high-speed links, act as broadcasting hubs to handle 
local traffic. The servers also are equipped to shift traffic from 
one hub to another in cases of high demand. 
</P>
<P>
	RealNetworks already broadcasts news, special events and other  
material over the Internet. But the picture has not matched 
television standards, and some viewers of highly popular events 
like the Victoria's Secret fashion show earlier this year couldn't 
view the show live. 
</P>
<P>
	``This does make it very clear that not only are they a player,  
they are one of the significant players in the space, and it 
certainly shows a potential maturing of the Internet broadcast 
arena,'' said analyst Rob Enderle of Giga Information Group. 
</P>
<P>
	RealNetworks has about an 85 percent share of the market and  
about 57 million registered users. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
