<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Angels' Edmonds To Undergo Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- The injury curse has struck the Anaheim  
Angels again. 
</P>
<P>
	Center fielder Jim Edmonds, who won his second straight Gold  
Glove last season and has averaged nearly 28 homers over the last 
four years, will be sidelined about four months due to a severely 
injured right (non-throwing) shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Edmonds, 28, had been placed on the 15-day disabled list on  
April 4 with a strained groin and irritated shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	All along, it was expected he'd return to action sometime this  
month, but the Angels announced Monday he will undergo arthroscopic 
surgery Thursday to repair a torn labrum and possibly tighten his 
shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've tried a variety of avenues via medication and therapy to  
treat the shoulder,'' said Dr. Lewis Yocum, the Angels' medical 
director. ``The surgery should allow for full return of arm 
strength, but we will know more following the procedure. The 
minimum amount of recuperation time should be roughly four 
months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Edmonds, who hit .307 with 25 homers and 91 RBIs last season,  
was expected to travel to Toronto with the Angels on Monday for 
their three-game series against the Blue Jays that begins Tuesday 
night. However, he arrived at Edison International Field for some 
early work with batting instructor Rod Carew, and was unable to 
participate in any drills. 
</P>
<P>
	He then informed the team of his desire to undergo surgery.  
</P>
<P>
	The Angels, who have a long history of injuries to key players,  
thus will be without two of their best -- Edmonds and shortstop Gary 
DiSarcina -- for more than half this season. 
</P>
<P>
	DiSarcina was hit in the left forearm by a fungo bat being swung  
by coach George Hendrick, who was hitting grounders before spring 
training had officially started in Tempe, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	DiSarcina suffered a broken bone in his left forearm, but was  
expected to return to action sometime this month. However, it was 
determined shortly before the start of the season that he needed 
surgery. Now, he's not expected back before the All-Star break in 
mid-July. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, first baseman Mo Vaughn, who signed an $80 million,  
six-year contract with the Angels last November, suffered a 
sprained ankle in the first inning of his first game with the team 
on April 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughn is expected to be activated and back in the lineup late  
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The possibility of surgery was something that existed, the  
players and staff of this organization knew that,'' Angels 
spokesman Tim Mead said, alluding to the Edmonds announcement. 
``But while we look forward to Jim and Gary's return later this 
year, our players will remain focused on the task on hand. 
</P>
<P>
	After Vaughn was signed, many expected the Angels to trade  
either Edmonds or Garret Anderson because the team appeared to have 
a surplus of outfielders. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, they have to be relieved they didn't make such a move.  
</P>
<P>
	``We were not going to give away one of those outfielders  
despite all the rumors,'' Mead said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
