<HEADLINE> Wheat Prices Drop, Corn Rises / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures were sharply lower Monday on the  
Chicago Board of Trade, while corn and soybeans both posted gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were higher in early trading Monday before falling  
off. Bad weekend weather in growing regions of the United States 
probably did less damage to the crop than anticipated, analysts 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures opened lower Monday on follow-through from Friday's  
weak close. But by midmorning prices turned higher, analysts said, 
as updated weather forecasts called for a pattern of wet weather 
most of the week, which could delay planting. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're kind of getting into a weather market here with cold and  
wet weather into last week ... and this week,'' said Jack Scoville, 
a trader with Price Futures Group in Chicago. ``All of the sudden 
now you're looking at a little delay'' in getting the crop in the 
ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans futures followed corn higher and received support from  
soy meal, which was boosted by talk of loading delays in Brazil, 
Scoville said. That could mean more business for U.S. growers. 
</P>
<P>
	Cold weather in Brazil also provided support.  
</P>
<P>
	In trading Monday, wheat for May delivery was down 4 1/4 cents to  
$2.52 1/4 a bushel; May corn rose 2 1/2 cents to $2.20 1/2 a bushel; May 
oats fell 1/4 cent to $1.20 3/4 a bushel; and May soybeans rose 1 1/4 cents 
to $4.88 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle, feeder cattle and pork futures prices were mixed  
Monday on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose 0.10 cent to 63.45 cents a pound; May  
feeder cattle rose 0.10 cent to 71.70 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
climbed 0.63 cents to 55.30 cents a pound; and May pork bellies 
rose 1.00 cents to 56.60 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
