<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up More Than 200 Points / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average was soaring at  
midday and on track for a sixth straight record close. Stocks got a 
lift from strong earnings reports as investors continued to shift 
millions of dollars out of technology stocks and into industrial 
companies that, until recently, have lagged glamorous Internet 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow was up 234.78, or 2.24 percent,  
at 10,728.67, having sped past the 10,500, 10,600 and 10,700 
markers. On Friday, the Dow posted its fifth consecutive closing 
high, rising 31.17 to 10,493.89. The record for consecutive records 
is 12, set in early 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	With the gains, which came in heavy trading, the Dow is up  
nearly 17 percent so far this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed, with the Nasdaq composite  
down 10.89 at 2,473.15 amid a backup in technology shares. But the 
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 composite was up 16.26 at 1,335.26. 
</P>
<P>
	Ned Riley, chief investment officer at BankBoston, said  
industrial stocks are sharply higher because investors are flocking 
to this sector of the market, where there are far fewer shares 
outstanding than, say, technology companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are rotating out of stocks that had clearly been the  
winners in the last 15-24 months, into a market that has a much 
smaller market capitalization,'' Riley said. ``If the lemmings 
clearly are all trying to get through the door at the same time 
with mega-orders (for industrial stocks), that is clearly going to 
push the prices of these stocks higher because of the lack of 
liquidity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Alcoa, for example, were up 3 3/8 at 56 1/16.  
</P>
<P>
	Strong earnings reports were also pushing stocks higher.  
Citigroup was up 3 5/16 at 74 15/16, and BankAmerica was up 3 at 
76, both on earnings reports that surpassed analysts' expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Mergers and acquisitions also helped. BellSouth's shares were up  
1 1/4 at 42 8/16, after the company announced it will buy a 10 percent 
stake in Qwest Communications for $3.5 billion, increasing its 
presence in fiber optics. Qwest's shares were up 4 1/4 at 86 1/4 in 
Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	But technology shares continued to fall amid massive selling.  
IBM was down 2 7/8 at 168 1/2 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq was down 3/16 at 23 7/16, after giving up earlier gains.  
The computer maker, which stunned Wall Street with dismal earnings 
projections earlier this month, disclosed on Sunday that chief 
executive Eckhard Pfeiffer had been ousted and its chief financial 
officer was leaving. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a better than 3 to 1  
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 530.91 million 
shares at midday, up from Friday's pace hectic pace. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
