<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rodgers Fails To Break Over-50 Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- As disappointed as Bill Rodgers was in not  
finishing the 103rd Boston Marathon, he vowed it would not be his 
last attempt at conquering the difficult 26-mile, 385-yard course. 
</P>
<P>
	``Next year, I will run with my brother, Charlie,'' the  
51-year-old Rodgers said Monday, after dropping out with more than 
6 miles remaining, ``and we'll duke it out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to end my marathon career with a DNF.''  
</P>
<P>
	This was Rodgers' 16th Boston Marathon and the third time he  
dropped out, but the first time since 1977. Sandwiched around that 
last DNF were victories in 1976, 1978, 1979 and 1980. Twice, he 
broke the course and American records. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with Frank Shorter, the 1972 Olympic gold medalist and  
1976 silver medalist, Rodgers, also a four-time winner of the New 
York City Marathon, was responsible for the running boom in the 
United States. He was ranked the No. 1 marathoner in the world 
three times and won 21 marathons in his illustrious career. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston fans adore him. He was born in nearby Hartford,  
Conn., went to college at Wesleyan in Middletown, Conn., and earned 
his Masters degree in special education at Boston College. 
</P>
<P>
	He was given the nickname of ``Boston Billy.''  
</P>
<P>
	That's why so many of the enthusiastic fans who lined the course  
Monday were cheering loudly for Rodgers to do well. Rodgers had a 
goal -- to try to break the course record for an over-50 American of 
2 hours, 31 minutes, 34 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't to be.  
</P>
<P>
	After going through the half-marathon in a sprightly 1:14,  
Rodgers could manage only another seven miles before dropping out 
from dehydration. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm at an age where it wasn't a day to try for records,'' he  
said. ``Boston is one of the toughest races. Halfway I started to 
feel it. By the time I hit the hills, I was doing the marathon 
shuffle. I started to see some flashing lights, which is a sign of 
dehydration. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did my best. I made a smart decision. I did not want to keel  
over. I'm disappointed not to finish. I wanted to get to the line. 
Next time I run Boston I will be a back-of-the-pack runner and have 
some fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So if the youthful-thinking Rodgers returns in 2000, he will  
come back with a different attitude. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can run the pace, but I can't push hard for records,'' he  
said. ``I have to run more carefully, then I'll finish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This was Rodgers' first serious marathon since 1992 and his  
first legitimate attempt at Boston since 1990. He did run Boston in 
1996, but only because it was the race's 100th anniversary. His 
time of 2:53:23 was more than 33 minutes slower than his previous 
worst at Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	He wanted to run Boston last year, but didn't train properly.  
This year, he thought he was ready, having prepared since December 
and competed in six shorter races, but the 60-degree heat, the 
demanding course and age combined to thwart his effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Rodgers will continue his heavy running program -- he ran 29  
races last year -- and keep pushing for a team training program to 
help United States marathoners. He also will maintain an interest 
in his Boston store that sells his line of clothing, help promote 
races, conduct clinics and make speaking appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though he didn't finish the Boston Marathon on Monday, that  
doesn't mean his career is over. Far from it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
