<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Roba Wins Third Straight in Boston </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Fatuma Roba was tiring as she headed up a hill  
toward the end of the Boston Marathon. Then some friends handed her 
a red, yellow and green sweatband -- the color of the Ethiopian 
flag. 
</P>
<P>
	``The flag they gave me in the hilly area gave me a boost, and I  
started running at a faster pace,'' said the 27-year-old Ethiopian, 
who won her third Boston Marathon on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	After running even with Catherine Ndereba for a good part of the  
race, Roba pulled ahead near the three-fourths mark. While becoming 
just the second woman to win the event three times in a row, she 
posted the fourth-best time in race history -- 2 hours, 23 minutes, 
25 seconds -- for her gender. 
</P>
<P>
	Roba, the 1996 Olympic marathon champion, now holds the third-  
and fourth-fastest times for the Boston Marathon. She is bested 
only by Joan Benoit Samuelson, who finished in 2:21:43 in 1983, and 
by Uta Pippig, who ran it in 2:21:45 in 1994. Pippig is the only 
other woman to win three times in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Jennings, the 38-year-old runner with 10 USA Outdoor  
Championships and an Olympic bronze medal under her belt, outpaced 
all of her American competitors, coming in 12th overall with a time 
of 2:38:37. 
</P>
<P>
	It was only her second marathon. In 1978, when she was just a  
high school senior at the Bromfield School in Harvard, Jennings 
came in third as an unofficial entrant. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Jennings beat the time of 2:47 she set 21 years ago,  
perhaps starting a new phase of her 23-year running career as a 
marathoner. 
</P>
<P>
	She said after the race that she was happy she qualified for the  
Olympic trials by coming in under 2:42. 
</P>
<P>
	Her coach, John Babington, said she ran too fast early on.  
</P>
<P>
	``She was suffering, but she didn't break down completely,''  
Babington said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jennings said she didn't expect to tire quite so early. She ran  
even with the leaders for the first half of the 26.2-mile race and 
then faded over the next few miles. 
</P>
<P>
	The race was a blur, she said, except for the cheering of the  
fans who lined the entire route from Hopkinton to Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was absolutely carried along by the fans,'' said the  
Newmarket, N.H., resident. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half of the race, 20-year-old Sun Yingje of China  
ran well ahead of the pack at a very fast pace, nearly a minute 
ahead of her closest pursuer. 
</P>
<P>
	Roba and Ndereba, 20, of Kenya, ran behind Sun until they caught  
her at about 12 1/2 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	Roba later said she didn't even notice Sun until the middle of  
the race. 
</P>
<P>
	For the next four miles, the two African women were locked in a  
stride-for-stride battle until Roba began to open up against 
Ndereba. 
</P>
<P>
	Ndereba, making her marathon debut, fell behind 32-year-old  
Franziska Rochat-Moser at the three-quarter mark and finished 
sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	Rochat-Moser also is a lawyer who owns a gourmet restaurant in  
her hometown of Crissier, Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Yukio Arimori, 32, finished third. She is a heroine in her  
native Japan for her second-place finish in the 1992 Olympic 
marathon and third at the 1996 Atlanta Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
