<HEADLINE> Bonds Sits Out Second Straight Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Barry Bonds has a bone spur in his left  
elbow and was out of the lineup for the second straight day as the 
San Francisco Giants played the Florida Marlins on Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds, batting .366 with four home runs and 12 RBIs, was seeking  
a second opinion from San Jose Sharks physician Dr. Art Ting. 
Results of those tests were expected Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The All-Star left fielder's status remained day-to-day.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's no determination until we know what's wrong,'' Giants  
manager Dusty Baker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds had an MRI on Monday that revealed the spur. He missed  
Sunday's game against the Arizona Diamondbacks with soreness. 
</P>
<P>
	Stan Javier took Bonds' place in left field, and Ellis Burks  
assumed Bonds' No. 3 spot in the batting order. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you lose a superstar, sure it's going to be different,''  
Baker said. ``But you've got to do what you've got to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds, an eight-time All-Star, has been on the disabled list  
just once in his 14-year career. 
</P>
<P>
	There had been speculation Bonds might have been injured during  
Friday's brawl with the Diamondbacks, during which Giants third 
baseman Charlie Hayes and Arizona pitcher Todd Stottlemyre got into 
a bench-clearing melee. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me clear that up right now: Barry told me it was bothering  
him on Friday during batting practice,'' Baker said. ``That wasn't 
it at all, that's 20 years of throwing.'' 
</P>
