<HEADLINE> Dow Up 53 After 270-Point Gain / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials squandered a 270-point gain  
in heavy trading this afternoon as traders dumped technology shares 
and sent the Nasdaq composite index reeling. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the technology heavy Nasdaq composite  
was down 89.91 points, or by nearly 4 percent, at 2,394.13. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average was up 53.36 at 10,547.25 as  
the final hour of trading began and flirting with a sixth 
consecutive closing high. But the Dow then turned to negative 
territory. 
</P>
<P>
	The previous record, 10,493.89, was set Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	It was a rough ride, with the Dow up as much as 271.85 after  
racing through the 10,500, 10,600 and 10,700 levels by early 
afternoon before selling picked up to cash in on the rally and as 
technology stocks plunged. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 composite was down 14.87 at 1,304.13.  
</P>
<P>
	Rao Chalasani, chief investment strategist at Everen Securities  
in Chicago, said tech stocks had gone up for a long time ``without 
any particular relationship to value, and now they being sold 
aggressively, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning early last week, investors have been swapping tech  
shares for industrial names that have been out of favor for a long 
time, and the shift has pushed the Dow to new heights. But even a 
string of six straight records would be far from the record of 12 
set in early 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Today the Dow was led higher by such deeply cyclical names as  
International paper, up 3/4 at 55 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks were taking body blows. Dow member IBM was  
down 3 7/16 at 166 15/16. AOL had plunged 18 5/8 to 121 1/8 in leading 
volume on the Big Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Hyman, senior equity analyst at Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum,  
explained the pullback in the Dow this afternoon by saying that the 
market ``could only run so far on the backs of'' the newly favored 
industrial stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The industrial stocks are cheap relative to the previously  
high-flying technology sectors, but they can't play the role of 
long-term leaders because they represent a much smaller portion of 
the market than technology shares do, Hyman said. 
</P>
<P>
	'' At some point in time, the tech stocks have to participate  
again if we're going to get a major rally here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq was down 1/2 at 23 1/8, after giving up earlier gains. The  
computer maker, which stunned Wall Street with dismal earnings 
projections earlier this month, disclosed on Sunday that chief 
executive Eckhard Pfeiffer had been ousted and its chief financial 
officer was leaving. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong earnings reports were pushing some stocks higher. Dow  
member Citigroup was up 2 1/16 at 73 11/16, while BankAmerica was 
up 3/4 at 73 3/4, both on earnings reports that surpassed analysts' 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a better than 2 to 1  
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume was very heavy at 
982.34 million shares at late afternoon, up from Friday's hectic 
pace. 

</P>
</TEXT>
