<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Economies Starting To Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Asia's crisis-hit economies are starting to  
rebound but the recovery is fragile and clouded with uncertainties, 
the Asian Development Bank said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The outlook for 1999 depends on how governments carry out  
reforms to combat the causes of the turmoil and the mood of world 
financial markets, the bank said. 
</P>
<P>
	It said an unexpected slowdown in the United States or Europe  
and continuing stagnation in Japan, the region's economic 
locomotive, could stall recovery by reducing the demand for 
imports. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although the financial crisis still reverberates throughout  
the region, we are seeing distinct signs that this sharp 
contraction may be bottoming out,'' bank Vice President Peter 
Sullivan said, presenting the bank's annual ``Asian Development 
Outlook.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kicking off the spring meetings of the International Monetary  
Fund and the World Bank, the IMF will present its ``World Economic 
Outlook'' on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The report by the Asian Development Bank, a regional development  
bank based in Manila, Philippines, says growth in the developing 
economies of East and Southeast Asia, excluding China, was the 
lowest since World War II, averaging more than negative 7 percent. 
Only Taiwan weathered the storm with little damage. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1999, Sullivan said, the pace of recovery will vary, but the  
most dramatic turnaround is expected in Korea, which may record 2 
percent growth, compared with a negative 5.5 percent for 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	China, which rode out the crisis despite a slight decline in  
exports, will see growth slow to around 7 percent. India, Asia's 
other giant, which was not affected by the crisis, will continue to 
grow at last year's rate of nearly 6 percent if it can avoid 
political turbulence, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Southeast Asia's more developed countries, the Philippines  
and Malaysia are most likely to grow in 1999, although at modest 
rates, the bank said. In Thailand, where the crisis began 21 months 
ago, success depends implementing financial and corporate sector 
restructuring. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank expects average growth for developing Asia to increase  
from 2.6 percent in 1998 to 4.4 percent this year and reach 5.1 
percent in 2000. Average inflation should moderate from 6.5 percent 
to about 4 percent in 1999 as the shock of the late 1997 currency 
depreciations dies out. 
</P>
<P>
	``While we would love to say that the recovery is secure,''  
Sullivan said, ``there are clearly risks to our forecast,'' among 
them continued poor performance in the banking sector. Asian banks 
have been plagued by bad loans and bank failures. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia will continue to have the group's most uncertain  
prospects as its economy tries to fight back from the ``verge of 
total collapse,'' the bank said. Until the results of the June 
presidential elections are known, Sullivan said, it is hard to 
predict when Indonesia will see growth resume. 
</P>
<P>
	The unpredictability of financial flows into and within the  
region is also a source of uncertainty, the bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
