<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Decisions in Brief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Supreme Court took the following actions Monday:  
</P>
<P>
	--Agreed to decide whether people convicted of a crime have a  
constitutional right to refuse the help of lawyers and represent 
themselves on appeal. Salvador Martinez says California courts 
wrongly refused to let him serve as his lawyer in appealing an 
embezzlement conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	--Agreed to decide whether people can avoid using inherited money  
to pay overdue federal taxes by disclaiming their rights to the 
inheritance. An Arkansas man says his disclaimer under state law 
meant he never had an interest in his mother's estate to which the 
government could attach a lien. 
</P>
<P>
	--Heard arguments in a Colorado case in which the justices must  
decide whether government ownership of the coal located on an 
Indian reservation includes ownership of the methane gas found with 
the coal. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allowed two women to sue Volusia County, Fla., under the  
federal Endangered Species Act trying to force the county to do 
more to protect endangered and threatened sea turtles. The county 
had argued it could not be sued for allegedly doing a bad job of 
regulating private citizens' conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	--Refused to kill a lawsuit by a New York man that accuses the  
federal government of letting zoos and research facilities keep 
chimpanzees and other primates in inhumane conditions. A medical 
research group had argued that the man could not sue on his claim 
that seeing the animals in those conditions caused him emotional 
distress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
