<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> RFK Jr. Going Into Water Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Robert F. Kennedy Jr. says he's going  
into the bottled water business to protect tap water. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy has helped set up a company that will sell Keeper  
Springs Mountain Spring Water, which has the following message on 
its turquoise labels: ``Every American has the right to crystal 
clean drinking water from a public water supply.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keeper Spring water, which comes from a spring in Saratoga  
Springs, goes on the market Tuesday in the New York area, with 
plans for it to gradually become available around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea is to capture some of the $4 billion spent each year on  
bottled water. Kennedy will not take a salary, and he said any 
profits -- he's hoping for ``a couple of million dollars a year'' -- 
will go toward clean-water campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who drink bottled water are making a statement that  
they are turning their back on a public water supply,'' said 
Kennedy, son of the slain Sen. Robert F. Kennedy and an 
environmental law professor at Pace University in White Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	``It occurred to me that the best way to reach those people is  
on the label of a bottle of water.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy said he's so adamant about his campaign that he won't  
drink Keeper Springs. ``I drink tap water,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
