<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbia Offers $6.6B for Gas Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Columbia Energy Group has offered $6.68  
billion in cash and stock for Consolidated Natural Gas Co., topping 
the $5.5 billion that Dominion Resources Inc. offered for CNG under 
a deal approved two months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter Sunday to Pittsburgh-based CNG, Columbia Energy  
chairman and chief executive Oliver G. Richard III made an 
unsolicited offer of $70 a share for CNG stock -- $45.50 in cash and 
$24.50 in stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer represents a 33 1/2 percent premium above CNG's closing  
share price Friday of $52.43 3/4 and a 21 percent premium above 
Dominion Resources' stock offer, Richard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard asked CNG chairman and CEO George A. Davidson Jr. for a  
response by May 3 to his request for formal merger talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter Applewhite, a spokesman for Dominion Resources, said the  
company believed its merger was a superior deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Dominion Resources today announced it was  
restructuring its Virginia Power and Dominion Energy divisions into 
a unit to handle power generating and another unit to handle 
transmission and distribution. 
</P>
<P>
	Dominion Generation will become responsible for the 80 fossil,  
nuclear and hydroelectric generating units Virginia Power owns in 
Virginia, West Virginia and North Carolina and the 24 generating 
facilities in which Dominion Energy has ownership or operating 
interests in five U.S. states, Argentina, Belize, Bolivia and Peru. 
It will also hold a generating plant Dominion Resources owns in the 
United Kingdom. 
</P>
<P>
	A second subsidiary will retain the name Virginia Power and  
manage the utility's retail, customer service, transmission and 
distribution and operations functions. 
</P>
<P>
	The reorganization was approved late Friday by the Dominion  
Resources board of directors but was not announced until today 
after Columbia Energy's unsolicited offer to CNG. Dominion 
Resources' chairman, Thomas E. Capps, said the plans to merge with 
CNG helped create the perfect oppurtunity for the restructuring. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy had offered $66 to $70 a share for CNG two days  
before the Dominion Resources deal was announced Feb. 22, according 
to Richard's letter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to believe a combination of our two companies  
would be an excellent financial and strategic fit,'' Richard wrote. 
``... We have adequate sources of financing and therefore our 
proposal is not subject to any financing conditions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dominion Resources-CNG deal would create a company serving  
nearly 4 million customers with $8.8 billion in annual revenue. 
When the merger was announced, CNG shares were at $55.18 3/4 and the 
deal was valued at $6.3 billion. But CNG and Dominion Resources 
shares have fallen since then. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday, shares of CNG rebounded 7 percent, or $3.56 1/4, to close  
at $56 on the New York Stock Exchange. Dominion rose $1.56 1/4, or 4 
percent, to close at $39.62 1/2. Shares of Columbia fell $1.50, or 3 
percent, to close at $46.75. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy, based in Herndon in the northern Virginia  
suburbs of Washington, had 1998 revenues of nearly $6.6 billion. 
Its natural gas business includes exploration and production, 
transmission, storage and distribution, as well as propane sales 
and electric power generation. It serves customers in 34 states and 
the District of Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	CNG supplies natural gas to 1.9 million customers in Ohio,  
Pennsylvania, Virginia and West Virginia. It also owns 7,600 miles 
of gas pipelines in New York, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Virginia, West 
Virginia and Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	Dominion Resources, the parent company of electricity supplier  
Virginia Power, had $6 billion in revenues last year. It has 
operations in the United States, Canada, Great Britain, Argentina, 
Belize, Bolivia and Peru. 

</P>
</TEXT>
