<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BellSouth To Invest $3.5B in Qwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- BellSouth, long-silent in the scramble of mergers  
and alliances reshaping the telephone industry, is speaking up with 
a $3.5 billion investment in a long-distance company that's 
building a national fiber-optic network. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal announced Monday gives BellSouth a 10 percent stake in  
Qwest Communications International, a fast-growing, Denver-based 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Coordinated marketing efforts will begin now, but the real  
payoff for BellSouth depends on whether it finally wins state and 
federal clearance to enter long-distance market. 
</P>
<P>
	BellSouth and the other regional telephone monopolies can't  
offer long-distance to their customers until they convince 
regulators that they've opened their markets to competition for 
local calling service. 
</P>
<P>
	Until those conditions are satisfied, BellSouth and the other  
``Baby Bells'' are limited to 10 percent ownership in any 
long-distance company. 
</P>
<P>
	But once those hurdles are removed, BellSouth and Qwest would be  
free to package a comprehensive set of high-speed data, image and 
voice communications for business and residential customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest is completing an 18,500-mile fiber optic network serving  
more than 130 U.S. cities and has other high-capacity 
infrastructure projects under way. 
</P>
<P>
	BellSouth's primary service area is in Alabama, Florida,  
Georgia, Kentucky, Louisiana, Mississippi, North Carolina, South 
Carolina and Tennessee. As a first step, it has applied to offer 
long distance in Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	The link-up with Qwest follows a series of much larger deals in  
the telecommunications industry, including SBC Communications' 
planned acquisition of Ameritech and Bell Atlantic's agreement to 
purchase GTE. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, industry analysts and investors were pleased with the  
partnership. 
</P>
<P>
	``It may look like a smaller move, but it has a very distinctly  
different flavor,'' said Phil Asmundson, a telecommunications 
partner with Deloitte Consulting. He said Qwest has been a ``very 
aggressive long-distance network builder,'' and the deal ``sets a 
platform'' for future growth for the two companies. 
</P>
<P>
	In Monday's trading on the New York Stock Exchange, BellSouth  
rose 68 3/4 cents per share, or 1.7 percent, to $41.87 1/2. But in Nasdaq 
trading, Qwest finished unchanged at $82 a share, surrendering an 
early $10 gain amid a sharp downturn on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the rapid change occurring in the communications  
industry today, there is no doubt that together we have the 
potential to be an even more significant driving force,'' said 
Duane Ackerman, BellSouth's chairman and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Ackerman expressed optimism Monday that his Atlanta-based  
company will gain permission sometime this year to offer 
long-distance service in Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement with Qwest, BellSouth will pay $1.93 million  
in cash for roughly 20.3 million Qwest shares. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Qwest's principal stockholder, Anschutz Co., will  
sell 16.65 million of its shares to BellSouth for about $1.57 
billion. This will reduce Anschutz's stake in Qwest to about 39 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is expected to close by the end of May.  
</P>
<P>
	In addition to local service, BellSouth provides wireless  
communications, digital television, and Internet and data services 
in 19 countries. Its primary service area 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest has more than 8,000 employees and 80 sales offices in  
North America, Europe and Mexico. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
