<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gives Back Most of 270-Pt. Gain / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a stunning and swift market swing, the Dow  
Jones industrial average nearly squandered a 270-point gain this 
afternoon as investors took profits in industrial stocks and 
technology shares tumbled. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow was up 17.97 at 10,511.86,  
after erasing all of a 271.85-point and then beginning to climb 
back. The Dow was on its way to making its sixth consecutive 
closing high, having risen 31.17 to 10,493.89 on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators retreated, giving up early gains, with  
the Nasdaq composite down 83.26 at 2,400.78 amid aggressive selling 
of technology shares. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 composite was down 
14.19 at 1,304.81. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Hyman, senior equity analyst at Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum,  
said the market ``could only run so far on the backs of'' the 
industrial stocks that had suddenly come into favor last week and 
taken the Dow to new heights. 
</P>
<P>
	The industrial stocks are cheap relative to the previously  
high-flying technology sectors, but they can't play the role of 
long-term leaders because they represent a much smaller portion of 
the market than technology shares do, Hyman said. 
</P>
<P>
	'' At some point in time, the tech stocks have to participate  
again if we're going to get a major rally here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Industrial stocks were still leading the Dow average higher,  
with International Paper, for example, up 2 5/16 at 57 5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	But technology stocks were still lower amid massive selling. IBM  
was down 5 13/16 at 164 9/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq was down 5/8 at 23, after giving up earlier gains. The  
computer maker, which stunned Wall Street with dismal earnings 
projections earlier this month, disclosed on Sunday that chief 
executive Eckhard Pfeiffer had been ousted and its chief financial 
officer was leaving. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong earnings reports were pushing some stocks higher.  
Citigroup was up 2 1/2 at 74 1/8 on earnings reports that surpassed 
analysts' expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a better than 2 to 1  
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume was heavy at 841.49 
million shares at midafternoon, up from Friday's hectic pace. 

</P>
</TEXT>
