<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wage Restraints Needed in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- Singapore's labor chief told citizens they  
should not expect wage restraints to be lifted this year, despite 
reports of an economic recovery, a newspaper reported Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we push for too much wage increase, we may stall the  
recovery,'' Lim Boon Heng, head of the National Trades Union 
Congress and Minister without Portfolio, was quoted as saying by 
The Straits Times on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	To help citizens ride out the regional economic crisis,  
Singapore adopted a multibillion-dollar cost-cutting package last 
year that slashed the average resident's income by at least 15 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But hopes for an early recovery were revived in recent weeks,  
following a rise in the stock and property markets, as well as 
official announcements that economic growth this year could be 
higher than previously expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite signs that the Singapore economy is bouncing back, Lim  
cautioned that the recovery is ``fragile and uncertain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is better that we be cautious and continue broadly with the  
consensus we reached last year than to say we should go for 
specific wage increases,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lim added that factors outside Singapore, like social and  
political problems in neighboring countries, will determine how 
fast the city-state can pull out of the recession. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
