<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Approves New Breast Cancer Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A device that uses electricity to map possible  
breast lumps may reduce the number of women who get unnecessary 
biopsies because their mammograms are unclear, the government said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration approved TransScan Medical  
Inc.'s T-Scan 2000 as an extra tool for radiologists to use in 
determining whether women with ambiguous mammogram results need an 
immediate biopsy to check for cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	American women undergo 30 million mammograms a year. The breast  
X-ray is the gold standard in detecting breast cancer, particularly 
early tumors. 
</P>
<P>
	Mammograms often clearly show which breast lesions should be  
biopsied immediately. But they also can be ambiguous, leaving a 
doctor in doubt as to whether to do a biopsy immediately, or to 
wait six months and X-ray again. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 800,000 biopsies are done every year, from which 180,000  
women are diagnosed with breast cancer. The rest are benign lumps. 
So scientists have hunted ways to reduce unnecessary biopsies 
without missing women who have cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Some doctors use ultrasound machines that use sound waves to  
picture lumps as an addition to the mammogram's X-rays. 
</P>
<P>
	The T-Scan 2000 is another alternative. It uses electricity to  
create a map of the breast. 
</P>
<P>
	A one-volt shot of electricity is sent into the hand, where it  
travels through the body into the breast. A handheld probe is moved 
over the breast, where it measures the electrical conductivity of 
breast cells. Cancer cells conduct much less electricity than 
healthy cells -- so when the probe flashes its findings onto a 
computer screen, possible tumors show up as bright white spots. 
</P>
<P>
	TransScan's studies suggest that adding the electricity test for  
women with ambiguous mammograms can improve diagnostic accuracy and 
lower unnecessary biopsies by about 20 percent, said company 
president George Solomon. 
</P>
<P>
	The T-Scan should be used only in women whose doctors cannot  
decide about ordering a biopsy based on other standard procedures, 
said Dr. Dan Schultz, FDA's chief of radiological devices. Women 
with ambiguous mammograms may need biopsies anyway, based on 
results of clinical breast exams or if they have close relatives 
with breast cancer. Those women don't need the T-Scan test. 
</P>
<P>
	What if the T-Scan incorrectly suggests that a woman doesn't  
need an immediate biopsy? Doctors already order a new mammogram 
within six months for women with ambiguous X-rays, advice that the 
T-Scan doesn't change, Schultz said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new scan should add less than $100 to a woman's exam,  
Solomon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990419.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 23:52:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Airways Top Airline in Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a complete turnaround, US Airways has moved  
from worst to first in a survey of major U.S. airline quality. 
</P>
<P>
	The change was an exception in a year that continued to see a  
decline in airline quality, as measured by two university 
professors who looked at on-time performance, denied boardings, 
mishandled luggage and passenger complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	``Generally, airlines do a good job of getting you from point A  
to point B on time and with your luggage,'' Dean Headley, associate 
professor of marketing at Wichita State University in Kansas, said 
in a statement released Monday. ``Evidently, the consumer is 
finding fault in the manner in which these services are being 
delivered. The airlines seem to be taking the attitude, `We get you 
there safely with your belongings. What else do you want?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Passenger dissatisfaction with such treatment has fueled a spate  
of legislative proposals aimed at securing new privileges for 
airline passengers. The congressional measures collectively have 
been dubbed an airline passenger's ``Bill of Rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joining Headley in the study was Brent Bowen, director of the  
Aviation Institute at the University of Nebraska. Their index used 
15 criteria for ranking airline quality. The information is drawn 
from government reports and other data readily available and deemed 
relevant to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	In the pair's 1997 survey, Southwest Airlines placed first and  
US Airways was last among the 10 major carriers, defined by the 
Transportation Department as airlines with operating revenue of $1 
billion or more per year. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, Southwest dropped to fifth and US Airways vaulted to  
the top of the pack. Propelling US Airways were relatively low 
claims of denied boardings -- when a ticketed passenger is denied a 
seat on a full aircraft -- and mishandled bags. 
</P>
<P>
	The full ranking was: US Airways, Continental Airlines, American  
Airlines, Delta Air Lines, Southwest Airlines, America West 
Airlines, TWA, Alaska Airlines, Northwest Airlines and United 
Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	United had the worst baggage handling record of all the majors,  
according to the survey. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
