<DOCNO> APW19990419.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 15:05:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mrs. Clinton Edges Closer to Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton, edging closer to running  
for Senate, opened a campaign-style swing Monday by declaring, ``I 
love New York,'' as her fledgling political operation combed the 
state for potential campaign workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm obviously still considering and exploring and am very  
interested,'' Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet she tried to minimize the political implications of the  
trip, which included talks about the humanitarian crisis in Kosovo 
and other traditional first lady fare. The White House called the 
trip an official function, thus U.S. taxpayers picked up the tab. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not an exploratory trip. This is a trip filled with  
events and occasions, some of which I agreed to do months ago,'' 
Mrs. Clinton told reporters after urging private foundations to 
help ease the Kosovo refugee crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Her aides, however, conceded the trip had political  
implications. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess anytime we're up here, it's part of the (exploratory)  
process,'' said press secretary Marsha Berry. ``She's thinking 
about this. I don't know when you turn it off and turn it on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friends and associates say Mrs. Clinton appears to be leaning  
toward a Senate bid, though some believe she will forgo the race at 
the last minute. Their assessments are based on clues from private 
conversations with her and the full-speed-ahead groundwork being 
laid by top political aide Harold Ickes. 
</P>
<P>
	The former deputy White House chief of staff has begun compiling  
lists of campaign operatives in the event she takes the plunge. He 
has secured commitments from some potential staff, said a source 
close to Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	One longtime associate said Mrs. Clinton told him two weeks ago  
that she intended to run, but would not finalize her decision until 
June or July. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton scheduled scores of New York stops Monday, Tuesday  
and -- after returning to Washington on Wednesday -- again Thursday, 
from Long Island to Niagara Falls. Monday's unusually crowded 
schedule contained seven stops, including the Columbia University's 
Teachers College, the Ukrainian Institute, the Jewish Child Care 
Association and a fund-raiser for Rep. Jerry Nadler, D-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Teachers, Ukrainians and the Jewish community are important  
Democratic constituencies. Nadler, a House Judiciary Committee 
member, staunchly defended President Clinton during the impeachment 
process. 
</P>
<P>
	The trip brought Mrs. Clinton fresh evidence that a Senate race  
against probable Republican nominee Rudolph Giuliani would be 
difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest poll from Marist College's Institute for Public  
Opinion showed the pair in a dead heat, with half saying Mrs. 
Clinton should not run. The New York mayor has gained ground since 
a February Marist poll, which had Mrs. Clinton leading Giuliani, 49 
percent to 38 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one said it was going to be a cakewalk,'' said Sen. Charles  
Schumer, D-N.Y., who ousted Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato last 
November and has urged the first lady to run. ``This is going to be 
a tough, tough race, but I think as people get to know her, she'll 
do better and better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers inside and outside the White House are studying whether  
Mrs. Clinton should form an exploratory committee to raise money 
that would defray the costs of future trips. She said would 
consider the move ``if it becomes appropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a brief news conference, Mrs. Clinton explained for the first  
time why a Senate race interests her: ``I love New York, to start 
with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With gushing reverence, Mrs. Clinton called New York ``a  
microcosm of America,'' with a ``dynamic, diverse city'' that would 
enable her to deal with issues such as education and health care 
that are as important in New York as they are across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Using the collective ``we'' in a way that could include the  
first lady herself, Mrs. Clinton said, ``We have everything in New 
York that we have in America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also announced plans to travel to Albania and Macedonia ``as  
soon as I'm given the green light'' by humanitarian workers, whose 
efforts she does not want to disrupt. 
</P>
<P>
	As for her career, Mrs. Clinton told several associates in  
recent days that she has concluded that serving in the Senate would 
be a good next step for her. When word first surfaced of her 
interest, Mrs. Clinton had told these same people she wasn't sure 
if she wanted to be in a Republican-controlled Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The new question: Is she willing to risk losing? Though a senior  
adviser said Mrs. Clinton is not afraid of defeat, other associates 
say she tends to avoid taking great risks. 
</P>
<P>
	Most friends and associates spoke on condition of anonymity.  
</P>
<P>
	Sandra Feldman, president of the American Federation of Teachers  
and a Mrs. Clinton supporter in New York, suggested the first lady 
is inclined to run. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't get a feeling that a final decision has been made yet,  
but I think she's very interested,'' Feldman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton was urged to run at every stop, including a Central  
Park event concerning hiking trails. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to wish her all the best as she hits a different kind  
of trail right here in New York state,'' said Rep. Carolyn Maloney, 
D-N.Y., as Mrs. Clinton, from the front row, shook her head from 
side to side. At another event, NBC ``Today Show'' host Katie 
Couric joked that Mrs. Clinton was ``taking time out from apartment 
hunting'' in New York to appear. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
