</P>
<P>
	Compaq's CEO and CFO Resign  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Eckhard Pfeiffer, who helped build Compaq  
Computer Corp. into the world's largest personal computer maker, 
resigned as chief executive officer yesterday after the company 
warned nine days ago of a stunning shortfall on profits. Compaq on 
April 9 said its first-quarter results are expected to show a 
profit of 15 cents per share on revenue of $9.4 billion -- $600 
million lower than expected. Earl Mason, Compaq's chief financial 
officer, also resigned. Shares of Compaq, which traded as high as 
51 1/4 earlier this year, were trading today at 23 7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	J&AMP;J Won't Sponsor 2002 Olympics  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Johnson &AMP; Johnson became the first sponsor  
to pull out of the scandal-ridden Olympics, backing off an 
estimated $30 million deal for the 2002 Winter Games. The company 
blamed the decision on internal disagreements about how to link the 
company's many brands under a sponsorship umbrella in time for the 
Salt Lake City Games. A spokesman said bribes connected to the 
Olympics were a factor. 

</P>
<P>
	Italian, German Telecoms May Ally  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Telecom Italia SpA confirmed today that it is  
considering a merger with Deutsche Telekom AG. A deal between the 
telecommunications giants could be the biggest alliance in history, 
beating the pending $73.7 billion linkup between Exxon Corp. and 
Mobil Corp. 

</P>
<P>
	Nissan: We'll Cut Without Layoffs  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Nissan Motor Co. is not planning layoffs or plant  
closings as part of its campaign to slash 5,000 jobs over the next 
two years, the company's president said today. The president of 
Japan's second-largest carmaker said the company is considering 
trimming staff through early retirement, shifting employees to 
affiliated companies and shutting down sections of plants. 

</P>
<P>
	BellSouth Is Buying Into Qwest  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- BellSouth Corp. plans to invest about $3.5  
billion for a 10 percent equity stake in long-distance company 
Qwest Communications International. Denver-based Qwest will issue 
about 20.3 million new shares to BellSouth in exchange for 
approximately $1.93 billion in cash. In addition, Qwest's principal 
stockholder, Anschutz Company, will sell another 16.65 million 
shares to BellSouth for approximately $1.57 billion. This will 
reduce Anschutz Company's ownership interest in Qwest to 
approximately 39 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Imports Fall 50 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's imports in January and February were down  
50 percent compared to the same period last year, as the devalued 
ruble made foreign goods too expensive for most Russians, officials 
said today. The ruble has gone from around six to the U.S. dollar 
before an economic crisis hit Russia in August to about 25 today. 
The report said exports have also declined more than 18 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom To Buy CAI Wireless  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- MCI Worldcom, the nation's No. 2 provider of  
long-distance calling service, is buying CAI Wireless Systems for 
about $414 million. MCI WorldCom has been the only major telephone 
company without a stake in wireless communication. CAI Wireless has 
been seeking a partner since its emerged from bankruptcy protection 
in October 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Five To Compete in Domain Name Game  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Five companies will be chosen this week to  
compete with Network Solutions Inc. in the business of registering 
Internet addresses. Network Solutions has had an exclusive contract 
with the federal government for registering World Wide Web 
addresses, such as those ending in with .com, .net and .org, since 
1993. But the government moved to end that monopoly last year by 
creating a nonprofit group to deal with administration of the 
Internet. The government must still reach a deal with Network 
Solutions on how to distribute its database. 

</P>
<P>
	WTO OKs Sanctions in Banana Dispute  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The World Trade Organization approved U.S.  
sanctions against the European Union today in a dispute over the 
import of bananas, trade diplomats said. The United States claims 
the EU discriminates unfairly against bananas imported from Latin 
American nations and favors those from former European colonies in 
the Caribbean and Africa. The WTO did not say when the sanctions 
would start. Washington has said it will slap tariffs of up to 100 
percent on products including French handbags, German 
coffee-makers, bed linen and cardboard packing material. 

</P>
<P>
	Toyota, GM To Make Fuel-Cell Cars  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Toyota Motor Corp. and General Motors Corp. have  
reached a five-year agreement to jointly develop cars and trucks 
that can run off fuel cells and other environmentally friendly 
alternative-fuel technology. Fuel cells produce electricity using a 
chemical reaction between hydrogen and oxygen and produce little or 
no emissions. GM, the No. 2 automaker, was the first to mass-market 
an electric car, which has failed to catch on. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: International trade  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Jobless claims  

</P>
