<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Coalition Likely Forming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Nationalist parties dominated Turkish  
elections yesterday and appear poised to form a coalition 
government, an administration that will likely rule out compromises 
with Kurdish activists and adopt a tough policy toward Cyprus. 
</P>
<P>
	A coalition between Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit's Democratic  
Left Party and the far-right Nationalist Movement Party, which led 
the voting, is also likely to lead to a chill in relations with the 
European Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey is a NATO member and a key U.S. ally in the unstable  
Middle East and Balkans. U.S. warplanes that patrol northern Iraq 
are based in southern Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation has had six governments since 1995, and an unstable  
coalition would jeopardize the chances for needed economic reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecevit's party and the Nationalist Movement Party, or MHP, were  
leading the vote with 22 percent and 18 percent respectively, 
according to results based on a count of 75 percent of the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	A coalition government must be formed, and the most likely  
parties to do so would be Ecevit's party, the MHP and the 
center-right Motherland Party, which was taking 14 percent of the 
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The Islamic Virtue Party -- the largest in parliament -- took only  
15 percent of the vote. The military, which has seized power three 
times since 1960, has ruled out any changes to the country's 
secular system and was at constant odds with Islamic activists. 
</P>
<P>
	``The voters don't want a military coup in Turkey. People saw  
that Virtue could have led to one,'' wrote Ismet Berkan, a 
columnist for the daily Radikal. 
</P>
<P>
	Many people who voted for Virtue's predecessor, the Welfare  
Party, apparently voted for the MHP, which is also deeply religious 
but does not mix Islam and politics. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said that fears of Kurdish activism also pushed voters  
toward Ecevit and the MHP. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the backlash,'' said Dogu Ergil, a political science  
professor at Ankara University. 
</P>
<P>
	It is almost certain that Ecevit, a staunch secularist who is  
popular with the military, will not invite the Islamic party into 
any coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	The nationalist coalition that appears most likely would be led  
by Ecevit, who ordered the 1974 Turkish invasion of Cyprus and saw 
his popularity soar after Turkish commandos captured Kurdish 
guerrilla leader Abdullah Ocalan in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecevit's policies are likely to be strengthened further in such  
a coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the foreign policy stage, there would be an absolute  
toughening,'' said Coskun San, a sociology professor at Ankara 
University. ``No concessions will be given on Cyprus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The island has been divided into a Greek Cypriot south and a  
Turkish-occupied north since Turkey invaded in 1974 after a coup by 
supporters of union with Greece. 
</P>
<P>
	The MHP is adamantly opposed to any compromises with Kurdish  
activists and is against any concessions on Cyprus. It also calls 
on Turkey to focus its foreign policy on the Turkic Central Asian 
states such as Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan rather than Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The party's sudden rise has worried some Turks, who identify the  
movement with the Gray Wolves, the party's youth branch. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gray Wolves battled leftists in the 1970s in clashes that  
killed 5,000 people and prompted the military to seize power in 
1980. Mehmet Ali Agca, the man who shot Pope John Paul II in 1981, 
was a Gray Wolf. 
</P>
<P>
	The party, however, has recently softened its image and now  
calls for an end to government corruption and respect for 
tradition. It is not clear how much influence they would have in an 
Ecevit government. 
</P>
<P>
	In the southeast, a pro-Kurdish party won the mayorships of at  
least six cities, the first time such a group has won local 
elections. 
</P>
<P>
	But the chances of the Kurds achieving any reforms on the  
national level seem to have diminished with the success of the MHP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
