<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lilly To Develop Cancer Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Eli Lilly and Co. announced a joint venture  
Monday with French drugmaker Sanofi to develop a treatment for 
colorectal cancer in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, the latest in a string of partnerships to tap  
innovations at other companies, may help Lilly carve out a new 
identity as a leading marketer of cancer therapies, chairman and 
chief executive Sidney Taurel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanofi developed oxaliplatin, a platinum-based cancer agent  
that's already being sold in 14 countries as a first- or 
second-line treatment for advanced colorectal cancer, in 
combination with a second drug called 5-FU. 
</P>
<P>
	The venture plans to submit oxaliplatin for review by the Food  
and Drug Administration by the end of September. It would seek 
approval to sell the drug as a first-line treatment for metastatic 
colorectal cancer, in combination with 5-FU. Approval could take a 
year or more. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly did not disclose financial details of the partnership,  
other than to say it would pay Sanofi an upfront fee and other 
payments for a share of U.S. sales of oxaliplatin. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are bringing to the party our knowledge of the cancer  
market in the U.S. and an established sales force which has 
established relationships with cancer specialists,'' Taurel said at 
a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Oxaliplatin joins a new-drug pipeline at Lilly that includes a  
product called MTA to treat tumors in breasts, lungs, the pancreas, 
colon, head and neck, and a hormone treatment for breast cancer. 
Lilly also is studying the potential of its osteoporosis drug 
Evista to prevent breast cancer. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
