<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Work of Breast Implant Panel Upheld </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- A federal judge Monday refused to throw  
out the work of an expert panel that found no link between breast 
implants and disease, rejecting women's claims that members were 
biased toward manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Sam Pointer ruled that the findings of the  
four-person panel were not tainted by the fact one member took a 
$750 honorarium from a company that used to make implants. 
</P>
<P>
	Pointer said he should have been more explicit in explaining  
what was expected of committee members, whom he appointed to be 
completely impartial and free of any conflicts of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I take some responsibility for that,'' said Pointer, who  
presides over thousands of federal lawsuits filed by women who 
claim breast implants harmed their health. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision cleared the way for attorneys to begin taking sworn  
testimony from committee members this week. Videotapes of the 
sessions will be available for use in implant cases nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Women's attorneys last week asked Pointer to block the testimony  
and disband the committee since one member, rheumatologist Peter 
Tugwell, accepted $750 from former implant maker Bristol-Myers 
Squibb Co. to attend a three-hour meeting dealing with issues other 
than implants. 
</P>
<P>
	Tugwell, chairman of medicine at the University of Ottawa, also  
solicited $5,500 in donations from Bristol-Myers Squibb and 3M, 
another defendant in implant cases, to sponsor conferences he 
helped organize. And a close colleague accepted at least $200,000 
to do work for a Bristol-Myers Squibb subsidiary. 
</P>
<P>
	Ralph Knowles, representing women with implants, said Tugwell's  
1996 appointment to the panel would have been ``dead on arrival'' 
had Pointer known of all his dealings with implant companies. 
</P>
<P>
	But attorneys for Bristol-Myers Squibb and the science panel  
argued that Tugwell followed all the court's rules and had no 
dealings involving breast implants with any company. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no conflict of interest, certainly as defined by this  
court,'' said John Kobayashi, representing the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	While refusing to overturn the work of the committee, Pointer  
said women's lawyers could question Tugwell about his ties to 
implant companies during his testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of women have sued claiming implants are to blame for  
illnesses including rheumatoid arthritis, lupus, aches, fatigue, 
memory loss and hardening of the breasts. They contend science 
backs up the claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Implant makers deny their products are a threat, and they say  
the work of the science panel and researchers proves it. They 
contend women's attorneys built their cases on bogus science. 
</P>
<P>
	Pointer, who has been in charge of all federal implant cases for  
more than six years, appointed the panel to sort out the 
conflicting scientific opinions. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
