<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Asks $6B for Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton asked Congress today for $6  
billion in emergency spending to sustain the U.S. military 
engagement in Kosovo and increase aid to ethnic Albanians fleeing 
the province. He urged quick, bipartisan action, and congressional 
leaders said they would give the request prompt attention. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO: We May Have Killed Civilians  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- After five days of agonizing, NATO  
acknowledged today that it may have killed an undetermined number 
of civilians in an attack on a convoy in Kosovo. In an elaborate 
explanation by Brig. Gen. Dan Leaf, commander of the air wing at 
Aviano air base in Italy, NATO described attacks last week near the 
town of Djakovica. Yugoslav officials reported about 80 people dead 
from the April 14 attack in the Yugoslav province, but NATO and 
other officials question the casualty figure as well as other 
details of the Serb report. 

</P>
<P>
	Annan To Discuss Kosovo in Moscow  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan said today he  
will go to Moscow next week to discuss the Kosovo conflict. Annan 
told the Security Council in closed consultations of his plans to 
add a day onto a previously scheduled visit to Germany from April 
26-28. U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard confirmed that Annan had 
consulted with the Russian government and decided to travel to 
Moscow on April 29. Last Friday, Yugoslavia rejected the key 
element of Annan's Kosovo peace initiative, saying an international 
military force in Yugoslavia was unacceptable. 

</P>
<P>
	Toyota, GM To Make Fuel-Cell Cars  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Toyota Motor Corp. and General Motors Corp. have  
reached a five-year agreement jointly to develop cars and trucks 
that can run off fuel cells and other environmentally friendly 
alternative-fuel technology. The joint effort should lead to result 
in commercially viable advanced technologies faster and at a lower 
cost to customers, GM vice chairman Harry Pearce said. The new 
venture will involve research and development of electric, hybrid 
electric and fuel-cell technology. Hybrid electric vehicles 
typically combine an electric motor with other power systems. 

</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma City Bombing Remembered  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Relatives clutched flowers, photos and  
buttons, wiped away tears and hugged children as they gathered 
today on the plaza where four years ago victims of the federal 
building bombing were brought. In the low-key ceremony marking the 
anniversary of the bombing, a crowd of about 300 looked out over a 
site under construction as workers took a morning break from their 
tasks in building a memorial. The bombing killed 168 people. 

</P>
<P>
	Spacecraft's Main Antenna Stuck  
</P>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- The main communications antenna on  
NASA's Mars Global Surveyor spacecraft has become stuck and unable 
to automatically point toward Earth. Jet Propulsion Laboratory 
spokeswoman Mary Hardin said today that a hinge on the antenna 
stopped moving late last week and flight controllers were unable to 
solve the problem during the weekend. The antenna can still be used 
even if the hinge doesn't work. But that requires periodically 
halting the collection of science data and turning the entire 
spacecraft to point the antenna at Earth. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 26; Nasdaq Down 96  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 26.12 at 10,520.01. The Dow had been up more than 
270 earlier today. Advancers on the NYSE outnumbered decliners 
2,147-963. The Nasdaq Composite Index was down 96.75 at 2,387.29. 

</P>
<P>
	Chebet Wins Boston Marathon  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Joseph Chebet, a runner-up no more, pulled away  
today with about four miles left and became the ninth straight 
Kenyan to win the Boston Marathon. And Fatuma Roba of Ethiopia, a 
winner again, became the second woman to capture the race three 
straight years. She took the lead just past the midpoint and was 
unofficially timed in 2 hours, 23 minutes, 25 seconds, easily 
beating the 2:25:51 of Franziska Rochat-Moser of Switzerland. 
Chebet, who finished second to countryman Moses Tanui by three 
seconds in last year's race, also was runner-up in the last two New 
York City marathons and, like Roba, takes home a first-prize of 
$80,000 from the $525,000 purse. 

</P>
<P>
	Devil Rays 4, Red Sox 1  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Rolando Arrojo pitched seven strong innings and  
John Flaherty drove in two runs with a double and home run as the 
Tampa Bay Devil Rays beat Boston 4-1 in the annual Patriot's Day 
game. The Devil Rays won three of four games in the weekend series, 
holding the Red Sox to two runs or less in each of the victories. 
Boston has dropped five of seven after starting the season 5-1. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PRUDENCE HELLER  

</P>
