<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Playoffs Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	With Wayne Gretzky retiring, the NHL lost its biggest name. Now,  
some teams will be playing without their own big names when the 
Stanley Cup playoffs begin Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia's Eric Lindros, Phoenix's Jeremy Roenick and Derian  
Hatcher of the Dallas Stars are among those who will be out of 
action when the NHL opens postseason play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody realizes that Eric won't be back for the first  
round, and it's not an issue,'' linemate John LeClair said. ``We're 
not just sitting here wishing he was back, we're going ahead 
without him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers will open at Toronto, and Phoenix will face St. Louis  
at home on Thursday, while Dallas will play host to Edmonton on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros is recuperating from a collapsed lung suffered more than  
two weeks ago in Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	Roenick has a broken jaw as the result of a hit by Hatcher,  
along with a broken thumb. Hatcher is in the midst of a seven-game 
suspension as the result of that illegal hit, and will miss the 
first five games of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas-Edmonton game is one of four Wednesday night. The  
others: Anaheim at Detroit, San Jose at Colorado and Buffalo at 
Ottawa. 
</P>
<P>
	In other Thursday night games, it's Pittsburgh at New Jersey and  
Boston at Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars, who won the Presidents' Trophy with the NHL's best  
record and the Jennings Trophy for fewest goals yielded, also are 
expected to miss high-scoring forward Pat Verbeek. 
</P>
<P>
	No matter, said forward Mike Keane.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're pretty confident,'' he said. ``You have to feel  
confident when you win the Jennings and the Presidents' Trophy. We 
had a good year, but now it's a whole different season. We're ready 
to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Oilers might be in trouble. They were 0-3-1 vs. Dallas  
during the season and two of their top players -- Bill Guerin and 
Josef Beranek -- are out with knee injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Detroit Red Wings are going for their third  
straight Stanley Cup, which would put them in pretty good company. 
No NHL team has won that many in a row since the New York Islanders 
pulled off four straight in 1980-83. 
</P>
<P>
	Defenseman Larry Murphy strikes a cautious note.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at every team out there in the west, it's going to  
be a battle again. ... You can't take anything for granted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings and Mighty Ducks are two of the few teams without  
any major injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're deeper than we ever have been in past years, in every  
position,'' said Detroit goaltender Chris Osgood. 
</P>
<P>
	Since an 0-4-1 start, the Avalanche have been on a tear --  
particularly in the second half of the season. And goaltender 
Patrick Roy, who has already won three Stanley Cups, has never 
looked better. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo and Ottawa played five overtime games this season, with  
the Senators holding a 1-0-4 edge. It will again be a battle of 
goalies: Buffalo's Dominik Hasek vs. Ron Tugnutt or Damian Rhodes. 
</P>
<P>
	``With Ottawa, you're dealing with a team that has great team  
speed,'' Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff said. ``They've had one heck of a 
year. Both their goaltenders have had a heck of a year.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
