<DOCNO> APW19990419.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 15:45:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marathon's Hill Does Its Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: AP Cleveland correspondent John Affleck ran his  
first Boston Marathon on Monday. His goal had been to finish in	
under 3 hours. This is the fourth and last of his stories about his	
experience.	
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Veterans of the Boston Marathon spook race rookies  
with tales of Heartbreak Hill the way grandparents scare their 
grandchildren with ghost stories. 
</P>
<P>
	And like those youngsters, the rookies listen with a mix of fear  
and skepticism. How bad could Heartbreak be, they think, even if it 
is the most famous climb at Boston and comes between the 20- and 
21-mile marks of the race? 
</P>
<P>
	After running my first Boston Marathon on Monday, I can say  
this: it can be pretty darn bad. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-mile Newton hills stretch of the course, which  
culminates with Heartbreak, took me from racing mode to survival 
mode. It feels good to be alive now. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, I ran 3 hours, 4 minutes, and -- I think -- about 10  
seconds, although, frankly, I was so bleary coming across the 
finish line I didn't stop my watch for a few more seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	That was slower than my ultimate goal in this race, breaking the  
3-hour barrier, but I don't feel down. In fact, I'm quite happy 
(when I don't have to walk) because I beat my personal best time by 
about 4 minutes and got to enjoy the spectacle of one of the 
world's great marathons. 
</P>
<P>
	And it is a spectacle.  
</P>
<P>
	From the start at Hopkinton on, the field is a lovely mass of  
color in motion. Fans are vociferous and everywhere -- from the 
patrons of a biker bar blasting Van Halen's ``Running with the 
Devil'' at 2 miles to the huge crowds lining the downtown streets 
down the home stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	A memorable crowd moment: early in the race, I caught up to a  
training buddy from my hometown of Cleveland who had a slightly 
better seeding than I did. 
</P>
<P>
	My friend, Jeff Ziol, and I had agreed that we would focus on  
trying to break 3 hours and ignore the crowd, particularly the 
women at Wellesley College near the halfway point. While their 
cheering is wonderful, and nearly deafening, it can also pump up 
runners too much, causing them to speed up and waste energy. 
</P>
<P>
	But as Ziol and I cruised past Wellesley, we found ourselves  
egging on the crowd to get louder. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh well,'' Ziol said. ``So much for that.''  
</P>
<P>
	``What the heck,'' I said. ``How often do you get screamed at  
like a Beatle?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ziol and I pushed each other pretty hard before we reached the  
hills at 16 miles. After the race, we realized both of us had 
wanted to slow down a little bit but we were afraid to tell each 
other for fear of seeming wimpy. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, I paid the price more than Ziol, who finished in  
2:57. As we climbed through the Newton hills, the effect of going 
up and down, up and down, on a hot day took its toll. My legs were 
cramped, peripheral vision diminished and brain started to fog. 
</P>
<P>
	By Heartbreak, I was jogging -- not racing. It was time for a new  
plan. 
</P>
<P>
	I told myself what remained of the race was just like my daily  
run. I went from drinking two cups of water a mile to three. I 
decided to enjoy the crowd a bit. 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing a singlet emblazoned with the name of my alma mater,  
Notre Dame, I tried to feed off the dozens of spectators who yelled 
``Go Fighting Irish!'' and the drunk guy who tried to sing the 
school's fight song. 
</P>
<P>
	Gradually, five miles to go became four, three, two and I was  
downtown, turning on Boylston Street for the last quarter-mile. 
</P>
<P>
	I remembered the advice of a friend who said I should wave to  
the crowd and blow kisses in those last yards. ``It's our Super 
Bowl,'' he said. But if this was the Super Bowl, the Boston course 
was the Denver Broncos and I was the Atlanta Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, I managed a smile as I crossed the line -- what a relief.  
A post-race feeling of good will has now set in, and I'm not 
worried about soreness or blisters. 
</P>
<P>
	But I know that sometime in the next few days a little voice in  
my head will say, ``You know, if you just go out a little slower, 
you might be able to break 3 hours at Boston.'' And pretty soon 
after that, I'll be back out on the hills, running long. 
</P>
<P>
	Wait 'til next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
