<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Asthma Drug May Fight Allergies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Merck &AMP; Co. has made a mild splash with its  
first asthma medicine, a chewable pill called Singulair that 
children can take once a day. But the drug's big payoff could come 
treating a much more common respiratory nuisance: hay fever. 
</P>
<P>
	A Merck-funded study of 458 patients last year showed those who  
combined Singulair with the best-selling allergy pill Claritin had 
substantially milder hay fever symptoms -- such as runny nose and 
itchy eyes -- than those who used Claritin alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Buoyed by these early findings, some allergists have already  
begun prescribing Singulair for seasonal allergies and Merck is 
continuing to research the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	Combining Singulair and Claritin into one pill could make for a  
blockbuster drug, according to experts. 
</P>
<P>
	About 35 million Americans suffer from hay fever, twice as many  
as those with asthma. And, about half of all people with asthma 
also suffer from hay fever. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes clinical, scientific and practical sense to treat  
with one medication,'' said Eli Meltzer, a principal investigator 
on the Singulair-Claritin study and professor of pediatrics at 
University of California-San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	But Schering-Plough Corp.'s patent on Claritin runs until 2004,  
so industry analysts say Merck will either have to wait or sign a 
co-marketing agreement with its competitor. Or it could set its 
sights lower simply by seeking Food and Drug Administration 
approval to sell Singulair alone for allergies. Neither company 
would disclose whether they are in talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering likely has little interest in Singulair, one analyst  
said. ``It already has a perfect drug. It does not need anything to 
muddy the waters,'' said David Sachs of Gruntal &AMP; Co. 
Schering-Plough also is in advanced human testing of its 
second-generation Claritin drug. 
</P>
<P>
	Claritin, which had U.S. sales of $1.9 billion last year is one  
of the most popular prescription medicines in the country. Claritin 
has more than 50 percent of the allergy market, largely due to its 
status as the only once-a-day antihistamine that does not cause 
drowsiness. Schering-Plough's heavy TV, magazine and billboard 
advertising has further pushed demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Singulair was launched in March 1998 and had sales of $194  
million last year. Its introduction was billed as big step forward 
in treating childhood asthma. Its most important benefit is that 
the chewable pill is significantly easier for children to use 
compared to corticosteroids, which must be taken by high-pressured 
inhalants that are difficult to use. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the convenience, some doctors still consider Singulair a  
weak sister to the more potent corticosteroids. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said Singulair sales were somewhat disappointing last  
year considering many expect the drug to eventually hit $1 billion 
in annual sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Singulair sales could grow by hundreds of millions if it could  
get U.S. approval for the drug as a supplement to Claritin, 
analysts said. ``It could be humongous,'' said Sachs. 
</P>
<P>
	Merck has experience finding new uses for established drugs.  
Last year, it started selling a version of its prostate drug 
Proscar as a hair growth pill called Propecia. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
