<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 23:24:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Get More Union Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Labor unions are hedging their bets by  
increasing campaign contributions to moderate Republicans as they 
pledge millions of dollars to help their longtime allies the 
Democrats win control of the House in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, the 20 labor unions that directed the most money to  
congressional candidates for last year's elections increased their 
contributions to Republicans by almost one-third, to $2.1 million, 
over the two-year 1996 election cycle. 
</P>
<P>
	Although union money still overwhelmingly favors Democrats, a  
pattern of increasing contributions since Republicans took control 
of Congress in 1994 shows some unions believe if you can't beat 
'em, join 'em at a fund-raising dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a real effort on our part to ensure that moderate  
Republicans -- those who are standing with working families -- are 
getting support from the labor movement,'' said Steve Rosenthal, 
the AFL-CIO's political director. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Republicans won control of Congress in 1994, the 20 union  
political action committees analyzed by The Associated Press gave 
only $881,630 to Republican candidates over the 1993-1994 election 
cycle. 
</P>
<P>
	``Labor unions are now falling into the pattern that we already  
saw in previous elections with other major PACs, which is to 
increase their funding to members of the majority party,'' said 
Anthony Corrado, a professor of government at Colby College in 
Waterville, Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	``What this represents is basically conceding to the fact of  
Republican control of the Congress and the need to gain access to 
the members who will make the important decisions,'' Corrado said. 
</P>
<P>
	This is not to say the unions are abandoning their old friends:  
The same 20 labor PACs contributed far more, $27.2 million, to 
Democrats in 1997-98, a review of disclosure reports showed. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, AFL-CIO leaders have pledged to raise more than $40  
million for television ads and mobilizing voters for the 2000 
election, an effort that would primarily help Democratic 
candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Political reality, however, is forcing organized labor to reach  
out to moderates in the party that controls Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they're always contributing to Democrats, it's going to be  
hard for them to get into the door to even meet Republicans,'' said 
Rep. Peter King of New York, a pro-union Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	The AFL-CIO's Rosenthal made a conciliatory move recently,  
assuring Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, chairman of the National 
Republican Congressional Committee, that unions would support 
pro-labor Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	NRCC officials also met with International Brotherhood of  
Teamsters representatives. Mike Mathis, Teamsters director of 
government affairs, said he was working to arrange a meeting 
between new union President James P. Hoffa and House Speaker Dennis 
Hastert, R-Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Education Association and its PAC so far this year  
have given $55,000 to national GOP committees and $5,000 to Rep. 
Johnny Isakson, the Georgia Republican elected to complete the 
congressional term of former Speaker Newt Gingrich. 
</P>
<P>
	Another union, the American Federation of State, County and  
Municipal Employees, more than doubled its Republican giving, from 
$41,925 in 1995-96 to $92,000 in 1997-98. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were not looking at parties. We were looking at records of  
candidates of both parties who stood with working families,'' 
federation spokeswoman Cheryl Kelly said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans welcome the union support.  
</P>
<P>
	``Union bosses and the Democrat Party have long marched together  
on the wrong side of issues affecting working Americans, like tax 
relief and job creation,'' Republican National Committee spokesman 
Tim Fitzpatrick said. ``This shift, small as it is, is an overdue 
sign that union leaders are finally listening to tens of thousands 
of American workers who vote Republican.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic National Committee spokesman Rick Hess said unions  
overwhelmingly favor his party because of its lawmakers' stands on 
issues including minimum wage, Medicare and Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not concerned that some members of the Republican Party  
are starting to moderate their anti-union concerns,'' Hess said. 
``We are concerned that the party that currently controls Congress 
has such a terrible labor record.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
