<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Little Insight on India's New Govt. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *AP Photos DEL108    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Sonia Gandhi and the Congress Party said  
today they are waiting for India's president to ask them to lead a 
new government, but gave no clue about what form it would take. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi, the widow of assassinated Prime Minister Rajiv  
Gandhi, met with her 140 lawmakers to discuss a Congress-led 
coalition to replace the Hindu nationalist-led one that collapsed 
by one vote on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are certainly going to form the government,'' Mrs. Gandhi  
said after the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consultations are going on with members of the other  
parties,'' she said. But differences are already flaring up among 
the groups that could support a Congress government. Two of the 
five communist and leftist parties that Mrs. Gandhi needs said they 
opposed joining Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we didn't have differences why would we be meeting?''  
communist leader A.B. Bardhan told The Associated Press after a 
gathering of communist groups. He said further discussions would be 
held after India's national budget is approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress leaders said they had unanimously agreed to let the  
Italian-born Mrs. Gandhi, their choice for prime minister and a 
political novice, make whatever decisions are needed to form a new 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as there is an invitation from the president, Sonia  
Gandhi will call on him,'' Congress party spokesman Arjun Singh 
said. ``There will be no problem in forming an alternative 
government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, the Bharatiya Janata Party, which led the government  
that collapsed Saturday, charged that Congress does not have enough 
support to form a long-term majority coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	The BJP demanded that the president reject anything less than a  
solid majority, since he required that Prime Minister Atal Bihari 
Vajpayee show he had support from a majority of Parliament before 
he took office 13 months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Congress party can't provide a viable alternative  
government,'' BJP spokesman Venkaiah Naidu said Monday. ``The 
choice is the Vajpayee government or fresh elections.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Congress party agreed that the proposed budget of  
the outgoing government would be adopted Wednesday without debate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not want to create any financial crisis arising out of  
the non-passage of the annual budget,'' Mrs. Gandhi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Politicians believe President K.R. Narayanan is waiting for the  
budget to actually pass the fractious 45-party lower house on 
Wednesday before inviting anyone to form a government. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock market, which plunged 7 percent when Vajpayee lost the  
confidence vote Saturday, responded positively to the news that the 
pro-business budget would pass by rising 3.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Without a budget, the government would run out of spending power  
by mid-May, tax provisions that went into effect in April would 
have to be reversed, and investors would see India as even more 
risky. 
</P>
<P>
	But business and industry remain nervous about the strong  
possibility of India's third election in as many years if Congress, 
which has fewer seats in Parliament than Vajpayee's BJP, fails to 
muster a stable government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
