<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Dole Supports Ground Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole, a Republican presidential  
hopeful fresh from her trip to Macedonia, said today that U.S.-led 
NATO ground troops should be ``pre-positioned in the theater'' and 
prepared to attack if necessary to end the purge of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a war,'' she said in a telephone interview with The  
Associated Press. ``We've got to win it, and win it absolutely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former American Red Cross president, a veteran of scores of  
humanitarian crises, said she was moved by her visit to refugee 
camps and the harrowing stories of Serbian attacks in Kosovo. 
``I've seen a lot of things that will haunt me forever,'' she said. 
``This is among the worst.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole and a crowded field of attention-starved GOP  
presidential candidates are eager to find a voice in the debate 
over the Yugoslavia conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, urged the Clinton administration  
Friday to pursue mediation with Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic rather than escalate the conflict. With her remarks, Mrs. 
Dole staked out a hard-line stance with fellow GOP hopeful Sen. 
John McCain of Arizona, a former prisoner of war who has said for 
weeks that the United States must do whatever necessary to win. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain has criticized Clinton for ruling out the use of ground  
troops, a stance Mrs. Dole echoed. 
</P>
<P>
	``With NATO meeting (in Washington) this week, the United States  
should demand military and humanitarian victories by calling for 
the pre-positioning of ground forces,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Would she support a ground war?  
</P>
<P>
	``If NATO commanders and the Joint Chiefs of Staff say ground  
troops, I say absolutely. I'd follow what they think is necessary. 
If that's ground troops, so be it,'' Mrs. Dole said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They should be pre-positioned in the theater so they'd be  
ready,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how many U.S. troops she thought might be killed in a  
ground war, Mrs. Dole said, ``That's not something I'm in position 
to know. All I know is we have to win this war absolutely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also called for more intense airstrikes, suggesting that the  
Clinton administration has hampered Pentagon planners. ``I think 
the political leaders have defined what we're doing, not the 
military leaders,'' she said. ``Let the military leaders do their 
jobs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole, wife of 1996 presidential nominee Bob Dole, said  
Milosevic should be branded a war criminal and eventually brought 
to justice. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, what we have to do is drive him and his forces out  
of the area,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
