<DOCNO> APW19990419.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 12:05:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Looks for Hope in Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- In tiny, mountainous Hong Kong, where property  
is a precious and scarce commodity, investors are hoping the first 
land auction in nine months will answer a key question: Is the 
recession-mired economy finally headed for recovery? 
</P>
<P>
	The government halted land sales in June to curb a slide in  
property prices. Tuesday's auction is a small one, with just three 
prime residential locations. 
</P>
<P>
	But the issues have drawn keen bidding interest and indications  
of satisfactory prices. Analysts expect the sales to fetch about 
1.2 billion Hong Kong dollars, or $154 million. That's less than 
the government could have gotten in the market's peak in 1997 but a 
figure analysts say would be respectable in the shrinking economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks in key property developers rallied Monday, helping to  
pull the blue-chip Hang Seng Index up by 2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The auction will reflect developers' confidence in the market.  
Prices they offer for the sites will translate into the kind of 
property prices they expect to see in the next few years,'' 
predicted Kinson Au, a property analyst for Amsteel Research (HK) 
Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong's leaders are anxious for a good showing. The  
government ``has engineered the auction so that it would not 
fail,'' said Otto Wong, a property analyst for Salomon Brothers 
Hong Kong Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Property prices in this congested city with a fast-growing  
population are among the highest in the world because land suitable 
for construction is scarce. 
</P>
<P>
	In the real-estate industry's heyday, developers' offices were  
swamped with speculators any time new developments went on sale. 
Rampant speculation drove prices out of reach of most middle-income 
families, many of whom live in government-subsidized housing. 
</P>
<P>
	But last year, Asia's financial turmoil sent property prices  
plunging by 50 percent and officials halted all land sales in June 
to try to prop up the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the drop, apartments are still more expensive than in  
most major cities, with a tiny two-bedroom apartment in a central 
location easily going for 3.3 million Hong Kong dollars ($420,000). 
</P>
<P>
	Recently, the real-estate industry has gained optimism as  
interest rates have eased and foreign funds have returned to Asia, 
driving regional stock markets up. Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index has 
risen nearly 25 percent since the beginning of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite the improving market sentiment, analysts are not  
expecting any big surprises Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Developers will remain cautious because the profit margins  
remain quite low after the financial crisis, judging from property 
prices today,'' Au of Amsteel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald Tsang, the territory's financial secretary, told  
reporters that property prices will unlikely shoot back to the 
levels seen before the financial crisis because the government is 
committed to ensuring adequate land supply to house the growing 
population. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market will not go erratic,'' he said. But with land  
supply still at a premium, Hong Kong ``will not become a very cheap 
real estate market.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990419.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 16:39:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Former E. German Premier Stoph Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Former East German Premier Willi Stoph, who was  
dropped as a defendant in a manslaughter trial for killings at the 
Berlin Wall because of illness, has died at age 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Stoph died April 13 in Berlin following a long illness, Hanno  
Harnisch of the Party of Democratic Socialism, which succeeded the 
East German communist party, said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Berlin on July 9, 1914, to a working-class family, Stoph  
joined a Communist youth group in 1928. He served in Hitler's army 
as a private in the artillery from 1940-42 and was released after 
being wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	According to his biography, Stoph studied at the Lenin Academy  
in the Soviet Union after the war and attended Soviet army weapons 
schools. 
</P>
<P>
	He became East Germany's first defense minister in 1956 and was  
known as the architect of the East German People's Army. 
</P>
<P>
	Stoph moved up in East Germany's Politburo hierarchy to become  
premier in 1970, succeeding Otto Grotewohl. He met the same year 
with then-West German Chancellor Willy Brandt for talks to ease 
relations between the communist East and capitalist West. 
</P>
<P>
	As East Germany's communist rulers faced growing pressure for  
reform from a peaceful, popular uprising, Stoph was ousted Nov. 7, 
1989, along with East German leader Erich Honecker. Two days later, 
the Berlin Wall was opened. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with Honecker and four other defendants, Stoph went on  
trial in Berlin on Nov. 13, 1992, charged with 13 counts of 
manslaughter in the killings of people trying to escape East 
Germany. He was dropped from the case in August 1993 after the 
court decided he was too sick to continue because of heart 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Honecker was also dropped from the trial due to illness. He died  
in exile in Chile in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
