<HEADLINE> Religious Advertising Pops Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ill. (AP) -- It's not every day you see a message from  
God. Especially on a billboard. 
</P>
<P>
	But there it is, overlooking a weedy lot and the parking lots of  
a strip mall on the north end of town: ``Come on over, and bring 
the kids. -- God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Standing underneath the sign is Bob Lord, general manager of  
Adams Outdoor Advertising, one of dozens of billboard companies 
that are posting divine messages as sly, attention-grabbing and 
often funny one-liners. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a powerful message. When have you seen anything like  
this?'' Lord asks. 
</P>
<P>
	A lot of people are getting the message. The billboards are now  
in 200 cities in 40 states, on more than $13 million worth of 
donated billboard space, said Sheila Hays, spokeswoman for the 
Outdoor Advertising Association of America. 
</P>
<P>
	Andy Smith, who owns the Fort Lauderdale, Fla., advertising firm  
that designed the campaign, said it began last year when a 
well-known Florida man -- who wants to remain anonymous -- walked 
into Smith's office with an idea. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a religious person, and he thought if people started  
thinking about God, maybe things would get better around the 
world,'' Smith said. ``He wanted to reach those people who had gone 
to church before but stopped, or who had gone to synagogue before 
but stopped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Out were stern reminders to pray and go to church. In were lines  
like, ``What part of 'Thou shalt not ...' didn't you understand? -- 
God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Or, ``Let's meet at my house Sunday before the game. -- God.''  
And ``I can think of 10 things that ARE carved in stone. -- God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the first anonymously sponsored billboards popped up  
around Fort Lauderdale, the Outdoor Advertising Association of 
America adopted the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``It certainly raises the idea of God in people's minds in a way  
and a place when you certainly wouldn't expect it,'' said the Rev. 
Edward Roberts, director of evangelization for the Catholic Diocese 
of Peoria. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is catching people, in a sense, off guard, and giving them  
pause to reflect,'' Roberts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shirley Happs, a clerk in The Church Mouse Thrift Shop, around  
the corner from one billboard in downtown Peoria, thinks the signs 
are a little unusual for religious advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just don't think He needs advertisement. ... This is just a  
little bold,'' Happs said. ``I will say this much. It attracts your 
attention right away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The billboard messages are drawing a positive reaction from the  
public, in part because they are nondenominational, Lord said. 
</P>
<P>
	``People take from it what they will,'' he said. ``They see it  
and the rest is up to them. ... But they are certainly seeing it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
