<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UN Panel Tries To Save Forests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Forests have virtually disappeared in 25  
countries and will continue to vanish unless governments change 
their policies now, an international commission warned as it 
proposed new initiatives to save the world's trees. 
</P>
<P>
	Virtually the only economic value officially assigned to forests  
today is timber. But the report Monday from the World Commission on 
Forests and Sustainable Development suggests the world can satisfy 
its material needs from forests without jeopardizing their 
ecological benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	The report recommends the creation of a Forest Capital Index,  
which would measure the real value of forests in terms other than 
timber, such as the role they play in water management and 
stabilizing the climate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Making an index is not the same as being able to charge people  
for services,'' said the commission's co-chairman, Ola Ullsten, the 
former Swedish prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, the index can be the basis for a financial  
mechanism -- such as credits for greenhouse gas emissions -- to 
compensate developing countries for lost income from cutting down 
forests, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission also proposed a host of community-based  
initiatives to monitor forests, develop policies to protect them 
and encourage corporations and countries to conserve them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fixing the forest crisis is basically a matter of politics,''  
Ullsten said. ``It's about governments assuming their mandate to 
protect their national resources -- including forests -- for the 
long-term benefit of their citizens.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
