<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Accepts Inheritance Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to decide  
whether people can avoid using inherited money to pay overdue 
federal taxes by disclaiming their right to the inheritance. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said it will hear an Arkansas man's argument that the  
federal government could not seize the money from his mother's 
estate because he had given up his right to collect it. 
</P>
<P>
	Irma Drye died without a will in 1994 in Pulaski County, Ark. At  
the time, her son, Rohn F. Drye Jr., owed the federal government 
about $325,000 in overdue taxes following the bankruptcy of his 
engineering firm. 
</P>
<P>
	In March 1995, Drye filed legal papers disclaiming his right to  
his mother's estate, which was worth $236,000 including a $75,000 
home. 
</P>
<P>
	A state probate court ruled that under Arkansas law, Drye's  
disclaimer meant he had no interest in Mrs. Drye's estate. The 
court ordered the estate given to his daughter, Theresa K. Drye, 
who put the money in a family trust with Rohn Drye, his wife and 
daughter named as beneficiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internal Revenue Service then filed a lien against the trust  
and collected $134,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The trust sued the government, saying that because Drye  
disclaimed his inheritance, he never had an interest in the estate 
to which the government could attach a lien. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge ruled for the government, as did the 8th U.S.  
Circuit Court of Appeals. The appeals court said Drye's right to 
inherit his mother's estate should be considered property to which 
the federal lien could be attached. Drye's disclaimer did not void 
the lien, the court said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal granted review today, Drye's lawyer said the 8th  
Circuit court ruling ``effectively strips the states of their 
traditional power to define property rights.'' About 35 other 
states have similar laws, the lawyers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department lawyers said people cannot avoid paying  
federal taxes through ``legal fictions'' in state law that make a 
disclaimer of an inheritance retroactive, with the intended effect 
that the person never inherited the money at all. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Drye vs. U.S., 98-1101.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990419.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 22:52:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nice Guy Robinson Finishes Last </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Larry Robinson's pleasant demeanor  
helped cost him his job as coach of the Los Angeles Kings. 
</P>
<P>
	The team said Monday it was not renewing Robinson's contract,  
which expired after four seasons. He had a 122-161-45 record, and 
the Kings missed the playoffs three of the last four years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our performance this year was less than expected,'' general  
manager Dave Taylor said. ``We lacked consistency, and at times we 
lacked the work ethic. That's not acceptable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also out of jobs are assistants Don Edwards, Rick Green and Jay  
Leach. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, who won six Stanley Cups during a Hall of Fame playing  
career with Montreal, came to the Kings after being an assistant 
with New Jersey when the Devils won the Stanley Cup in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson was well liked by his players, and left wing Luc  
Robitaille suggested that niceness might have been his undoing. 
</P>
<P>
	``When a guy's not producing, he always gave them an extra  
chance and unfortunately, guys didn't realize how lucky they 
were,'' Robitaille said. ``I don't know that we need a new coach, 
but we need a new attitude from everybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The soft-spoken Robinson acknowledged he probably should have  
been tougher on the players, but he said that's not his nature. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this day and age, I guess you've got to do a lot of  
screaming and yelling, and that in itself is a lot of wear and 
tear,'' he said. ``I don't feel my demeanor works well with problem 
super athletes. I'm a good teacher and I work well with young 
kids.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, 47, never pulled punches, whether he was talking to  
team management, his players or the media. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't guard my words, I speak from the heart,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	So when he declined to sign a three-year contract extension  
offered last September, musing out loud that he wasn't sure he 
wanted to continue coaching, Taylor interpreted it negatively. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was difficult to understand why he didn't accept the  
extension,'' Taylor said. ``He was not sure of himself and that has 
given the wrong image. 
</P>
<P>
	``The players look to the coach for leadership. For him to have  
any hesitation is the wrong message back to the players. There was 
a lot of speculation to Larry's future all year and that was a 
distraction to the club.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although he was troubled by the mounting losses and numerous  
injuries, Robinson later decided he wanted to stay with the Kings. 
He asked Taylor about his job status before Sunday's 3-2 loss to 
St. Louis, and was told he would not be back. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not what I envisioned,'' Robinson said. ``I still feel  
there was a lot to be done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings had a 32-45-5 record this season, a year after they  
finished second in the Pacific Division, made the playoffs and 
Robinson was runner-up for NHL coach of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	But this season, the team lost 25 games by one goal, had one of  
the league's worst power plays and lost 335 man-games to injuries 
or illness. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we're as talented as we were made out to be,''  
Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson was known for exhibiting patience during trying times --  
including the loss of goalies Stephane Fiset and Jamie Storr to 
groin injuries in the early weeks of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Several players who had career years last season failed to  
repeat those performances, including Jozef Stumpel, who led the 
team in points last season with 79, but had just 34 this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``How do you instill heart, drive and intestinal fortitude in  
people who don't have it or don't want to have it?'' Robinson 
asked. ``We had more talkers than leaders and not enough doers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen a place where the players aren't held  
accountable for their lackluster play. With the way some of these 
guys played, they would've been run out of Montreal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor said the Kings have not yet begun a search for Robinson's  
replacement, and said there is no timetable for hiring someone. 
</P>
<P>
	There could be more changes in store.  
</P>
<P>
	Taylor planned to meet today with individual players to discuss  
their performances. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be some players that will not be back next year,''  
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
