<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pa. Halts Sales of Grain Alcohol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Hoping to reduce binge drinking on  
college campuses, the state has banned liquor stores from selling 
grain alcohol to the general public. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite a concerted effort by Pennsylvania colleges and  
universities to deal with alcohol problems in their communities, we 
have found that a disproportionate number of grain alcohol sales 
are still occurring in college areas,'' John E. Jones III, the 
state's Liquor Control Board chairman, said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain alcohol -- a potent form of alcohol also called ethanol --  
will continue to be sold to hospitals and other businesses that 
need permits to buy it. 
</P>
<P>
	The state's liquor board, which oversees all of Pennsylvania's  
648 liquor stores -- the only places that sell hard liquor by the 
bottle -- also licenses beer distributors, taverns and restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	Orders went out over the weekend to the state's Wine &AMP; Spirits  
Shoppes to stop sales to the general public -- at least partly in 
commemoration of April as Alcohol Awareness Month. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's better to walk the walk than simply talk the talk,'' said  
Jones, who was flanked by board members and legislators at a 
Capitol news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain alcohol was sold along with other types of liquor at state  
stores until 1990, when the board ordered it removed from the 
shelves and made it available to customers only upon request. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales plummeted from more than 121,000 bottles in fiscal 1990 to  
fewer than 65,000 the next year. Sales continued to decline until 
last year, when the number increased by 5 percent to nearly 54,000 
bottles. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said grain-alcohol sales are highest at stores closest to  
college and university campuses, although he acknowledged officials 
have only anecdotal evidence about the extent of binge drinking. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain alcohol also is used to clean machine parts and as a  
preservative. ``It's high octane, super-strength,'' said Dr. Robert 
S. Muscalus, the state physician general. 
</P>
<P>
	Muscalus said the action will both discourage people from using  
grain alcohol as a quick and comparatively inexpensive way to get 
drunk and may protect those who unwittingly consume it in spiked 
punch. 
</P>
<P>
	College students and anyone else who wants to buy grain alcohol  
can still buy it in neighboring states, but they could be fined $25 
per bottle if they are caught transporting it back into 
Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey, Delaware, Maryland and West Virginia all allow sales  
of grain alcohol, while Ohio sells it only by special permit, and 
New York has banned sales altogether, board officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
