<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hockey Is a Big Hit in Music City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Charlie Tidwell promised he ``wouldn't  
be caught dead'' at a Nashville Predators game. 
</P>
<P>
	Tidwell's game was golf.  
</P>
<P>
	He didn't know anything about hockey and didn't want to learn.  
The NHL's newest franchise couldn't entice him with a splashy ad 
campaign featuring country music's biggest stars. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, Tidwell had two season tickets, but those were business  
purchases and he planned to give them all away. Then his son-in-law 
convinced him to go to a game. Tidwell was hooked. 
</P>
<P>
	He bought two more season tickets in December -- for himself and  
his wife. They also purchased matching Predators sweaters. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just full of action,'' Tidwell said. ``It's just  
completely fun. ... We're upgrading our seats for next year if we 
can. That's after me saying I wouldn't be caught dead down here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Move over NASCAR. Watch out college basketball and football.  
Music City is becoming a hockey town. 
</P>
<P>
	The Predators concluded their inaugural season as the NHL's  
attendance leader in markets under 2 million people, despite a 
28-47-7 record. They averaged 16,145 a game, and 10 of their 17 
sellouts came after January, when their playoff hopes had dimmed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fan support in the stands and Nashville in general has  
been fantastic,'' general manager David Poile said. ``The Nashville 
Arena sort of become the place to be in Nashville. It's been really 
a rewarding experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the NHL granted Nashville a franchise in 1997, the worry  
was the city was ``too Southern'' to embrace such a Northern game. 
The team quickly changed that sentiment with a flashy ad campaign 
and sabre-tooth tiger logo that became popular with fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Once they got people in the door, Predators officials promised  
them they would like what they saw. Each game was a party where 
fans could rub elbows with country stars like Vince Gill and Reba 
McEntire, participate in contests and a listen to a live band. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans who didn't know a two-line pass from a two-step got help  
from the Predators, who held ``Hockey 101'' and ``Predators 
University'' clinics to teach the fans the game. The public address 
announcer explained calls during the games, sometimes in 
excruciatingly basic terms. 
</P>
<P>
	The explanations were so simple some of the Predators players  
thought fans might be offended. Instead, fans appreciated the 
helping hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Captain Tom Fitzgerald has been amazed at how knowledgeable the  
fans have become in a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are their team. It's been very overwhelming,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Predators got their foot in the door with fans by using  
country music stars in its ``Got Tickets?'' campaign, which 
featured celebrities like Garth Brooks sporting a blacked-out tooth 
and asking fans, ``Got tickets?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tradeoff has been that many country music stars are hooked  
on hockey, giving the Predators a celebrity cachet usually found in 
Los Angeles or New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Gill has season tickets near the ice. McEntire has her own  
suite. Barbara Mandrell is a regular on the arena's Celebrity Cam 
shots on the Jumbotron along with singers like Mindy McCready and 
Deana Carter. 
</P>
<P>
	McEntire, whose son plays in a children's hockey league, hadn't  
seen an NHL game before the Predators' debut. Now she hates to miss 
a game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I go to as many games as my schedule will allow, which about  
half the games this year. I will attend as many game as possible 
next year and can't wait for the new season,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Predators' biggest challenge will be avoiding a sophomore  
slump as the franchise builds toward the playoffs through draft 
picks rather than aging veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	The team is confident Nashville fans will stay with the team  
through its growing pains. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've been bitten,'' Fitzgerald said. ``They've got the bug,  
and it's been great. I hope I'm around a lot of years to see it 
keep growing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
