</P>
<P>
	Italian, German Telecoms To Merge  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Telecom Italia SpA and Germany's Deutsche Telekom  
AG are expected to announce tomorrow that they are merging in a 
mega-deal that would create a new global competitor to U.S. giants 
such as AT&AMP;T. A Telecom Italia-Deutsche Telekom combination would 
dwarf its competitors in Europe. Also, a German business newspaper 
said Deutsche Telekom is negotiating a takeover of U.S. 
telecommunications company Sprint Corp. Telecom Italia's stock was 
unchanged at 106 1/8. Deutsche Telekom was down 3/4 at 39 15/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Best Buy Won't Sell iMac Computers  
</P>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- Best Buy Co. Inc. will not sell the  
new iMac computer, protesting Apple Computer's requirement that the 
retail chain carry all five fruity colors. A Best Buy spokeswoman 
said all the colors would cause inventory problems. The move leaves 
CompUSA as the only national retail chain offering the iMac. 

</P>
<P>
	US Airways Tops Airline Survey  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- US Airways placed first in a survey of U.S.  
airline quality released today, one year after it finished dead 
last. The research was headed by two university professors, who 
based the findings on on-time performance, denied boardings, 
mishandled luggage and passenger complaints. Southwest Airlines, 
which was first in 1997, dropped to fifth. Continental was second, 
with American third. 

</P>
<P>
	Big Banks Report Solid Profits  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Citigroup Inc., BankAmerica Corp. and the Bank  
of New York Co. all reported strong first-quarter profits today, as 
U.S. consumers ran up their credit card bills and businesses 
borrowed to expand their reach. Citigroup posted net income of 
$2.36 billion, up 9 percent from the first-quarter last year. 
BankAmerica reported net income of $1.91 billion, a 44 percent 
increase over the first quarter last year. Bank of New York posted 
first quarter earnings of $316 million, a 12-percent rise from last 
year. 

</P>
<P>
	FDA Approves New Breast Cancer Test  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A device that uses electricity to map possible  
breast lumps may reduce the number of women who get unnecessary 
biopsies because their mammograms are unclear, the government said 
today. The Food and Drug Administration approved TransScan Medical 
Inc.'s T-Scan 2000 as an extra tool for radiologists to use in 
determining whether women with ambiguous mammogram results need an 
immediate biopsy to check for cancer. Some 800,000 biopsies are 
done every year, from which 180,000 women are diagnosed with breast 
cancer. So scientists have hunted for ways to reduce unnecessary 
biopsies without missing women who have cancer. 

</P>
<P>
	Columbia Offers $6.6B for Gas Firm  
</P>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Columbia Energy Group has offered $6.68  
billion in cash and stock for Consolidated Natural Gas Co., topping 
the $5.5 billion that Dominion Resources Inc. offered for CNG under 
a deal approved two months ago. Columbia Energy had 1998 revenues 
of nearly $6.6 billion. Its natural gas business includes 
exploration and production, transmission, storage and distribution, 
as well as propane sales and electric power generation. CNG 
supplies natural gas to 1.9 million customers in Ohio, 
Pennsylvania, Virginia and West Virginia. 

</P>
<P>
	Lilly Profit Up, Prozac Sales Fall  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Eli Lilly and Co.'s first quarter profit  
excluding one-time items rose 12 percent despite a 4 percent 
decline in sales of its best-selling drug, the antidepressant 
Prozac. Lilly shares tumbled on disappointment over the decline in 
Prozac sales, down 9 1/16 to 73 1/4. Lilly earned $625.7 million in 
the quarter ending March 31, compared with $521.1 million in the 
same period a year ago. 

</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom To Buy CAI Wireless  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- MCI Worldcom, the nation's No. 2 provider of  
long-distance calling service, is buying CAI Wireless Systems for 
about $414 million. MCI WorldCom has been the only major telephone 
company without a stake in wireless communication. CAI Wireless has 
been seeking a partner since its emerged from bankruptcy protection 
in October 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Five To Compete in Domain Name Game  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Five companies will be chosen this week to  
compete with Network Solutions Inc. in the business of registering 
Internet addresses. Network Solutions has had an exclusive contract 
with the federal government for registering World Wide Web 
addresses, such as those ending in with .com, .net and .org, since 
1993. But the government moved to end that monopoly last year by 
creating a nonprofit group to deal with administration of the 
Internet. The government must still reach a deal with Network 
Solutions on how to distribute its database. 

</P>
<P>
	EU To Ease Banana Import Policies  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The European Union promised to change its banana  
import policies after the World Trade Organization approved tough 
U.S. sanctions against European products. The United States claims 
the EU discriminates unfairly against bananas imported from U.S. 
multinational companies in Latin America and favors those from 
former European colonies in the Caribbean and Africa. Washington 
had announced a package of sanctions worth $191.4 million a year 
imposing tariffs of up to 100 percent on a list of products. 
Products affected include French handbags, German coffee-makers, 
bed linens, cardboard packing material and felt paper. After a WTO 
expert panel approved the sanctions, EU trade ambassador Roderick 
Abbott said the EU would change its licenses and quotas to comply 
with WTO rules. It may take until next year to put the changes 
through. 

</P>
<P>
	Toyota, GM To Make Fuel-Cell Cars  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Toyota Motor Corp. and General Motors Corp. have  
reached a five-year agreement to jointly develop cars and trucks 
that can run off fuel cells and other environmentally friendly 
alternative-fuel technology. Fuel cells produce electricity using a 
chemical reaction between hydrogen and oxygen and produce little or 
no emissions. GM, the No. 2 automaker, was the first to mass-market 
an electric car, which has failed to catch on. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: International trade  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Jobless claims  

</P>
