<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Calls for Halt to Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- In their first talks since the onset of the NATO  
airstrikes on Yugoslavia, Russian President Boris Yeltsin conferred 
today with President Clinton. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan 
scheduled a peace mission to Moscow. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian leader urged Clinton to call off the NATO airstrikes  
that began March 24, the Kremlin press service said. Russia has 
staunchly opposed the NATO airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Deeply divided over the Kosovo crisis, NATO and Russia cracked  
open the door to an Annan initiative last week, in a sign that both 
sides view the secretary-general as a possible mediator. 
</P>
<P>
	Annan's mission comes even though Yugoslavia rejected the key  
element of his Kosovo peace initiative, saying an international 
military force in Yugoslavia was unacceptable. 
</P>
<P>
	In their phone conversation Monday, Clinton and Yeltsin also  
discussed the plight of the ethnic Albanian refugees fleeing 
Kosovo, the Interfax news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, a White House official said the discussion  
largely centered on matters the two leaders agree on, including the 
need for Serb forces to withdraw from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin has ruled out Russian military intervention in  
Yugoslavia, and has sought to help bring about a diplomatic 
settlement. However, Russia's influence with Yugoslavia is limited, 
and NATO has ignored Moscow's calls to stop the daily bombing 
raids. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite sharp disagreements on the strikes, Russia and the  
United States have pledged to work together to try to settle the 
conflict. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright agreed in meetings 
last week with Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov that there must 
be an end to repression, a pullout of Serb troops and police from 
Kosovo, a return of displaced refugees to their homes and access 
for humanitarian organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, senior Russian officials claimed that NATO,  
frustrated by the lack of success of its airstrikes, was preparing 
for an invasion on the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivanov said Monday the alliance was denying plans for sending  
ground troops into combat only to assuage public opinion in NATO 
member countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivanov warned of dire consequences, ``not only for Europe but  
for the world as a whole,'' should ground troops be deployed. He 
stressed that any such offensive will only hurt chances for a peace 
settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Kosovo problem has no military solution,'' Ivanov said.  
``The war must be stopped today. Every day that passes makes the 
problem more difficult to solve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO says it has no intention of launching ground combat in  
Yugoslavia, though it would deploy troops to implement a peace 
settlement. Russia contends NATO ground forces should not go into 
Yugoslavia at all, unless they are invited in by the Yugoslav 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's protests have been largely symbolic. The country's  
military and its economy are both in shambles, leaving it with few 
resources. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin said Monday that Russia had decided not to send any  
additional ships into the Adriatic. Russia has sent only one ship 
into the Adriatic to monitor NATO warships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
