<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Rates Rise / T-Bills  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on short-term Treasury  
securities rose in Monday's auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department sold $7.52 billion in three-month bills  
at a discount rate of 4.230 percent, up from 4.190 percent last 
week. An additional $7.51 billion was sold in six-month bills at a 
rate of 4.370 percent, up from 4.320 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-month rate was the highest since April 5, when the  
bills sold for 4.265 percent. The six-month rate was the highest 
since March 22, when the rate was 4.420. 
</P>
<P>
	The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors  
-- 4.346 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling 
for $9,893.10 and 4.543 percent for a six-month bill selling for 
$9,779.10. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the  
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index 
for making changes in adjustable-rate mortgages, rose to 4.67 
percent last week from 4.66 percent the previous week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
