<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Banks Report Solid Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Citigroup Inc., BankAmerica Corp. and the Bank  
of New York Co. all reported strong first-quarter profits Monday, 
as U.S. consumers ran up their credit card bills and businesses 
borrowed to expand their reach. 
</P>
<P>
	The banking industry's impressive results reflect an economy  
with strong consumer confidence, a turbocharged stock market, low 
unemployment and benign inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	``This morning's reports were nothing short of fantastic,'' said  
Michael Ancell, an analyst with Edward Jones. ``The market rebound 
we've seen over the last quarter or two has given a huge boost to 
the banks' underwriting and trading revenues, and that's resulted 
in most companies beating earnings estimates, and it's certainly 
lit fire to their stock prices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bank stocks rallied in the morning, but were dragged down with  
the market and ended the day mixed. Investors had bid up the prices 
of several top banks on the hunch that Monday's solid results will 
be repeated Tuesday when Chase Manhattan Bank, Bank One, Wells 
Fargo and Mellon Bank report their profits for the first three 
months of the year. 

</P>
<P>
	 *Citigroup    	
</P>
<P>
	The banking and insurance behemoth posted net income of $2.36  
billion, or $1.01 a share, up 9 percent from the first-quarter last 
year, when Citigroup earned $2.16 billion or 90 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Citigroup's profits from operations, which is widely watched by  
Wall Street, totaled $2.42 billion, or $1.04 a share, handily 
beating analysts' average estimate of 87 cents a share, according 
to First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based financial services company, which was formed  
last year by the merger of Citibank and Travelers Group, has cut 
more than 4,100 jobs to reduce expenses. Citigroup said it has 
already realized $900 million of its targeted $2 billion in annual 
savings. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's global consumer business, which includes its North  
American banking and lending operations, grew 33 percent to $1.05 
billion in the quarter. Business was strong across the board, but 
especially in North American credit cards, where earnings jumped 75 
percent to $268 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Citigroup has bought several credit card businesses, including  
its recent acquisition of Mellon Bank's card unit. 
</P>
<P>
	``That, combined with higher prices and fees has really helped  
their card business take off,'' Ancell explained. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, Citigroup announced it was selling its $930 million  
automobile finance business to Dime Bankcorp Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	During the first quarter, Citigroup's electronic banking was one  
of the few weak spots. The loss at its e-Citi unit widened 20 
percent to $36 million as the company spent heavily to develop the 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Results for the global corporate and investment bank operations  
rebounded sharply in the first quarter, rising 31 percent to $1.36 
billion over the comparable quarter in 1998 and more than doubling 
from the fourth quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The gain was most notable at the Salomon Smith Barney brokerage  
and investment banking unit, which posted record earnings on total 
revenues of $3.3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The Travelers Life &AMP; Annuity business saw a 20 percent increase  
in income to $147 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Reacting to the bottom line numbers, investors sent Citigroup's  
stock up as high as $76.25, but the shares ended the day off $1 at 
$70.62 1/2 on the New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
	 *BankAmerica    	
</P>
<P>
	BankAmerica, based in Charlotte, N.C., reported net income of  
$1.91 billion, or $1.08 a share, a 44 percent increase over the 
first quarter last year, when the bank earned $1.33 billion, or 75 
cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	BankAmerica's performance beat analysts' estimate of $1.03 a  
share, according to First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	``BankAmerica had a good quarter, but not as good as the New  
York banks because their investment banking business was a bit 
sluggish,'' Ancell said. 
</P>
<P>
	BankAmerica's investment banking and securities revenue was hurt  
by an employee exodus at Montgomery Securities, and by the sale of 
its Robertson Stephens division last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank's net interest income of $4.65 billion was virtually  
unchanged from a year ago, as loan and deposit growth offset 
declines in loan sales and interest rate spreads. 
</P>
<P>
	Average managed loans grew 11 percent to $385 billion,  
reflecting increases in both consumer and business loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Noninterest expenses fell by 5 percent to $4.45 billion,  
illustrating the effect of the job cuts and other cost reductions 
from the merger of BankAmerica and NationsBank. 
</P>
<P>
	BankAmerica's stock closed down $1.25 at $71.75 on the NYSE.  

</P>
<P>
	 *Bank of New York    	
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of New York Co. posted first quarter earnings of $316  
million, or 41 cents a share, matching Wall Street's estimate. 
Profits were up 12 percent from the first quarter last year, when 
the bank earned $284 million or 36 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Net interest income rose almost 8 percent to $436 million in the  
first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Total noninterest income reached $625 million, up 5 percent from  
the year-ago period, driven by strong fees and a gain on 
securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Expenses were virtually flat at $509 million.  
</P>
<P>
	With few surprises in the numbers, investors reacted mildly,  
pushing the Bank of New York's stock up 12 1/2 cents to $37.68 3/4 on the 
Big Board. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
