<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Team Begins Searching for Capsule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- An underwater salvage team set off  
today in search of Mercury astronaut Gus Grissom's space capsule, 
entombed in the Atlantic for 38 years. 
</P>
<P>
	A 180-foot ship, the Needham Tide, headed for the 3-mile-deep  
waters 300 miles southeast of Cape Canaveral. The ship was a day 
late raising anchor; the crew needed time to get a new switch for a 
hydraulic power unit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anxious to get going,'' said Curt Newport, the expedition  
leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Newport estimated it would take at least one day to reach the  
area where he believes Grissom's Liberty Bell 7 lies on the ocean 
floor. His calculations are based on 14 years of poring over NASA 
charts and photographs. 
</P>
<P>
	The capsule splashed down July 21, 1961, following Grissom's  
15-minute suborbital flight, which made him only the second 
American in space. The hatch blew open too soon, and the capsule 
became waterlogged and was too heavy to be lifted by helicopter. 
The rescue line was cut, and the capsule sank. 
</P>
<P>
	Grissom, who nearly drowned, insisted until his death in the  
1967 Apollo launch pad fire that he did nothing wrong. Many have 
speculated that he may have bumped something or panicked and blown 
the hatch. 
</P>
<P>
	If the capsule and hatch can be found, the mystery might be  
solved. The hatch will be especially difficult to find; Newport 
said it could be up to a mile from the capsule. 
</P>
<P>
	Newport and his team will use sonar to survey a 24-square-mile  
area. They will be probing 3,000 feet deeper than the Titanic 
wreckage site in the North Atlantic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990419.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 12:05:19 </DATE_TIME>
