<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Vehicles Rigged To Steal Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- You didn't want to get caught waiting behind  
Alberto Perez when he got the itch to fill up his rickety van at 
the gas station. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say Perez's vehicle held 600 gallons -- allowing him  
to make regular trips to neighbors' houses to sell the fuel for as 
little as 70 cents a gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials in Florida say vans and trucks like Perez's -- shabbily  
rigged to hold as much as 1,000 gallons -- are increasingly being 
used to steal and resell gas across Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Typically, gas peddlers use stolen credit cards to fill up the  
rigged vehicle at a service station, often returning several times 
to the same station. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, when they deliver the gas to customers, usually at their  
homes or at a secret meeting place, the sellers use a hose with a 
meter that tells them how many gallons the customer bought. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to see a lot more of it,'' said Tony Pilla of the  
state Department of Transportation's law enforcement division, who 
noted that recently increasing fuel prices will boost demand for 
black-market gas. 
</P>
<P>
	Gas prices have soared roughly 25 percent over the past six  
weeks. The authoritative Lundberg Survey showed the average price 
was nearly $1.23 a gallon last week. Three weeks ago, it was $1.09, 
and in late February a stunningly low 99.8 cents. 
</P>
<P>
	Since it's not illegal to sell gasoline, those caught with large  
quantities of fuel have been charged with illegally transporting 
hazardous materials. Since late 1997, 20 people, including Perez, 
have faced such charges in Miami-Dade and Broward counties. 
</P>
<P>
	But with overhead cheap, vendors can simply pay their fines,  
which range from $500 to $3,000, and return to work, authorities 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	Advertising is also easy and inexpensive, Pilla said. The word  
spreads to relatives and friends who want in on inexpensive gas. 
</P>
<P>
	And legitimate gas sellers aren't the only ones hurt by the  
scam. Some say the rigged vehicles amount to rolling bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	A van like Perez's could have pulverized with the force of six  
sticks of dynamite -- damaging as much as an entire neighborhood 
block, Pilla said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to take out a few houses, of course,'' he said.  
``They're parking them in residential areas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to combat the problem, authorities have warned gas  
stations to be alert to people filling up with large quantities. 
And Pilla said he is gathering material for legislation that would 
result in stiffer penalties for violators in Florida. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
