<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Ford's Brazilian subsidiary denied  
reports Monday it would suspend work on a $1 billion plant after 
the governor of a southern state retracted millions of dollars in 
incentives. 
</P>
<P>
	Corporate affairs director Celio Batalha brushed aside the  
reports, made by the O Globo news agency, explaining the company 
was still negotiating ``an end to the impasse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rio Grande do Sul state's previous government had enticed Ford  
and General Motors to build plants in the state with offers of $468 
million in financial aid and infrastructure projects. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Rio Grande do Sul state government said last month it  
would not honor the commitments, saying it needed the money for 
other spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford has already received $22.8 million of a total $249.2  
million. GM has already received $188.3 million of a total of 
$219.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	According to O Globo, Rio Grande do Sul's decision had also  
caused General Motors to delay the scheduled year-end opening of 
its new plant in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors and Rio Grande do Sul officials were not  
immediately available for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Federal agents have arrested a former state  
police commander and a soldier suspected of leading a drug 
distribution ring in southern Mexico, a newspaper reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Romeo Espinoza Pimentel, a former state judicial police  
commander in Chiapas state, and Moises Montejo Lopez were arrested 
Sunday in the state capital, Tuxtla Gutierrez, the Mexico City 
daily Reforma reported. Montejo's rank was not given. 
</P>
<P>
	The two are suspected of running a drug ring that distributed  
cocaine and marijuana in the city, according to the federal 
attorney general's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Three men and two women suspected of being part of the band also  
were arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators searched five homes in the city and discovered  
nearly 160 pounds of marijuana and 1.76 ounces of cocaine. They 
also found pistols, ammunition, military uniforms and T-shirts with 
the federal judicial police logo. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- About 40 members of the  
Lutheran church in El Salvador called on NATO to stop bombing 
Yugoslavia in a prayer for peace Monday outside the U.S. Embassy. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters, including several Americans, carried signs and  
shouted slogans denouncing the bombing campaign, which entered its 
26th day Monday. Police watched over the demonstration but took no 
action. 
</P>
<P>
	``May God enlighten the mind of NATO. In the name of God we ask  
that they cease these bombings against the people of Yugoslavia,'' 
the Rev. Roberto Pineda shouted. 

</P>
</TEXT>
