<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 15:35:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How FCC Handles Radio Pirates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	How the Federal Communications Commission tracks down radio  
pirates: 
</P>
<P>
	It receives complaints from the public, licensed broadcasters or  
other pirates. Or FCC engineers and other experts may find a pirate 
by just listening to the radio. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's airwaves police, in offices across the country, can  
simply tune to the frequency to verify that a signal is there, then 
check the FCC's database to make sure no licensed station is 
permitted to operate on that frequency. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC also can use mobile, direction-finding vehicles to  
pinpoint the location, a process that can take 15 minutes to an 
hour depending on traffic. All 25 of the FCC's nationwide offices 
have such vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of the easiest things to do,'' said the FCC's point  
man on the matter, Richard Lee. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	How the FCC notifies the pirate:  
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's airwaves police go to the station and ask to do an  
inspection. In many instances, inspections are allowed. Then 
officials explain that the station is in violation of FCC rules 
because it lacks the required license. The agency also will send a 
written notice requesting that the station voluntarily shut down. 
</P>
<P>
	If the station refuses to close, the FCC can go to court to  
obtain an injunction to make the station stop broadcasting or to 
obtain a warrant to seize equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency also can seek to impose penalties for operating  
unlicensed radio stations, including fines and prison terms of up 
to one year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990419.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 19:32:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TV Networks Work On Satellite Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Customers who use big ``backyard'' satellite  
dishes and aren't entitled to receive CBS, NBC, ABC and Fox 
programs by satellite will keep getting them that way for a while, 
a top broadcast industry executive said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 1.3 million customers were supposed to be cut off  
from those network signals on April 30, but they now will be able 
to continue receiving them, National Association of Broadcasters 
lobbyist Jim May said at the organization's annual convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, some viewers -- those living closest to their local TV  
stations as determined by a technical test involving the stations' 
coverage areas -- will lose their current satellite signals for CBS, 
Fox, ABC and NBC programs on June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers living on the edges of the stations' coverage areas  
will lose that network programming on Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law lets satellite companies provide customers with  
``distant'' network signals -- which come from other broadcast areas 
-- only if those customers cannot receive their local stations using 
rooftop antennas. 
</P>
<P>
	May said the four major networks worked out the agreement, which  
is subject to approval by a federal court in Miami, with several 
companies that provide network programming to satellite TV 
customers with big backyard dishes. He didn't have a list of the 
companies involved, but said the agreement covers all big dish 
customers who faced being cutoff from network signals on April 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
