<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo's Stock Index Falls / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's main stock index fell Monday as concerns  
about the earnings of high-technology companies weighed down the 
market. The U.S. dollar was lower against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 177.37 points,  
or 1.05 percent, to close the day at 16,674.21. On Friday, the 
index gained 124.50 points, or 0.74 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 118.18 yen, down 0.04 yen from late Friday in  
Tokyo but above its late New York level of 118.02 yen on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the poor performance Friday in America's  
Nasdaq index, which includes many high-technology shares, triggered 
selling of Japanese hi-tech issues on Monday. The Nasdaq closed 
down 4.20 percent on the week Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese precision machinery and electronic share prices have  
languished since U.S.-based companies Compaq and Intel warned last 
week that their earnings may not be as strong as expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's dip from its levels late last week has exacerbated  
those worries, as a weak U.S. currency makes Japanese exporters' 
products more expensive overseas and reduces the value of 
repatriated earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sentiment is good, but the market can't advance as a whole  
because technology stocks figure prominently in the Nikkei 
average,'' said Masatoshi Sato, manager of the investment 
information department at Kankaku Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section was down 10.34 points, or 0.77 percent, to 
1,332.69. The TOPIX rose 5.10 points, or 0.38 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average gained  
another 31.17 points to finish at 10,493.89, setting its fifth 
consecutive record close. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, dollar-supportive comments by Japanese  
monetary authorities pushed the dollar higher than its levels in 
New York on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's influential Vice Finance Minister for International  
Affairs Eisuke Sakakibara warned against excessive yen 
strengthening and said that Japanese monetary authorities would 
take action in such an event. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was sold against the yen mainly  
due to the Kosovo conflict, which shows no signs of ending, they 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was traded at 126.44 yen, up from 126.20 yen late  
Friday in Tokyo. Against the dollar, the euro rose to 1.0690 from 
an all-time low of dlrs 1.0627 late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 211 10-year Japanese government  
bond dropped to 1.585 percent from Friday's close of 1.605 percent, 
driving its price up to 101.88 yen from 101.70 yen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
