<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Off 138.43; Dow Off 53.36 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors dumped technology shares Monday,  
pummeling the Nasdaq Stock Market with its second-biggest point 
drop ever. The wave of selling on record volume more than wiped out 
a 270-point gain in the Dow industrials, snapping a five-day string 
of record highs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it was the decimation of everything tech, everything  
Internet, everything healthcare,'' said Larry Wachtel, a market 
analyst at Prudential Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The technology heavy Nasdaq composite index plunged 138.43, or  
by 5.6 percent, to 2,345.61. The only time the index had a bigger 
one-day point drop was on Aug. 31, 1998, when it slid 140.43 
points, or 8.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average, at one point in the afternoon  
up 271.85 points, squandered those gains and closed down 53.36 at 
10,440.53. 
</P>
<P>
	For investors, it was a $292 billion hit to their portfolios.  
That was the drop Monday in Wilshire Associates Equity Index, which 
measures the market value of all the stocks on the New York Stock 
Exchange, American Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow had easily cruised through the 10,500, 10,600 and 10,700  
levels by early afternoon Monday. But as investors saw the Nasdaq 
crumble under the weight of huge losses in technology shares, they 
began to sell blue chips as well, cashing in on a week of gains. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the Nasdaq undermined everything else,'' said Wachtel.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you owned a big winner this year, you got whacked today,''  
Wachtel said. ``They just got around to (selling) the extraordinary 
winners of 1999. It had the ring of inevitability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 composite fell 29.52 to 1,289.48.  
</P>
<P>
	Consolidated volume of NYSE-listed stocks, which includes  
trading on regional exchanges, was a record 1.47 billion shares. 
The previous high of 1.42 billion was set Sept. 1, 1998. Volume on 
the Nasdaq Stock Market was 1.20 billion shares, ranking tenth. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the rout in blue-chips, advancing issues had a strong  
2-to-1 lead on decliners on the NYSE, helped by some strong 
earnings reports and merger news. 
</P>
<P>
	That was an encouraging sign to A.C. Moore, chief investment  
strategist for Dunvegan Associates in Santa Barbara, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're probably not on an edge of a precipice just at this  
point,'' Moore said. ``Until overall breadth starts to turn down, I 
think the market probably will continue to flex around in here at 
these levels.'' He said that most such declines, especially when 
advances lead declines, are followed by a market rebound. 
</P>
<P>
	The selling Monday accelerated a trend from last week, when  
investors dropped more glamorous Internet and technology shares in 
favor of industrial issues that had been lagging. Dow member IBM 
fell 3 5/8 to 166 3/4 Monday, and AOL had plunged 23 7/8 to 115 7/8 in leading 
volume on the Big Board. 
</P>
<P>
	The industrial stocks that did so well last week can't play the  
role of long-term leaders because they represent a much smaller 
portion of the market than technology shares, said Barry Hyman, 
senior equity analyst at Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum. 
</P>
<P>
	``At some point in time, the tech stocks have to participate  
again if we're going to get a major rally here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq ended 7/8 lower at 22 3/4, after giving up early gains. The  
computer maker, which stunned Wall Street with dismal earnings 
projections earlier this month, disclosed on Sunday that chief 
executive Eckhard Pfeiffer had been ousted and its chief financial 
officer was leaving. 
</P>
<P>
	Some industrial shares held on. Dow components International  
Paper rose 3/4 to 55 3/4. Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing advanced 4 
5/16 to 84 1/4. United Technologies climbed 3 to 145. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 9.02 to 615.88, and the Amex  
composite index declined 10.30 to 735.11. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 9.14 to 412.44.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's main stock index fell 1.05 percent. In Europe,  
the leading market indexes dropped 0.71 percent in Britain but rose 
1.26 percent in Germany and 1.82 percent in France. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
