<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 17:33:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sauvage Wins Wheelchair Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- While Louise Sauvage barely won her third straight  
Boston Marathon wheelchair title, Franz Nietlispach took his third 
in a row with no other competitor in sight. 
</P>
<P>
	Sauvage held off rival Jean Driscoll in the final seconds to  
capture the women's crown on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sauvage, of Australia, and Driscoll, of Champaign, Ill., dueled  
to the finish line for the second straight year. Both finished with 
a time of 1 hour, 42 minutes, 23 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	In last year's race, Driscoll was beginning to raise her hands  
in victory when Sauvage sprinted past her in the final inches. 
</P>
<P>
	Driscoll had won seven straight Boston Marathons when her  
wheelchair overturned on trolley tracks in 1997 about three miles 
from the finish and Sauvage passed her. Driscoll recovered and 
rolled to second place on a flat tire. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, it has been all Sauvage.  
</P>
<P>
	In the 103rd Boston Marathon, the 25th year for wheelchair  
competitors, the two swapped the lead several times, but Sauvage 
held the advantage coming into the end of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was quite happy to be there,'' Sauvage said. ``If I'm in  
front, I'm in control and I like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Driscoll was drafting on her wheels and was waiting to make  
a jump and sprint to victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was hoping to do to her what she did to me last year,''  
Driscoll said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sauvage knew what was coming and began her own sprint before  
Driscoll made her move. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kicked and I figured I had some more if she tried it,''  
Sauvage said. ``I was looking for her front wheel and I never saw 
it. So I kept pushing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Crouched over and pumping in unison, one behind the other, the  
duo rolled toward the finish. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is, obviously, frustrating,'' said Driscoll, who said  
she's not sure if she will return next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Edith Hunkeler of Switzerland, who stayed with Driscoll and  
Sauvage until the 17th mile, finished third in a time of 1:43:48. 
</P>
<P>
	In sharp contrast to the tight women's competition, the lead in  
the men's race never changed after the second mile. 
</P>
<P>
	As he's done for the past two years, Nietlispach used his weight  
-- 187 pounds -- on the downhill stretch to gain a substantial lead 
heading into Heartbreak Hill, a rolling climb between miles 16 and 
21. 
</P>
<P>
	The strategy helped put 3 minutes, 42 seconds between him and  
second-place finisher Saul Mendoza, of Mexico, who led for the 
first two miles. Mendoza, who weighs 125 pounds, had a climbing 
advantage because he didn't have to haul as much weight up the long 
hill. 
</P>
<P>
	But he still couldn't make up the gap between Nietlispach.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was pushing very strong,'' Mendoza said. ``I was hoping I  
could catch him. I was trying to come back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mendoza finished in 1:25:18. He was followed by Scot Hollonbeck,  
of Atlanta, who finished in 1:27:58 after recovering from a crash 
early in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Nietlispach's time of 1:21:36 was 13 seconds off the record set  
in 1994 by Heinz Frei, also of Switzerland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990419.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 09:25:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton To Visit Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, in New York  
for a trip largely designed to explore a potential Senate race, 
said today she plans to go to Albania and Macedonia to meet with 
refugees ``as soon as I'm given the green light to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is very important for me to go to Kosovo  
eventually, but I want to go when my going does not interfere with 
the work and in any way displace resources'' of the international 
community trying to help thousands of refugees fleeing from the 
fighting in Kosovo, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been asked to go. I've expressed my very strong interest  
in going and as soon as I'm given the green light to go, I intend 
to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She made the remarks after meeting with the heads of several  
private foundations raising money to help the refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's meeting with the foundations was the first event  
in a crowded schedule that seems designed to stoke interest in a 
potential Senate campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady is expected to decide in June or July whether to  
seek the seat being vacated by retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick 
Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton said she is seriously considering whether to run  
but insisted her schedule on this trip was a typical one for a 
first lady. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm obviously still considering and exploring (the Senate  
race) and interested in doing so but right now I'm very focused on 
the situation in Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a new poll, from Marist College's Institute for Public  
Opinion, 52 percent of New Yorkers polled said Mrs. Clinton should 
not run, up from 37 percent in a February survey. Forty-two percent 
of voters in the latest poll said she should run, down from 56 
percent in February. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone poll of 512 registered voters was conducted  
Tuesday and Wednesday and has a margin of error of plus or minus 
4.5 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Because this was billed as an official White House trip, the  
taxpayers are paying for the first lady's travel. Her most recent 
foreign trip, a journey to North Africa that ended earlier this 
month, was also considered official business and paid with public 
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton said she might consider establishing an exploratory  
committee to defray the costs of her travel ``if it becomes 
appropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also will be in New York Tuesday and Thursday, mostly for  
events unrelated, such as an education speech this afternoon at 
Columbia Teachers College. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
