<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> African Peace Pact Has Skeptics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Congolese rebels and their Rwandan allies  
voiced skepticism Monday about a peace pact for Congo's civil war 
reached without their participation. 
</P>
<P>
	Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi brokered the cease-fire deal  
between Congolese President Laurent Kabila and the presidents of 
Chad and Uganda, in two hours of talks on Sunday, according to 
Libya's state-run news agency JANA. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people sign a cease-fire, it affects those who have  
signed it, not those who have not signed it,'' Rwandan Vice 
President Paul Kagame told the Congolese rebel newspaper Le Soft on 
Monday in an interview to be published later this week. ``I think 
the agreement is, as far as I can see it, between Uganda and 
Kabila. It remains to be seen if it works.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chadian President Idriss Deby, an ally of Kabila, and Uganda's  
Yoweri Museveni signed the deal with the Congolese leader. It was 
witnessed by Eritrean President Isaias Afwerki, whose country is 
not directly involved in the conflict, JANA said. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan calls for the withdrawal of foreign troops fighting in  
Congo and the deployment of African peacekeepers. Uganda and Rwanda 
have troops backing the Congolese rebels, who took up arms in 
August, while Kabila has military support from Chad, Zimbabwe, 
Angola and Namibia. 
</P>
<P>
	In Congo, rebel leader Ernest Wamba dia Wamba said he was  
unaware of the agreement and waited to be briefed by Museveni, who 
was expected to return to Uganda later Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Congo's rebels have swept through the eastern half of the  
country and threatened the southern diamond and mineral centers of 
Mbuji-Mayi and Lubumbashi, Kabila's main source of revenue. They 
accuse Kabila of mismanagement, corruption and warmongering. 
</P>
<P>
	Cease-fire talks sponsored by Zambian President Frederick  
Chiluba collapsed in Lusaka last week when the rebels walked out, 
saying the government was not talking seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels said they will attend talks in Rome on April 30  
sponsored by the lay Roman Catholic Sant' Egidio Community to 
discuss the future of Congo. But rebel leaders said they would 
attend only if both sides of the conflict are represented and if 
Kabila releases political prisoners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
