<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Monday on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock Market, 
and American Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *Citigroup fell 1 to 70 5/8.    	
</P>
<P>
 *BankAmerica fell 1 1/4 to 71 3/4.    	
</P>
<P>
	Both gave up early gains that came after the banking companies  
announced stronger-than-expected first-quarter earnings. Citigroup 
rose as high as 76 1/4 and BankAmerica rose as high as 76 1/8 before 
retreating. 

</P>
<P>
 *Deutsche Telekom fell 3/4 to 39 15/16.    	
</P>
<P>
 *Sprint Corp. fell 2 5/8 to 97 7/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom confirmed it is in merger talks with Telecom  
Italia. Separately, a German business weekly, Manager Magazin, says 
it will report Deutsche Telekom is negotiating a takeover of 
Sprint. Deutsche Telekom already owns 10 percent of Sprint, as does 
France Telecom. 

</P>
<P>
 *Compaq Computer fell 7/8 to 22 3/4.    	
</P>
<P>
	Compaq, which stunned Wall Street with an ominous earnings  
warning earlier this month, disclosed Sunday that its chief 
executive had been ousted and that its chief financial officer also 
was leaving. CEO Eckhard Pfeiffer, who built Houston-based Compaq 
into the world's largest personal computer maker, had struggled to 
maintain profits while PC prices are plunging. The company has also 
had difficulty integrating two acquisitions, Digital Equipment 
Corp. and Tandem Computers Inc. 

</P>
<P>
 *Theragenics Corp. fell 1 3/16 to 6 13/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	First-quarter earnings were 10 cents a share, down a penny from  
last year. The earnings were in line with Wall Street analysts' 
estimates, but the Buford, Ga., company, which makes a radioactive 
prostate cancer treatment device, still reported a drop in profits 
despite an 11-percent rise in revenues. 

</P>
<P>
 *ZDNet fell 8 3/16 to 31 5/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	Goldman Sachs began coverage at ``market outperform,'' but the  
stock still fell in sympathy with other technology shares. 

</P>
<P>
 *Consolidated Natural Gas rose 3 5/8 to 56.    	
</P>
<P>
 *Columbia Energy fell 1 1/2 to 46 3/4.    	
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy offered to buy Consolidated Natural Columbia for  
$70 a share in cash and stock. Consolidated Natural already has a 
definitive merger agreement with Dominion Resources, Inc., which 
was up 1 15/16 at 40. 

</P>
<P>
 *CompUSA Inc. unchanged at 5 15/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	The computer retailer's shares escaped a brutal selloff in  
technology stocks, after the company said it plans to streamline 
operations at its CompuUSA Net.com Internet-only operations, which 
it said will reduce fourth-quarter profits by $5 million to $8 
million. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Intel Corp. fell 1 3/4 to 55 1/2.    	
</P>
<P>
	The stock gave up initial gains in a big selloff in technology  
shares. The computer chip maker said it will enter the network 
processor market with specific product offerings to be unveiled 
later this year. Intel said its plans include products that will 
support high-speed communication within local-area and wide-area 
networks. 

</P>
<P>
 *ACTV fell 5 1/8 to 15 5/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company bought a patent for a method to link video and audio  
programming to the Internet. The technology allows users to 
``pull'' content from the Internet to enhance television and radio 
programming. 

</P>
<P>
 *USABancShares rose 3 3/8 to 14 1/4.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company activated its new Internet banking system.  

</P>
<P>
 *Vantive Corp. fell 3 1/16 to 6 5/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company, which makes customer-interaction software, said it  
expects to break even this year, less than analysts' estimates of 
profit of 6 cents. 

</P>
