<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Marathon Winners Take On Boston </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The winners of the last three New York City  
Marathons are ready for Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	But something else connects Italy's Franca Fiacconi, Romania's  
Anuta Catuna and Switzerland's Franziska Rochat-Moser. All three, 
without hesitation, insist Fatuma Roba of Ethiopia will be the 
toughest to beat for the women's title in today's Boston Marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	With moderately dry air, mixed sunshine and cool temperatures,  
Roba was favored to win her third straight Boston Marathon. Her 
time of 2 hours, 23 minutes, 21 seconds last year was the third 
fastest on the course by a woman. 
</P>
<P>
	Roba, the 1996 Olympic gold medalist, leads a strong field that  
also includes Lynn Jennings, the top American woman distance runner 
making her official marathon debut. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 'big woman' is Fatuma,'' Catuna said. ``I think we'll stay  
together (in the race). I think I can win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The men's field features defending champion Moses Tanui who  
finished in 2:07:34 last year. He is part of a nine-member Kenyan 
team that includes Joseph Chebet, who placed second last year in 
2:07:37, and John Kagwe, who won his second straight NYC Marathon 
last year in 2:08:12. 
</P>
<P>
	Kagwe ran a personal best and second-fastest course time of  
2:08:12 at New York in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Catuna won the NYC Marathon in 1996, when she overtook Tegla  
Laroupe -- who set the women's world mark of 2:20:47 at Rotterdam 
last year -- and finished in 2:28:28. 
</P>
<P>
	Catuna trains in Boulder, Colo., where the air is clean and the  
hills abundant, to prepare for Boston's hilly course. 
</P>
<P>
	More than any other race, the 30-year-old Romanian said she  
enjoys running the Boston Marathon, citing its history and 
competitiveness -- particularly the women's field. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone wants to run the Boston Marathon,'' Catuna said.  
</P>
<P>
	She said Boston is not as difficult as the New York City  
Marathon because New York has more hills. 
</P>
<P>
	``Boston is easy,'' said Catuna, who placed third in Boston last  
year in 2:27:34. ``It has only four hills. In New York, they have 
plenty. Every two kilometers, there is (another) hill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rochat-Moser disagreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``New York and Boston are very hard,'' she said. ``I don't see a  
lot of differences, they are both very hilly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conditions were favorable with projected temperatures in the  
mid-50s at the start, according to the National Weather Service. 
Temperatures could climb to 60 along part of the course and then 
drop during the afternoon. There was also a chance of showers. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Catuna and Fiacconi, who focus much of their training for  
Boston on hill workouts, Rochat-Moser works on her quick pace. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to have speed, the hills will come on their own,''  
said the 32-year-old who has been running long distances since she 
was just 10. ``I think the race will go very fast. There are a lot 
of good women here, fast women,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rochat-Moser, who trains in Lausanne, Switzerland, incorporates  
cycling workouts into her marathon training. She runs about 100 
miles a week. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiacconi won New York last year in her personal best of 2:25:17  
and has not raced in any other marathons since. In 1997, she ran 
three marathons in 60 days. She placed third at New York, 13th at 
the world championships in Athens, Greece, and second in Italy's 
Capri Marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	Since winning New York, Fiacconi, who at 5-foot-8 towers over  
most of her competitors, has spent much of her time on interviews, 
traveling and training. For the past two months, she has trained at 
her favorite spot, Rocca Canterano, a hilly area outside of Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	In any case, she thinks Roba will be wearing the laurel wreath  
at the finish. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's the Olympian,'' Rochat-Moser said. ``She runs very fast,  
and if she's in good shape, nobody can beat her.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
