<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa Cubs' Owner Has Stroke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Iowa Cubs owner Ken Grandquist suffered  
a stroke over the weekend while watching his minor-league baseball 
team play, and he remains in critical condition today. 
</P>
<P>
	Grandquist, 75, collapsed in his skybox at Sec Taylor Stadium  
during Saturday night's game against Las Vegas, team officials said 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Grandquist, a Des Moines businessman, was listed Sunday in  
critical condition at Iowa Methodist Medical Center, said Sam 
Bernabe, the club's general manager and family spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital said Grandquist remained in critical condition  
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was sitting in his favorite chair in his favorite skybox  
watching his favorite team,'' Bernabe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Grandquist has been talking about selling the Chicago Cubs'  
Triple-A team after this season, but Bernabe said he doesn't think 
that caused him any stress. 
</P>
<P>
	Grandquist has acknowledged talking with various businessmen,  
most recently Michael Gartner, the owner-editor of the Tribune, a 
daily newspaper in Ames. 
</P>
<P>
	Grandquist has said the club is worth from $10 million to $12  
million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
