<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 23:13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CDC Eases Mercury Standard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal health agency is easing its  
benchmark for mercury contamination in a move critics say could 
jeopardize future regulation of mercury in the environment. 
</P>
<P>
	The revised health standard, or ``toxicity profile,'' for  
mercury, announced Monday by an agency of the Department of Health 
and Human Services, sets proposed limits that are three times 
higher than the Environmental Protection Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The relaxation of the standard and discrepancies between federal  
agencies ``will only cause more confusion,'' said Sen. Patrick 
Leahy, D-Vt., who for years has pushed for tighter regulation of 
mercury emissions. 
</P>
<P>
	Leahy and several other senators as well as state environmental  
officials had urged the health agency to hold off on revising its 
toxicity profile for mercury until next year when an in-depth study 
of mercury's health effects is to be completed. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter last month to Health and Human Services Secretary  
Donna Shalala, state environmental officials from the Northeast 
expressed concern that easing the standard would ``adversely impact 
existing state-based public health programs'' for mercury. 
</P>
<P>
	The New England states have some of the highest concentration of  
mercury contamination in waterways in the country and have embarked 
on an aggressive program to try reduce mercury exposure through 
fish advisories and emission reductions. 
</P>
<P>
	But the health impact of low-levels of mercury contamination has  
been widely disputed. Congress last year barred further regulation 
of mercury until the National Academy of Sciences completes an 
18-month study of the health effects next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmentalists as well as some state officials said the  
easing of the standard Monday by the Agency for Toxic Substance and 
Disease Registry at a time when the EPA is standing firm on its 
standards will only add to the uncertainty. 
</P>
<P>
	``It simply sends the wrong message to the public and to the  
polluters that mercury is not a problem,'' Sen. Paul Wellstone, 
D-Minn., wrote Shalala last month when a draft of the revised 
standard began being circulated. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA said in a statement that the health agency's revised  
standard ``should not change any warning or advisory currently in 
place to protect public health from mercury contamination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In easing its mercury standard the health agency also urged  
states and other agencies ``not to change existing fish 
advisories'' based on the new toxicity profiles. ``The amounts 
we're talking about are extremely minute. The difference is very 
small,'' said Kathy Skipper, an ATSDR spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	The health agency said that based on the latest studies, people  
can consume as much as 0.3 micrograms of mercury per kilogram of 
their body weight without health risks. Its previous standard -- and 
the standard still used by the EPA -- has been 0.1 microgram. 
</P>
<P>
	Skipper said the changes were based on examination of new  
studies of low-level mercury contamination from fish consumption. 
</P>
<P>
	But critics said the agency largely based its revision on a  
controversial study in the Seychelles Islands in the Indian Ocean. 
That study found no developmental effects among children whose 
mothers were exposed to levels of mercury somewhat above the 0.1 
microgram threshold while pregnant. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Seychelles study has been cited by industry as  
evidence that the federal health standard of 0.1 micrograms is too 
stringent, it also has come under attack from some health experts 
and environmentalists as possibly an aberration. 
</P>
<P>
	The critics argue another study of children in the Faroe Islands  
off Scotland suggest the opposite. There, researchers found adverse 
developmental effects among children from their mothers' relatively 
low-level exposure to mercury in fish. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're ignoring the Faroes study. They have an agenda that  
they only want to push the Seychelles study,'' said Michael Bender, 
director of the Mercury Policy Project, an advocacy group based in 
Montpelier, Vt., that has been active in lobbying for tighter 
controls on mercury emissions. 
</P>
<P>
	Bender said electric utilities already has been using the  
anticipated easing of the standard based on the Seychelles study to 
argue in Congress and with state officials against tougher mercury 
emission regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Utilities in Wisconsin recently questioned that state's mercury  
reduction programs, including its many fish advisories, in light of 
expected government acceptance of a less stringent mercury 
standard. 
</P>
<P>
	And a manufacturer of light bulbs recently asked the federal  
government consider the expected revised standard when the EPA 
issues its regulations for disposal of mercury-containing lamps, 
according to state officials in Minnesota. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990419.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 20:14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italian, German Telecoms Near Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Telecom Italia SpA and Germany's Deutsche Telekom  
AG are nearing a mega-deal that would create a new global 
competitor to U.S. giants such as AT&AMP;T. 
</P>
<P>
	The move, which would pair two former state monopolies, would be  
subject to intense regulatory scrutiny and would undoubtedly 
present the companies with political and cultural obstacles. 
</P>
<P>
	A Telecom Italia-Deutsche Telekom combination would dwarf its  
competitors in Europe and would most likely become the largest 
merger in history, topping the pending $74 billion deal between 
Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	A Telecom Italia official who spoke on condition of anonymity  
said earlier Monday the two firms' chief executives -- Franco 
Bernabe and Ron Sommer -- would outline the merger agreement at a 
Tuesday news conference in London. 
</P>
<P>
	However, after separate board meetings Monday, both companies  
said the press conference had been postponed, Dow Jones News 
Service and other news organizations reported. Talks are expected 
to resume Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Times reported in its Tuesday edition that the  
main problem appeared to be over the structure of the merged 
company, with the German group demanding a 56 percent stake. The 
London-based newspaper said Telecom Italia officials blamed the 
delay in board approval on the complexity of the merger talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom spokesman Stephan Althoff on Monday declined to  
comment on earlier published reports that the two companies planned 
to fold their stock into a new telecommunications holding company 
on a 60-40 percent basis. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian prime minister's office has said that any accord  
must be on an equal footing, underlining fears in Italy of foreign 
ownership of the strategic telecommunications industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia may not be the only partner Deutsche Telecom is  
eyeing. The German business weekly Manager Magazin issued a news 
release Monday saying that Deutsche Telekom is also negotiating a 
takeover of U.S. telecommunications company Sprint Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a report to be published Friday in the magazine,  
Telekom boss Sommer has been negotiating a deal with Sprint Corp.'s 
Chief Executive William Esrey for several weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Althoff dismissed the story as ``just speculation.'' Officials  
at Sprint did not respond to requests for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia confirmed late Sunday that it was examining the  
possibility of an industrial alliance with Deutsche Telekom. 
Telecom Italia is known to be seeking a white knight to save it 
from a hostile takeover bid by its smaller Italian rival, Olivetti 
SpA. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom and Telecom Italia have refused to say how they  
might share ownership in a combined company and have declined to 
say how they might calculate their respective values in any merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom has a market capitalization of about $117  
billion while Telecom Italia is at about $77 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema said today that any merger  
between Telecom Italia and Deutsche Telekom would require a 
privatization of the German company. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot imagine that a privatized Telecom Italia may merge  
with a company whose main shareholder is the German state,'' 
D'Alema told reporters. Deutsche Telecom is 72 percent-owned by the 
German government. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian government owns 3.4 percent of Telecom Italia, but  
it has veto power over the acquisition of more than 3 percent of 
the shares of the telecommunications company. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti has offered $12.31 a share for Telecom Italia. Olivetti  
plans to proceed with its tender offer despite the German-Italian 
merger talks, company spokesman Ugo Panerai said today. Olivetti 
has already filed a prospectus with the Italian regulatory body 
Consob. 
</P>
<P>
	A merger also would raise a rash of regulatory issues. Deutsche  
Telekom has close financial and operational ties with another major 
telecommunications company, France Telecom. In addition, Deutsche 
Telekom is still majority owned by the German government, which 
would have to divest it in order to gain approval of the deal from 
Italian regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	France Telecom said Deutsche Telekom can't withdraw unilaterally  
from its strategic agreements with the French telecommunications 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our agreements with Deutsche Telekom are clear and  
incompatible with a unilateral strategic turnaround,'' France 
Telecom said. The companies own 2 percent of one another's stock. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
