<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Faces Future Off World Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *AP Photo Planned    	
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Sneered at for decades as one of the  
world's least exciting capitals, Bonn is getting even sleepier as 
the government packs up and leaves for Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
	A dreaded moment came today when parliament inaugurated its new  
home in the imposing, renovated Reichstag: A cause for celebration 
in Berlin, it marked the beginning of the end for Bonn as a 
political center. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonn residents are doing their best to cope, fighting for  
businesses and international organizations to set up shop. But a 
United Nations center for bat research really can't compete with 
the thousands of politicians, foreign diplomats and lobbyists who 
kept the town of 300,000 on the map for the past 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	By fall, they will be gone, when the government takes up regular  
business in Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
	Symbolizing the void in Bonn is the legislature's old quarters,  
a low, boxy structure whose glassy, 1990s remodeling makes it look 
more like an insurance headquarters. Plans to turn it into a 
conference center are on hold because of financing wrangles, so the 
building may wind up empty for a while. 
</P>
<P>
	What hurts more than any economic loss, though, is the lost  
prestige for a place otherwise best known as Ludwig van Beethoven's 
birthplace. 
</P>
<P>
	``Filling the real estate is about the least of our problems,''  
city spokesman Werner D'Hein said. For instance, the 1970s-vintage 
chancellery -- Germany's version of the White House -- will be taken 
over by development aid bureaucrats. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, Bonn is getting a golden handshake from the government.  
More than half the 22,000 federal jobs are staying in the city 
under a complex arrangement that splits many ministries between 
Bonn and Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
	A hefty $1.5 billion in aid for projects such as a new postal  
service high-rise has further sweetened the farewell. German 
telecommunications giant Deutsche Telekom also has set up 
headquarters here. 
</P>
<P>
	In its new role, a more modern Bonn also hopes to shake an  
unflattering Cold War image famously summed up by spy novelist John 
LeCarre. Once a young diplomat at the British Embassy in Bonn in 
the 1960s, LeCarre later immortalized the city in ``A Small Town in 
Germany'' as dank and dreary -- ``an unnatural capital village.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
