<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 103rd Boston Marathon Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The second largest field in Boston Marathon  
history began the race under sunny skies today as defending 
champion Moses Tanui tried to extend Kenya's streak to nine 
consecutive men's victories. 
</P>
<P>
	In the women's division, two-time defending champion Fatuma Roba  
of Ethiopia tried to become the second three-time winner, a feat 
accomplished from 1994 through 1996 by Uta Pippig of Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	As the race began at noon in Hopkinton, 26.2 miles west of the  
finish line in downtown Boston, the sky was bright, the air was dry 
and the temperature was 60 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	And the field of 12,797 official runners was exceeded only by  
the 38,708 entered in the Boston Marathon's centennial race in 
1996. Last year's field of 11,499 is now the third biggest. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of $525,000 in prize money, not counting bonuses for  
record performances, included $80,000 each for the men's and 
women's winners. 
</P>
<P>
	While Kenyans were expected to dominate the men's race, Bill  
Rodgers shared the spotlight. The 51-year-old Rodgers, four-time 
winner of both the Boston and New York City marathons, was shooting 
for the over-50 course record by an American of 2 hours, 31 
minutes, 34 seconds set in 1983 by Norm Green. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodgers, who lives in Sherborn, Mass., wasn't the only area  
runner attracting attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Jennings of Newmarket, N.H., made her official marathon  
debut at the age of 38. She ran in Boston when she was 17 but 
didn't meet the minimum age requirement. Since then, she developed 
into one of the world's top distance runners and won three straight 
world cross-country champions from 1990 through 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Former world-record holder Ingrid Kristiansen of Norway, who won  
the Boston race in 1986 and 1989, also was in the field. 
</P>
<P>
	In the wheelchair division, which began 15 minutes before the  
men's and women's races, another sprint to the finish was possible. 
Last year, Louise Sauvage of Australia edged seven-time winner Jean 
Driscoll of Champaign, Ill., although both were timed in 1:41:19. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanui, who won in 1996 and 1998, was seeking to become the  
seventh three-time men's winner despite a strong field dominated by 
Kenyans. His main competition could come from countryman Joseph 
Chebet, last year's runner-up who finished three seconds behind, 
the fourth closest finish in the race's history. Chebet also was 
the runner-up in the last two New York City marathons. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 race was the first in which three men finished the  
course in less than 2:08. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the top women's contenders besides Roba, the 1996 Olympic  
champion, were the last three New York winners -- Italy's Franca 
Fiacconi, Romania's Anuta Catuna and Switzerland's Franziska 
Rochat-Moser. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
