<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> President of College Board Named </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A former West Virginia governor has been named  
president of the College Board, the nonprofit group that oversees 
the SAT tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaston Caperton, 58, a Democrat, served two terms as governor  
and is widely credited with spearheading improvements in West 
Virginia's public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``He embodies all that the College Board stands for --  
intellectual vision, professional excellence and a commitment to 
educational access and opportunity for all children,'' Thomas W. 
Payzant, chairman of the board of trustees, said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Caperton served as a fellow and instructor at Harvard University  
following his governorship. He is now executive director of the 
Institute on Education and Government at Teachers College, Columbia 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	Caperton succeeds Donald M. Stewart, who held the job for 12 1/2  
years. Stewart is joining the Carnegie Corp. as a program director 
for higher education policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
