<DOCNO> APW19990419.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 09:25:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Says Asian Economies on Mend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Southeast Asia's embattled economies  
are expected to start mending this year, although the recovery will 
depend on the impact of reforms and the mood of world financial 
markets, the Asian Development Bank said today in its annual 
forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the region's more developed countries, the Philippines and  
Malaysia are the most likely to grow in 1999, although at modest 
rates, the bank said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia will continue to have the group's most uncertain  
prospects as its economy attempts to fight back from the ``verge of 
total collapse,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	For all developing countries in the Asia-Pacific region, the  
bank's forecast growth will rise to 4.4 percent this year, compared 
with 2.6 percent in 1998. For 2000, the region's gross domestic 
product is predicted to grow by 5.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the slump in Asian growth that began with the 1997  
currency crisis turned into one of the worst economic performances 
in recent history, particularly for the richer developing countries 
in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank said the outlook for China was positive in 1999, with  
continued growth of about 7 percent likely. 
</P>
<P>
	``The combination of large reserves and stringent restrictions  
on foreign capital movements means that China is unlikely to face a 
financial panic of the kind that struck so many of its neighbors,'' 
it said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the 10 countries in Southeast Asia, growth of 0.8 percent is  
forecast in 1999 after the region's GDP contracted 6.9 percent last 
year, ``under-performing even the most pessimistic expectations,'' 
the bank noted. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia and Thailand are expected to perform the worst among  
Southeast Asia's more developed economies, with zero growth 
forecast for both countries after their GDPs contracted by 13.7 
percent and 8 percent respectively in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Restructuring East Asia's banking systems, whose weakness  
contributed heavily to the region's vulnerability, will be a top 
priority in 1999, the bank said. 
</P>
<P>
	It expressed concern about the region's banking system, marked  
by a sharp increase in bad loans and bank failures, even though 
many countries have instituted ``significant'' financial reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	In many countries, it said, monetary officials have faced a  
dilemma resulting from Asia's currency crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``Defending the currency required maintaining relatively high  
interest rates, but that worsened the financial condition of banks 
and firms,'' the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
