<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 22:24:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kennedy To Sell Bottled Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- As a pitchman for bottled water,  
Robert F. Kennedy Jr. makes a pretty good environmental lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy, a defender of New York City's reservoirs, is launching  
a bottled water called Keeper Springs Mountain Spring Water. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea, Kennedy says, is to capture some of the $4 billion now  
spent annually on bottled water and channel the money into 
preserving public water supplies. Keeper Springs goes on sale today 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy is taking no salary and all profits are to go to  
clean-water campaigns. He said he's so adamant about his campaign 
that he won't drink Keeper Springs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best thing that could happen to our company is to put us  
out of business,'' Kennedy said. ``That's what our aim is, to put 
ourselves out of business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy said that people who drink bottled water are turning  
their back on a public water supply. ``I drink tap water,'' he 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990419.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 17:23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Business Magazine To Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nation's Business, the country's oldest  
business magazine, will cease publication after the June issue, the 
U.S. Chamber of Commerce announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The chamber, which has put out the magazine since 1912, said in  
recent years the publication has been losing $3 million annually. 
The shutdown will result in elimination of 29 jobs in the 
Washington area and a number of sales positions around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Donohue, president of the Chamber of Commerce, said  
closing the publication will allow the chamber to devote more 
resources to its Wide World Web site to enable quicker 
communication with members. 
</P>
<P>
	``Expanding our online communications will enable us to more  
effectively serve, inform and rally the 3 million businesses that 
make up the chamber federation,'' Donohue said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Perkins, publisher of Nation's Business, will be in charge  
of upgrading the chamber's Web site (www.uschamber.org). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990419.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 11:37:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Secular Tensions Looming in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Divisions between religious and secular Jews  
are looming large in Israel's election campaign, with each side 
proclaiming nightmare visions of the life sought by the other. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultra-Orthodox Jews fear the secular majority will turn Israel  
into a spiritual wasteland of Western decadence. Their secular foes 
predict they'll soon be ruled by the ultra-Orthodox. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides are trying to galvanize voters before the May 17  
election with warnings that the other is trying to impose its 
beliefs on the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	``They (the Orthodox) must be stopped,'' is the succinct slogan  
of a secular rights party. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are providing the nation with its soul,'' promises the  
bouncy jingle of an Orthodox party. 
</P>
<P>
	Why the tensions -- a back-burner issue in earlier elections --  
have moved to the forefront depends on who's asked. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orthodox are angry over court rulings rolling back their  
religious monopoly in some areas of civil law. Secular activists 
fear the Orthodox are using their political clout as swing votes in 
governing coalitions to undermine Israel's democracy. 
</P>
<P>
	The confrontation is most intense in holy Jerusalem.  
</P>
<P>
	``My capital marches step by step toward Teheran,'' said Ornan  
Yekutieli, a Jerusalem city council member and secular rights 
activist who once ran a notorious campaign depicting the 
ultra-Orthodox as black dots overwhelming the city map. 
</P>
<P>
	Years ago, street brawls over mixed-sex swimming pools,  
miniskirts and moviegoing were seen as belonging uniquely to 
Israel's capital. Now, the fight has spread across the land. 
</P>
<P>
	Yekutieli campaigns nationwide against ultra-Orthodox schools  
that offer longer hours and free meals to tempt secular parents -- 
and, he charges, hook kids with anti-Western indoctrination. 
</P>
<P>
	``In five years, ultra-Orthodox concepts will rule Jerusalem and  
Israel will follow -- if we don't act now,'' Yekutieli said in the 
cramped city hall offices he shares with ultra-Orthodox council 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonathan Rosenblum, an ultra-Orthodox legal activist, said  
Western liberalism is driving secular parents to schools run by 
``Haredim'' -- a word suggesting ``tremblers before God'' that the 
ultra-Orthodox use to describe themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	He cited a litany of vices he identifies with secular Israel:  
drugs, prostitution, juvenile delinquency. ``When I walked through 
Jerusalem on the Sabbath 20 years ago, it was empty, quiet,'' he 
lamented. ``Now it's hopping'' with discos and bars. 
</P>
<P>
	Each side's argument contains a kernel of truth.  
</P>
<P>
	With about 17 percent of Israel's 5 million Jews describing  
themselves as religious, religious parties won an unprecedented 23 
seats in the 120-member parliament, the Knesset, in the 1996 
election. Orthodox lawmakers provide the votes that keep the 
governing coalition in power and were given control of powerful 
parliamentary committees and government ministries. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side, a series of Supreme Court rulings rolled back  
political arrangements that guaranteed draft exemptions for 
rabbinical students and an Orthodox monopoly in matters of 
conversion, burial and funds for synagogues. 
</P>
<P>
	Another reason for the emergence of secular-religious tensions  
is vacuum in political ideas created by broad acceptance of the 
principle of ceding territory for peace with the Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	``Inevitably, what you now see is a move ... back to the  
internal debates'' over Jewish and Israeli identity, said David 
Rosen, the Israel representative of the U.S.-based Anti-Defamation 
League. 
</P>
<P>
	Activists on either side dismiss talk of natural political  
processes and instead look for conspiracies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Haredim accuse the secular elites of trying to keep them in  
their place. ``We don't trust the state,'' said Itzik Luben, a 
Jerusalem seminary student. ``The state is insane. It's too 
strong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Arieh Deri, the leader of the religious-oriented Shas Party  
and the country's most prominent Haredi lawmaker, was convicted 
March 17 of taking bribes and peddling influence, his defenders 
charged the court was interfering in the election. 
</P>
<P>
	A Haredi demonstration against Supreme Court decisions drew  
200,000; a secular counter-demonstration attracted 50,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Some secular activists go on blitzkrieg operations, tossing  
piles of pamphlets questioning God's existence into rabbinical 
seminaries -- then racing back to their cars, motors running. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Party, always secular but once careful not to alienate  
possible coalition partners among the religious, now sees such 
alliances as hopeless. The party's leader, Ehud Barak, calls the 
Haredim ``extremist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone has given up on dialogue. There has been a  
flourishing of secular-religious discussion groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``Believe me, the first missile from Saddam and everyone will  
love everyone else,'' said Rachel Levy, a religious kindergarten 
teacher who attends weekly discussions at a Tel Aviv pub. 
</P>
<P>
	A few tables down, secular businessman Moshe Elron was not so  
sure. 
</P>
<P>
	``My problem is not with the people here, who want to talk,'' he  
said after an evening of amiable chat with a religious youth. 
``It's with the people who don't.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
