<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Donna Cottier    	
</P>
<P>
	TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) -- Donna Cottier, a former reporter for several  
Ohio newspapers, died Friday. She was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Cottier wrote about events in Maumee, Perrysburg and other  
southern Lucas County communities for 35 years. She joined the 
staff of the Maumee Valley News, a weekly newspaper, in 1951, and 
after that publication folded, worked for The Blade until retiring 
in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include a son, four daughters and eight grandchildren.  

</P>
<P>
                           *Mary Lutyens    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Mary Lutyens, a prolific novelist, biographer,  
magazine writer and editor whose career spanned more than six 
decades, died April 9. She was 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Although she wrote 13 novels and excelled as an editor, she was  
most acclaimed for her biographies, including writings about her 
father -- the well-known architect Sir Edwin Lutyens -- her parents' 
unhappy marriage and her grandfather. 
</P>
<P>
	She also wrote a biographical series on the Indian religious  
teacher Krishnamurti, who was a spiritual adviser to her mother, 
and about art critic and social theorist John Ruskin and his wife, 
Effie. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Don McGuire    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Don McGuire, a screenwriter, actor and  
director who penned ``Bad Day at Black Rock'' and co-created the 
story of ``Tootsie,'' died Tuesday. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Working in the movie industry since the mid-1940s, McGuire won  
Screenwriters Guild awards for ``Bad Day,'' which starred Spencer 
Tracy as a mysterious stranger in a desert town, and the 
cross-dressing comedy, ``Tootsie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGuire also directed Frank Sinatra to a breakthrough role in  
the western ``Johnny Concho,'' which portrayed the cool crooner as 
a coward struggling to build courage for a gun fight. 
</P>
<P>
	As an actor, McGuire was Red Skelton's straight man in ``The  
Fuller-Brush Man'' and appeared in several other movies in the 
1940s. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Albert Popwell    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Character actor Albert ``Poppy'' Popwell, who  
played various thugs in Clint Eastwood's ``Dirty Harry'' films, 
died April 9 of complications from open-heart surgery. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Popwell appeared as heavies in ``Dirty Harry'' and its sequels  
``Magnum Force'' and ``The Enforcer'' before graduating to a police 
detective in the series' fourth installment ``Sudden Impact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eastwood, as Dirty Harry, trained his magnum on Popwell's  
character and challenged him to ``Go ahead, make my day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Popwell's career in entertainment spanned six decades on the  
stage and in film. The New York City native grew up during the 
Harlem Renaissance and danced in Broadway shows as a teen-ager. 
</P>
<P>
	Popwell also had roles in the films ``Cleopatra Jones,''  
``Coogan's Bluff'' and ``The Buddy Holly Story.'' He made 
appearances on such TV series as ``The A-Team,'' ``Wonder Woman,'' 
and ``Night Gallery.'' 

</P>
<P>
                            *Rege Cordic    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Rege Cordic, a popular Pittsburgh radio show  
host, died Friday of brain cancer and related complications. He was 
72. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, his ``Cordic &AMP; Co.'' show commanded 85 percent of  
Pittsburgh's radio audience. 
</P>
<P>
	In March 1943 while still a high school student, Cordic  
persuaded radio host Davy Tyson to let him go on the air at WWSW. 
Cordic became the show's junior announcer and took over for Tyson 
when he went to another station. 
</P>
<P>
	Cordic moved to KDKA in 1954, bringing a cast of characters such  
as the wealthy Baldwin McMoney, punster Carmen Monoxide and Louie 
the Garbage Man. 
</P>
<P>
	Cordic's popularity never caught on in Los Angeles, where his  
show lasted just two years. He became a prolific network TV 
announcer and appeared in such movies as Woody Allen's ``Sleeper'' 
and Brian De Palma's ``Obsession.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, a sister, and four children.  

</P>
<P>
                           *Alan T. Sagal    	
</P>
<P>
	COLLINSVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Alan T. Sagal, a former reporter for  
radio station WTIC and a spokesman for the AAA, Automobile Club of 
Hartford, died Friday of pancreatic cancer. He was 57. 
</P>
<P>
	Sagal began his career in Connecticut radio at WSTC in Stamford.  
</P>
<P>
	He worked at WICC in Bridgeport and as public information  
officer for the state Department of Health Services before joining 
WTIC in 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, Sagal became manager of public and government affairs  
for the Automobile Club of Greater Hartford. He continued his radio 
presence by reporting state weekend events on AM radio station 
WDRC. 
</P>
<P>
	His series ``Traveling in Connecticut,'' which aired Saturdays  
on WTIC, and his AAA feature articles, ``Touring Connecticut,'' won 
numerous awards and led to his appointment to the Connecticut 
Tourism Council by Gov. Lowell Weicker Jr. in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife.  

</P>
<P>
                          *Eddie Saunders    	
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Eddie Saunders, a onetime hotel bellboy  
and street performer who broke the color barrier in Columbus radio 
and television, died Saturday on his 90th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Saunders was best known for his radio program ``Sermons and  
Songs'', which began its Sunday run on WVKO-AM in 1948. The show 
was on the air until 1995, when failing health forced Saunders to 
end the program's long run. 
</P>
<P>
	Saunders also became a TV pioneer through a weekly show on  
WTVN-TV, now WSYX, beginning in the 1950s. 
</P>
<P>
	James ``Eddie'' Saunders was born April 17, 1909, in Virginia.  
During the Depression years he searched for work, singing and 
dancing on street corners for tips. 
</P>
<P>
	Upon his arrival in Columbus during the World War II years, the  
city ``was one of the most segregated'' in the United States, 
Saunders recalled in a 1994 interview. 
</P>
<P>
	During the weekly ``Sermons and Songs,'' Saunders would chat  
with callers, take song requests and relate words of wisdom. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Skip Spence    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Skip Spence, an original member of the rock  
band Jefferson Airplane, died Friday of lung cancer. He was 52. 
</P>
<P>
	Spence's death came weeks before the release of ``More Oar,'' a  
CD tribute to Spence including songs by Beck, Robert Plant, Tom 
Waits and members of R.E.M. The recording was inspired by ``Oar,'' 
Spence's unique, folk-psychedelic solo album from 1969, which will 
soon be reissued. 
</P>
<P>
	Spence had long battled schizophrenia and alcoholism. He had  
been on a ventilator since entering the hospital April 5. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Bill Wendell    	
</P>
<P>
	BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) -- Bill Wendell, the veteran radio and  
television announcer perhaps best known for his ``Late Night'' 
introduction of ``Da-a-avid Letterman!'' died Wednesday of 
complications from cancer. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	The native New Yorker and World War II Army veteran began his  
radio career in the late 1940s and played sidekick to stars such as 
Jack Benny, Bob Hope and Ernie Kovacs. 
</P>
<P>
	Wendell joined the DuMont television network in the early 1950s.  
His television career included a 1969-1978 stint with Garry Moore 
on a syndicated version of ``To Tell the Truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wendell was perhaps best known for his role on ``Late Night With  
David Letterman,'' where he announced the lineup of guests and the 
opening joke that was part of the distinctive introduction of 
Letterman's name. 
</P>
<P>
	Wendell stayed with Letterman when the comedian moved to CBS in  
1993, but retired from the program in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
