<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Criticize Government Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTH ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Farmers fearing that big business  
was squeezing out small producers criticized government policies 
during a rare meeting with two federal officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of farmers who came from as far away as Texas joined a  
rally Sunday billed as the ``Midwest Farm Price Crisis Forum.'' The 
event was organized by Democratic Sens. Paul Wellstone of Minnesota 
and Tom Harkin of Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Joel Klein, an assistant attorney general who directs the U.S.  
Justice Department's antitrust division, and Mike Dunn, who 
oversees the U.S. Agriculture Department's Grain Inspection, 
Packers and Stockyards, flew in from Washington for the rally. 
</P>
<P>
	Klein and Dunn heard from farmers who are concerned about low  
commodity prices and a lack of control in swiftly consolidating 
agricultural industries such as meatpacking, grain-processing and 
farm supply. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going out of business because livestock markets aren't  
functioning anymore and you're not doing anything about it,'' said 
farmer Linus Solberg of Cylinder, Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	The farmers handed Klein and Dunn a seven-point action list.  
Topping the list was a requirement that meatpackers report to the 
USDA what they pay farmers, and to share that information with the 
public. 
</P>
<P>
	According to USDA figures, as of 1997 the four largest packing  
companies accounted for 80 percent of cattle slaughter, 54 percent 
of hog slaughter and 70 percent of sheep slaughter. 
</P>
<P>
	Market shares of the four largest grain exporting companies  
ranged from 47 percent for wheat to almost 70 percent for corn in 
1997, according to the USDA. 
</P>
<P>
	Both federal officials asked the crowd for patience. ``I want to  
be straight with you, and I want to listen,'' Klein said. ``I know 
you want action ... but I've got to know the facts. And when we 
have the facts, we are not afraid to act.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He and Dunn spent much of the afternoon taking notes as farmers  
took turns speaking. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, USDA, I don't want to pick on you too much, but it  
wouldn't even be fair to say you stood by as an agency and let this 
happen,'' said Rhonda Perry, a farmer from Howard County, Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Millions of taxpayer dollars were used to help finance this  
concentration in the form of corporate welfare, in the form of 
guaranteed loans to hog factories,'' Perry said. ``It's no surprise 
to the people in this audience. It's only a surprise, apparently, 
to the people in this administration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unease about market concentration has intensified since Cargill  
Inc. of Minneapolis, the nation's largest grain company, announced 
plans to buy the worldwide operations of second-ranked Continental 
Grain Co. The Justice Department is reviewing the proposed merger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
