<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Errant Bombs Kill 1 in Puerto Rico  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- A civilian was killed and four  
people were injured Monday when two U.S. Marine jets dropped bombs 
on a lookout post at a remote training ground in Puerto Rico. The 
two F-18 jets based on the USS John F. Kennedy aircraft carrier 
were on a night training run over Vieques, said Roberto Nelson, 
spokesman for Roosevelt Roads Naval Station. The base operates the 
training ground in the U.S. territory. Residents oppose the use of 
live munitions on Vieques, saying the frequent explosions disturb 
fishing grounds and have thwarted the island's efforts to attract 
tourism. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Refugee Exodus Halted  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The fate of tens of thousands was  
uncertain Monday as Yugoslavia closed the main crossing point for 
ethnic Albanian refugees fleeing Kosovo. Refugee traffic from 
Kosovo into Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro slowed to a trickle, 
but it was not immediately clear why the refugee flow was halted. 
The Yugoslav government made no statement on the matter. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Still Dogged By Attacks  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO showed dramatic aerial footage  
narrated by a U.S. Air Force general to explain how allied planes 
may have hit civilians during an airstrike in southwestern Kosovo. 
Despite Brig. Gen. Dan Leaf's analysis and videotape of exploding 
vehicles, NATO said it may never know exactly what happened in 
raids on convoys last week. The attack has dogged NATO's air 
campaign for five days, but allied warplanes have continued 
airstrikes, striking today a government building in Serbia's 
second-largest city and a television transmitter in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Florida Fires Burn 130,000 Acres  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Daylight was transformed to darkness Monday near  
the Everglades as smoke from a fire consumed about 130,000 acres. 
The smoke blanketed south Florida's main east-west highway, 
Interstate 75, and forced authorities to keep about 60 miles of it 
closed. The road, known as Alligator Alley, could be closed for 
days. Meanwhile, in communities east of the fire, about 25 miles 
northwest of Miami, people with asthma, bronchitis and emphysema 
were urged to stay indoors if possible. 

</P>
<P>
	2 US Marines Killed in Japan Crash  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A U.S. Marine helicopter crashed into the Pacific  
Ocean during training in southern Japan, killing at least two of 
the four servicemen aboard, the Marine Corps said Tuesday. Japan's 
Marine Safety Agency said a third serviceman was also killed, but 
the Marines said they could not confirm that. No survivors had been 
found by Tuesday morning. The CH-53E helicopter went down in 
northeastern Okinawa on Monday during routine night flight 
training, a Marine spokesman said. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Upholds E-Mail Law  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal law aimed at limiting e-mail smut  
does not violate free-speech rights, the Supreme Court ruled today. 
The court's unanimous decision rejected ApolloMedia Corp.'s 
argument that a portion of the Communications Decency Act of 1996 
threatens free-speech rights. ApolloMedia developed the 
``annoy.com'' Web site to let people anonymously communicate their 
opinions to public officials. 

</P>
<P>
	Italian, German Telecoms Near Deal  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Telecom Italia SpA and Germany's Deutsche Telekom  
AG are nearing a mega-deal that would create a new global 
competitor to U.S. giants such as AT&AMP;T. A Telecom Italia-Deutsche 
Telekom combination would dwarf its competitors in Europe and would 
most likely become the largest merger in history, topping the 
pending $74 billion deal between Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp. 
Telecom Italia confirmed late Sunday that it was examining the 
possibility of an industrial alliance with Deutsche Telekom. 
Telecom Italia is known to be seeking a white knight to save it 
from a hostile takeover bid by its smaller Italian rival, Olivetti 
SpA. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Lower at Midday  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks slipped on Tuesday following losses  
on Wall Street. The Nikkei fell 18.48 points to close the morning 
session at 16,655.73. In New York, the Dow ended down 53.36 at 
10,440.53. The Nasdaq dropped 138.43 to 2,345.61, almost its 
biggest point loss ever. 

</P>
<P>
	Rockets Blast Supersonics 120-113  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Sam Mack led a 3-point shooting show that kept  
the Houston Rockets from blowing a big lead for the second straight 
game as they beat the Seattle SuperSonics 120-113 Monday night. 
Mack was 7-for-11 from 3-point range and finished with 21 points, 
Charles Barkley scored 25 points, Hakeem Olajuwon had 24 and 
Scottie Pippen 22. Houston shot 13-on-27 on 3-pointers. The 
Rockets, who blew a 23-point lead Sunday at San Antonio, built an 
early 16-point advantage before Seattle closed to 105-100 with 3:07 
left. This time, the Rockets didn't fold. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  



</P>
</TEXT>
