<DOCNO> APW19990419.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 09:25:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Will Hear Medicare Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to decide  
whether nursing homes can challenge Medicare regulations in federal 
court without first seeking an administrative decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices said they will hear the federal government's  
argument that federal Medicare law allows the rules to be 
challenged only during specific enforcement proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, the Illinois Council on Long Term Care, which  
represents about 200 nursing facilities, filed a federal lawsuit in 
Chicago challenging new Medicare rules for nursing homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Illinois group said the rules provided stricter guidelines  
and more severe penalties for facilities that did not meet them. 
Before the guidelines took effect in July 1995, only 6 percent of 
Illinois nursing homes were found out of compliance, but the 
Illinois nursing home group said that number went up to nearly 70 
percent under the new rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit said the rules were vague and were not properly  
adopted by federal officials. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge dismissed the lawsuit, saying the federal  
Medicare law required the Illinois council to present its arguments 
first to the Department of Health and Human Services during 
enforcement proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals disagreed and reinstated  
part of the lawsuit. The appeals court said federal Medicare law 
allows such challenges to new regulations to be filed directly in 
federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal granted review today, Justice Department lawyers  
said the Medicare law requires nursing facilities to go through the 
administrative enforcement process before filing a challenge in 
federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	The Illinois council disagreed, but urged the Supreme Court to  
grant review and resolve conflicting appeals court decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Shalala vs. Illinois Council on Long Term Care,  
98-1109. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
