<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Lower at Midday / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was lower against the yen Tuesday  
morning, while Japanese stocks slipped following losses on Wall 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 118.04 yen at midday, down 0.12 yen from late  
Monday in Tokyo but above its level of 117.58 yen in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average fell 18.48 points, or 0.11 percent, to  
close the morning session at 16,655.73. On Monday, the index lost 
177.37 points, or 1.05 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar weakened as U.S. investors  
placed large orders for yen to buy Japanese stocks, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other major currencies, the euro was traded at 125.69 yen,  
down from 125.87 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices were lower following the weakness  
earlier in U.S. stocks, traders said. Many high technology issues 
such as Sony Corp. and NEC were lower Tuesday morning, mirroring a 
selloff in technology shares in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the Tokyo market rebounded slightly from early lows as  
investors bought shares of blue-chips such as Fujitsu, Matsushita 
and Toyota. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average fell Monday  
after five straight sessions of record highs, slipping 53.36 
points, or 0.5 percent to 10,440.53. The Nasdaq Composite Index 
lost 138.43 points to 2,345.61 for its second steepest drop ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section was down 4.68 points, or 0.35 percent, to 
1,328.01. The TOPIX lost 10.34 points, or 0.77 percent, the 
previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond dropped to  
1.505 percent from Monday's close of 1.575 percent, driving its 
price up to 102.60 yen from 101.97 yen. 

</P>
</TEXT>
