<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Antenna Stuck on NASA Mars Surveyor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Scientists were mystified Monday about why  
the main antenna to NASA's Mars Global Surveyor became stuck. 
</P>
<P>
	The antenna is designed to swivel at the end of a boom to stay  
pointed at Earth during communication sessions. The problem, if not 
fixed, would greatly reduce the amount of mapping data the 
spacecraft could send home. 
</P>
<P>
	The spacecraft, which arrived at Mars in 1997 but only began its  
primary mission last month, was otherwise in good health, said 
Joseph Beerer, Mars Global Surveyor flight operations manager at 
NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory. 
</P>
<P>
	The mapping instruments remained off, however, while engineers  
at JPL and Lockheed Martin Astronautics in Denver tried to 
determine what caused the antenna's gimbal to get stuck Thursday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Communicating through a smaller antenna, controllers aimed the  
big antenna at Earth by turning the entire spacecraft about noon 
PDT Monday. About 50 minutes of data recorded Thursday night was 
played back. 
</P>
<P>
	Possible causes of the stuck gimbal include debris in the gears  
or lack of lubrication. 
</P>
<P>
	Mars Global Surveyor has sent numerous detailed images of  
martian features back to Earth since arriving in 1997, but the main 
mapping mission was delayed a year because a weakened joint in one 
of its solar panels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
