<HEADLINE> Porpoise Escapes From NYC Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A small harbor porpoise is back swimming with  
the big fishes after it became trapped in a New York City tidal 
pond. 
</P>
<P>
	When the 4-foot-long mammal turned up in Flushing Creek, near  
Shea Stadium, on Saturday, the city's Parks Department mobilized a 
rescue effort. 
</P>
<P>
	While the porpoise swam in circles for several hours,  
marine-life specialists stood by, ready to haul it back to deep 
water in a plastic net. 
</P>
<P>
	But the porpoise figured things out for itself, using high tide  
to swim back the way it had come -- through a pipe under a railroad 
viaduct -- into Long Island Sound. 
</P>
<P>
	Animal experts said the porpoise probably got lost after playing  
hooky from its school and following some small fry into the creek. 
</P>
<P>
	``It didn't appear to be in any kind of distress,'' said Kim  
Durham, director of the Riverhead Marine Research and Preservation 
Foundation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
