<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women's World Cup Draws Closer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two months before the Women's World Cup, ticket  
sales have exceeded projections and some predict a sellout for the 
opener at Giants Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	On a day when FIFA's tournament trophy was unveiled and English  
pop singer Billie performed the official song, ``Because We Want 
To,'' organizers said the soccer championship has sold more than 
325,000 tickets. Initial estimates in 1997 of potential sales were 
312,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Those estimates have been upgraded to 475,000. And Marla  
Messing, president of the organizing committee, said Monday she 
thinks more than 500,000 tickets will be sold. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the 1994 men's World Cup opened the eyes of the U.S.  
public to what World Cup soccer is all about,'' she said at a news 
conference. ``The Atlanta Olympics opened eyes to the power and 
excitement of women's team sports. We are bringing both of those to 
bear to show the importance and attraction of this event.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 16-team tournament begins June 19 with two games at East  
Rutherford, N.J. More than 44,000 tickets have been sold for the 
doubleheader: United States vs. Denmark followed by Mexico vs. 
Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great place to open the World Cup and it should be an  
exciting atmosphere,'' U.S. veteran Kristine Lilly said. ``This is 
what it's all about for us. We play attractively and with passion 
and we think people will want to come and be a part of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other World Cup teams are North Korea, Nigeria, Germany,  
Italy, Norway, Russia, Canada, Japan, China, Australia, Sweden and 
Ghana. 
</P>
<P>
	The American players understand the significance of their role  
in the tournament, which ends July 10 at the Rose Bowl. If the U.S. 
team flops as the men did in France last year, any hope for huge 
walk-up sales disappears. If the women repeat their performance at 
the 1996 Olympics or 1991 World Cup, both of which they won, the 
tournament could be an enormous success. 
</P>
<P>
	Single-game tickets went on sale Monday for all venues: Giants  
Stadium, Rose Bowl, Foxboro Stadium, Jack Kent Cooke Stadium, 
Soldier Field, Spartan Stadium (San Jose, Calif.), Stanford 
(Calif.) Stadium and Portland (Ore.) Civic Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have said all along that we will have full or near-full  
stadiums for major games like the opening and final,'' Messing 
said. ``And we will have very respectable numbers for the other 
matches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Average ticket sales for first-round doubleheaders not involving  
the U.S. team are at 14,257. 
</P>
<P>
	The trophy, designed by William Sawaya, a native of Lebanon now  
working in Italy, was crafted by hand. It features a spiraling band 
tapering upward to embrace a soccer ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's startling, with a single gesture from the ground, aiming  
high, dancing and rising in a crescendo of movement -- just like the 
growing interest that the world is showing in women's football,'' 
Sawaya said. 
</P>
<P>
	The theme song was performed live by 16-year-old Billie, who  
debuted a song on the British pop chart at No. 1 and has a double 
platinum record. She also will sing the theme at the opener. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990419.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 14:25:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italian, German Telecoms To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Telecom Italia SpA and Germany's Deutsche Telekom  
AG are expected to announce Tuesday that they are merging in a 
mega-deal that would create a new global competitor to U.S. giants 
such as AT&AMP;T. 
</P>
<P>
	The move, which would pair two former state monopolies, would be  
subject to intense regulatory scrutiny and would undoubtedly 
present the companies with political and cultural obstacles. 
</P>
<P>
	A Telecom Italia-Deutsche Telekom combination would dwarf its  
competitors in Europe and would most likely become the largest 
merger in history, topping the pending deal between Exxon Corp. and 
Mobil Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	A Telecom Italia official who spoke on condition of anonymity  
said the two firms' chief executives -- Franco Bernabe and Ron 
Sommer -- will outline the merger agreement at a Tuesday morning 
news conference in London. The planned announcement ends days of 
frenzied speculation about such a move. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia may not be the only partner Deutsche Telecom is  
eyeing. The German business weekly Manager Magazin issued a news 
release Monday saying that Deutsche Telekom is also negotiating a 
takeover of U.S. telecommunications company Sprint Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a report to be published Friday in the magazine,  
Telekom boss Sommer has been negotiating a deal with Sprint Corp.'s 
Chief Executive William Esrey for several weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom spokesman Stephan Althoff dismissed the story  
as ``just speculation.'' Officials at Sprint did not respond to 
requests for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia confirmed late Sunday that it was examining the  
possibility of an industrial alliance with Deutsche Telekom. 
Telecom Italia is known to be seeking a white knight to save it 
from a hostile takeover bid by its smaller Italian rival, Olivetti 
SpA. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom and Telecom Italia have refused to say how they  
might share ownership in a combined company and have declined to 
say how they might calculate their respective values in any merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom has a market capitalization of about $117  
billion while Telecom Italia is at about $77 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema said today that any merger  
between Telecom Italia and Deutsche Telekom would require a 
privatization of the German company. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot imagine that a privatized Telecom Italia may merge  
with a company whose main shareholder is the German state,'' 
D'Alema told reporters. Deutsche Telecom is 72 percent-owned by the 
German government. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian government owns 3.4 percent of Telecom Italia, but  
it has veto power over the acquisition of more than 3 percent of 
the shares of the telecommunications company. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti has offered $12.31 a share for Telecom Italia. Olivetti  
plans to proceed with its tender offer despite the German-Italian 
merger talks, company spokesman Ugo Panerai said today. Olivetti 
has already filed a prospectus with the Italian regulatory body 
Consob. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia's board met Monday to address issues related to  
such a merger, the company official said from Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	Althoff, the Deutsche Telekom spokesman in Bonn, refused to say  
whether the German company's directors were planning a meeting of 
their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``Deutsche Telekom is examining Telecom Italia's potential in an  
industry alliance, but the elements of such an alliance are still 
under evaluation,'' Althoff said. 
</P>
<P>
	Althoff declined to comment on newspaper reports that the two  
companies planned to fold their stock into a new telecommunications 
holding company on a 60-40 percent basis. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian prime minister's office has said that any accord  
must be on an equal footing, underlining fears in Italy of foreign 
ownership of the strategic telecommunications industry. 
</P>
<P>
	A merger also would raise a rash of regulatory issues. Deutsche  
Telekom has close financial and operational ties with another major 
telecommunications company, France Telecom. In addition, Deutsche 
Telekom is still majority owned by the German government, which 
would have to divest it in order to gain approval of the deal from 
Italian regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	France Telecom said Deutsche Telekom can't withdraw unilaterally  
from its strategic agreements with the French telecommunications 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our agreements with Deutsche Telekom are clear and  
incompatible with a unilateral strategic turnaround,'' France 
Telecom said. The companies own 2 percent of one another's stock. 

</P>
</TEXT>
