<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Linux Guru Shines at Comdex Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Margaret Hadam came to the Comdex computer show  
Monday on a mission. But it wasn't Bill Gates -- or the Microsoft 
chairman's glitzy 90-minute debut of Windows 2000 -- she was after. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pleeeeeeeease, Linus, will you sign this?'' the 20-year-old  
university computer tech asked, jamming a program guide in the face 
of Linus Torvalds, the developer of the lesser-known Linux computer 
operating system. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hadam was among the more effusive of the scores of techies  
who jammed an overflowing conference room at Chicago's McCormick 
Place to meet the man who created the operating system she uses at 
Loyola University. But she was far from the only one who asked for 
an autograph or a handshake from the somewhat bewildered Torvalds, 
whom some say is David to Gates' Goliath in the high-tech world. 
</P>
<P>
	Linux is a version of the Unix operating system used by  
businesses to run computer networks and Internet sites. Linux can 
be downloaded for free off the Web; commercial versions with 
additional features can be bought at retail stores for as little as 
$30. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hadam and others praise Linux because its source code -- the  
programming language that makes Linux run -- is also freely 
available, allowing programmers to personalize it to suit their 
needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Torvalds said his system is gaining popularity because it gives  
people what they want. 
</P>
<P>
	``It didn't get to this point because of the hype,'' Torvalds  
said. ``It got here because it does what people want it to do. 
Let's not forget that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he also wants to provide computer users with an option  
to Windows, used to run roughly 90 percent of the world's personal 
computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Linux's use in business computers is a tiny fraction of  
more established Unix systems and Windows NT, and the software 
rarely appears on desktop computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Gates unveiled Windows 2000, the latest generation of  
the Windows NT business-oriented operating system, in a 
presentation that included techno music and tongue-in-cheek videos. 
</P>
<P>
	Gates also showed his sense of humor by showing a clip of last  
year's embarrassing computer crash during the debut of Windows 98. 
In it, his assistant Chris Cappesello looked unpleasantly surprised 
when a blue ``error'' screen popped up for all the world to see. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people have asked me in the last year, 'What happened  
to that guy?' '' Gates told the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Cappesello then walked onto the stage Monday to the tune of ``I  
Will Survive'' and successfully orchestrated a demonstration of 
Windows 2000 as well as other new Microsoft products, including a 
new computer mouse that has no dust-prone moving parts underneath 
and can operated on most surfaces. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials say the latest test version of Windows 2000  
will be distributed to companies nationwide by next month and be on 
the market by the end of the year. Improvements include easier ways 
for company employees to transfer computer documents into laptops 
to take on the road, Gates said. 
</P>
<P>
	His employees also demonstrated Windows-based computers' ability  
to receive images and data by infrared light, rather than a 
hardwire connection -- an option that brought ``oohs'' from the 
crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone was impressed, however. ``Microsoft does a really,  
really good job of selling,'' said Mike Ho, a student at 
Northwestern University who attended Gates' speech. ``But a lot of 
the things from today I've already seen from other companies, like 
Apple.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For her part, Hadam called Gates a ``genius'' and said the  
Windows system -- which, in contrast to Linux, is fiercely protected 
by Microsoft -- may give Gates the competitive edge in the computer 
wars. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're both ruthless,'' Hadam said of Torvalds and Gates.  
``One is just a little more ruthless than the other.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
