<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Rodgers Fades in Record Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- This has been his race. ``Boston Billy'' and the  
Boston Marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Rodgers is one of only three four-time winners of the  
world's most prestigious 26-mile, 385-yard test. So what was he 
doing, six miles from the finish line, stretched out on his back, a 
blank look on his gaunt face? 
</P>
<P>
	At age 51, the hometown legend was trying to recover and facing  
the reality that records and victories are for younger men. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disappointed I couldn't finish,'' he said Monday. ``But I  
didn't want to keel over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From 1975 through 1980, he won four Boston Marathons, the last  
three in succession. His last win came at age 32, and he also won 
four New York City marathons from 1976 through 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	His last serious run in Boston came in 1990, and his last  
attempt to win a marathon -- something he has done 21 times -- was 
the first Vietnam International Marathon in 1992. There, he 
staggered across the finish line in oppressive heat, finishing 19th 
in 3 hours, 19 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	He did return for the centennial Boston Marathon in 1996, but  
ran casually with friends and finished in 2:53. 
</P>
<P>
	He's still very active, having run 29 races at various distances  
last year, and if he runs in Boston again next year, he said, he 
might do it for fun with his brother, Charlie. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll cruise it. I can run the marathon but I can't seem to  
duke it out any more,'' Rodgers said. ``I don't want to end my 
marathoning career with a DNF (did not finish) at the Boston 
Marathon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, he had hoped to break the over-50 course record for  
an American of 2:31:34, set by Norm Green in 1983. Eight days 
earlier, he had set his sights on Green's American record for a 
10-mile race of 52:53. But he missed it by 1:11 at the Cherry 
Blossom Run in Washington. Still, Rodgers was 33rd in a field of 
about 6,200. 
</P>
<P>
	He had been training diligently since December for his 58th  
serious marathon and 16th in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe next time I won't run for any record,'' Rodgers said.  
``I'll just run to finish the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was doing well for the first half of the race, covering it in  
about 1:14. That gave him a chance to break Green's record. Soon 
after, though, trouble began. 
</P>
<P>
	``My legs started to get tight. By the time I hit the hills, I  
was starting to do the marathon shuffle'' as he began to tire, 
Rodgers said. ``Then I started seeing a lot of flashing lights, 
which is a sign of dehydration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And a message that the unseasonably warm day would not be  
remembered for being one of his best Boston Marathons. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't a day to try for a record, no matter what your  
age,'' he said. ``Boston is one of the toughest races to compete 
in, but I did my best. I felt I made a smart decision. I'm 
disappointed I couldn't finish. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're not absolutely on, the marathon will really get you,  
especially if you're pushing hard. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodgers said he was felt tired during the week preceding the  
race. 
</P>
<P>
	He failed to finish only twice before in Boston, in his debut in  
1973 and again in 1977 before he won three in a row. In his last 
two serious attempts at the race, he competed in the master's 
division for runners 40 and older, where he finished second in 1988 
and fifth in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he stayed away for five years before returning as part of  
the 1996 celebration. If he runs in Boston again next year, he'll 
have more realistic expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could run the race, but I can't push hard for records and  
stuff,'' he said. ``Next time I run Boston, I think I'm going to be 
a back-of-the-pack runner. I'm going to have fun out there.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
