<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nets' Williams Vows To Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Despite concern that his career  
might be in jeopardy because of a badly broken right leg and knee 
injury, New Jersey Nets center Jayson Williams pledged Monday that 
he would play next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't feel sorry for me, I'll definitely be back to playing  
basketball,'' Williams said, sitting in a wheelchair with his 
broken right leg extended. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury, which happened April 1 against Atlanta when Williams  
collided with teammate Stephon Marbury, wasn't a simple break. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard it snap,'' Williams said in his first news conference  
since being hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only did Williams sustain a plateau fracture, a break in the  
kneecap area, Dr. Russell Warren also discovered an 8-to-10 inch 
vertical crack in the tibia and a torn meniscus in the knee. 
Williams said the meniscus might have been hurt before he broke his 
leg but wasn't discovered until the surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	The planned one-hour surgery dragged on for five hours, during  
which Warren had to put a plate and five screws in the leg and 
repair the meniscus. A bone graft from Williams' hip was needed to 
repair the plateau fracture. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors have told Williams not to put any weight on the leg for  
eight weeks, and he won't be able to get back onto a basketball 
court for another six to eight weeks after that. 
</P>
<P>
	``He (Warren) has faith that I'll have a full recovery,'' said  
Williams, whose 12 rebounds per game was the NBA's second best at 
the time of his injury. ``He fixed everything and said I'll be back 
40 percent stronger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If this was anyone else other than Jayson I would be  
worried,'' said Nets president Michael Rowe, who signed Williams to 
a seven-year, $100 million contract before the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said doctors have already told him he is already ahead  
of schedule as far as how he can position his leg. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm rushing back to get everything done,'' he said. ``I want  
to be back in training camp.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the funniest men in the NBA, the injury hasn't caused  
Williams to lose his sense of humor. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that he once said the only way he would ever leave a  
game was by ambulance. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the one prediction I predicted right in eight years  
here,'' Williams said. ``I've been predicting championships, 
playoffs wins, wins over the Knicks. I say an ambulance will take 
me out of here before I give up, and sure enough here come the 
sirens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toward the end of Williams news conference, former teammate  
Derrick Coleman came in and gave him a hug. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll see you tonight,'' Williams said as Coleman turned and  
walked away. ``You're driving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even Gov. Christie Whitman, who recently broke her leg in a  
skiing accident, wasn't immune from Williams' humor. 
</P>
<P>
	``She told me she was bearing weight after this accident she  
had, and it was similar, after 7 1/2 weeks,'' Williams said, ``and I 
know I'm in better shape than the governor. I'm not taking nothing 
away from the governor. She's a beautiful woman but I'm a little 
stronger than the governor, a little more popular now, too. We're 
both Republicans. ... I might be a Democrat now.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
