<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nisshin Steel To Cut 21 Pct of Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Major Japanese steelmaker Nisshin Steel Co. has  
decided to slash 1,200 jobs, about 21 percent of its work force, 
over two years, a company spokesman said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The steelmaker expects to save $51 million (6 billion yen) a  
year in labor costs by reducing personnel to 4,400, from 5,600, 
said the spokesman, who declined to be named. 
</P>
<P>
	Nisshin Steel plans to accomplish the job cuts mainly through  
attrition, the spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company calculates a pretax loss of $17 million for the  
fiscal year ended March. It aims to post a pretax profit of $9.3 
million in fiscal 2001 through the restructuring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
