<HEADLINE> CBOT Directors Side With Donovan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The directors of the Chicago Board of Trade gave  
President Thomas R. Donovan a vote of confidence Monday in his 
battle with Chairman David P. Brennan. 
</P>
<P>
	The directors rallied around Donovan, 61, a week after Brennan,  
41, tried to enlist their help in a failed attempt to oust the 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	The 27-member board of directors enacted several motions  
designed to renew confidence in Donovan's leadership and 
policy-making structure. The board also called for ``unity and 
communication among the chairman, president and full board of 
directors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Brennan issued a statement supporting Donovan and the  
board's action. 
</P>
<P>
	``I sincerely regret and accept responsibility for the events of  
the past week. I intend to demonstrate that Tom and I can work 
together,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear whether Brennan -- who was elected by CBOT members  
last December in a narrow upset victory over longtime Chairman 
Patrick H. Arbor -- could be ousted by the directors. Others 
questioned the wisdom of such a move at a time when the CBOT and 
the whole pit-based futures industry is under heavy competition 
from lower-cost electronic rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Brennan who scrapped a Donovan-supported alliance with  
the electronic German-Swiss Eurex exchange earlier this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
