<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blacks Criticize Social Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Harry Dunbar has worked for the Social  
Security Administration for almost two decades without ever getting 
a promotion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had hoped that at some point the agency would use my  
skills,'' said Dunbar, who said he has a college degree but 
described his job as ``paper pushing and, every once in a while, 
furniture moving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a waste of the government's money and my ability,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now in his 50s, Dunbar, who is black, is part of a class-action  
complaint alleging that black male employees get fewer promotions 
and more unsatisfactory job evaluations than warranted by their 
numbers at Social Security's headquarters near Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	He was among scores of the men who traveled by bus to a news  
conference on Monday outside the Equal Employment Opportunity 
Commission's offices here. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunbar and two others first filed their complaint with the EEOC  
in 1995. After a four-year delay caused by the Social Security 
Administration's challenges to the men's right to pursue the 
complaint jointly, the EEOC ruled this year that the case could 
move forward. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission has made no ruling yet on the merits of the  
complaints. A preliminary hearing before an EEOC judge is scheduled 
for May 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Social Security officials denied that the agency treats black  
male employees unfairly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Social Security is one of the most diverse, if not the most  
diverse agency in all of government,'' said Paul Barnes, the 
agency's deputy commissioner of human resources. ``We really do 
look like the America we serve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barnes said that at Social Security headquarters, where the bias  
complaints are being made, 6.7 percent of workers are black men, 
compared with 5.2 percent in the civilian work force nationally. Of 
the most senior executives, 10 percent are black men. And last 
year, 6.1 percent of headquarters employees who received promotions 
were black men. 
</P>
<P>
	As required by law, Social Security has notified 612 current and  
former black male employees of the agency's headquarters who are 
potential members of the class-action complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for the three men who originated the complaint --  
Dunbar, Gilbert A. Jefferson and Kenneth A. Burden -- said they have 
heard from more than 100 others who claim to have had similar 
experiences. They are seeking monetary compensation for the men and 
changes in Social Security's personnel system to ensure fairness. 
</P>
<P>
	``Systematic discrimination has been going on against African  
Americans at the Social Security Administration for decades,'' said 
Michael Kator of the Washington labor-law firm Kator, Scott &AMP; 
Parks. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Kator said statistics on black women's experiences at  
Social Security ``didn't bear out as great a disparity,'' as for 
black men. 
</P>
<P>
	According to 1994 figures reported by Social Security, Kator  
said, black men comprised 9 percent of the workforce in one 
department employing 3,000 people, the agency's Office of the 
Deputy Commissioner for Finance, Assessment and Management. But 
black men in that department received 51.9 percent of the 
disciplinary actions, 75 percent of the discharges and only 6.3 of 
the promotions to the top three federal pay grades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
