<DOCNO> APW19990419.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 02:25:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Threats Disrupt Educators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUNSWICK, Maine (AP) -- When threatening phone calls used to  
ring at Maine's schools, posing the potential to disrupt classes, 
the temptation used to be to call it a hoax. 
</P>
<P>
	No longer. Mindful of recent on-campus violence, school  
authorities don't consider bomb threats on campus as mere crank 
calls made to avoid tests or dodge assignments. 
</P>
<P>
	Maine schools have recorded a half-dozen bomb threats over the  
past month -- reflecting a problem across the country. In Brunswick 
recently, all it took was a single phone call just after midnight 
to turn the town upside down for a day. 
</P>
<P>
	Someone called police to say there was a bomb in the local high  
school. Within an hour, officer Mark Lafountain could hear his 
heart pounding as he and several bomb-sniffing dogs were inching 
through every corner of the school. 
</P>
<P>
	No bomb was found. But the threat shut down the town's six  
schools for the day, forcing parents to scramble for day care and 
tacking an extra school day onto the summer holiday for 3,322 
students. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials should be wary and have ready a crisis  
management plan to handle explosives or bomb threats, said Ronald 
Stephens at the National School Safety Center near Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	``In light of the significant levels of violence that our public  
schools have experienced for the past year and a half, it has 
dramatically changed the way threats are being handled,'' Stephens 
said. ``Threats can no longer be taken lightly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1997, school-related violence has erupted on several  
occasions, most notoriously in Jonesboro, Ark.; in Pearl, Miss.; 
West Paducah, Ky.; Edinboro, Pa.; Fayetteville, Tenn.; Springfield, 
Ore.; and Richmond, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	There are no precise figures on the number of bomb threats at  
schools because educators are not required to report such 
incidents, said Michael Higgins, special programs coordinator for 
the Maine Department of Education. 
</P>
<P>
	In East Montpelier, Vt., educators got so fed up after seven  
bomb threats at a high school that they decided to rethink the 
policy of canceling school. Instead, classes were moved outside. 
Lunch was served from trucks and portable toilets lined the 
athletic field. 
</P>
<P>
	After five threats in two weeks last fall, Fort Dodge Senior  
High School in Iowa began requiring that materials be delivered in 
clear containers. Students are greeted by two guards posted at the 
building's only entrance. 
</P>
<P>
	In Maryland's Anne Arundel County, hundreds of students phoned  
in or posted bogus bomb threats, forcing nearly daily evacuations. 
Now callers to at least one Annapolis high school are greeted by a 
warning that calls may be recorded or traced. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Jersey, the Lower Camden County Regional School District  
adopted a tough expulsion policy last year after it had 50 hoaxes 
at its four schools. Criminal charges have been filed against 27 
people, including 24 students. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if no bomb accompanies the threat, it's still a headache  
for authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a huge disruption in the normal course of business,''  
said Brunswick Police Chief Jerry Hinton. ``This just isn't kids 
out of school for a day. You can't put a dollar figure on it.''' 
</P>
<P>
	In Brunswick, Lafountain and the dogs had to check out the  
entire school, including lockers, ceiling tiles and the noisy 
boiler room. 
</P>
<P>
	He could not turn on the lights, nor could he use radio  
communications, because of fears that electricity or radio waves 
could set off an explosive device. And opening classroom doors was 
terrifying. 
</P>
<P>
	``You always wonder if it's booby-trapped,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
