<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Decide Self-Representation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to use a  
California case to decide whether people convicted of a crime have 
a constitutional right to refuse a lawyer's help and represent 
themselves on appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said it will hear a California man's argument that he  
should be allowed to file and argue his own appeal from his 
embezzlement conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	Salvador Martinez acted as his own lawyer during his trial last  
year in Orange County state court. The jury that convicted him also 
found that he had three prior convictions under California's 
``three-strikes'' law. Therefore, he was sentenced to 25 years to 
life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Last September, Martinez filed notice that he planned to appeal  
and was waiving his right to a lawyer. A state appeals court barred 
him from representing himself, relying on a California appeals 
court decision in 1976 that said ``a criminal defendant has no 
right under the U.S. Constitution of self-representation on 
appeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	California's highest court denied review last October.  
</P>
<P>
	In his self-written brief asking the Supreme Court to hear his  
appeal, Martinez said state and federal appeals courts had split on 
whether the Constitution's Sixth Amendment -- which has been 
interpreted as giving defendants the right to represent themselves 
at trial -- also provides that right on appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, California's lawyers said states are free to devise  
their own systems of review in criminal cases. California rules 
provide for appointment of lawyers to represent indigent 
defendants, they added. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nothing in the text of the Constitution which  
guarantees to a criminal defendant the right to elect 
self-representation on appeal,'' the state's lawyers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Martinez vs. Court of Appeal of California, 98-7809.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990419.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 07:25:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Allows Turtle Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today refused to kill a  
lawsuit seeking to force a Florida county to do more to protect 
endangered and threatened sea turtles. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices, without comment, turned away arguments that local  
governments cannot be sued under the federal Endangered Species Act 
for allegedly doing a bad job of regulating private citizens' 
conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	The county's appeal had raised an intriguing question of  
environmental law and the constitutional balance between federal 
authority and states' rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Female adult sea turtles come ashore in the spring, deposit eggs  
in the sand and return to the ocean. Months later, when sea turtle 
hatchlings break out of their shells at night, they instinctively 
crawl toward the brightest light on the horizon. 
</P>
<P>
	On an undeveloped beach, the brightest light is the moon's  
reflection off the surf. But in a developed area, the brightest 
light can be beachfront lighting -- street lamps, car headlights or 
someone's porch light. Hatchlings attracted to such lights can die 
without reaching the ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	Volusia County, Fla., has more than 40 miles of Atlantic Ocean  
beaches, including the communities of Daytona Beach, Daytona Beach 
Shores, Ormond Beach and New Smyrna Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	The county, not the individual municipalities, has regulatory  
control of all beaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Two women sued the county in 1995, contending that the  
Endangered Species Act required its officials to do more to protect 
three turtle species from the effects of beachfront lights. The 
species are the loggerhead, green and leatherback turtle. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal trial judge dismissed the lawsuit, ruling that the  
women could not sue the county because its regulation of lighting 
did not in itself illegally ``take'' a protected species. Under the 
federal law, ``take'' means to harass, harm, pursue, hunt, shoot, 
kill, trap, capture or collect a protected creature. 
</P>
<P>
	The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated the lawsuit  
last August, ruling by a 2-1 vote that the women had the proper 
legal standing to sue the county of its allegedly inadequate 
regulation of ``light users'' in developed beach areas. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, Volusia County's lawyers argued  
that the appeals court wrongly had expanded the reach of the 
federal law. No other court previously had ruled that the absence 
of private-conduct regulation can violate the Endangered Species 
Act, the appeal said. 
</P>
<P>
	Interpreting the law in that way, the appeal said, intrudes on  
state sovereignty in violation of the Constitution's 10th 
Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	Two conservative legal advocacy groups filed friend-of-the-court  
briefs urging the justices to grant the county's appeal. One of 
them, the Pacific Legal Foundation, said the county was being held 
accountable because it ``has not made it illegal to turn on a porch 
light in Daytona Beach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Volusia County vs. Loggerhead Turtle, 98-1137.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990419.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-19 23:13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
