<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Looking for Late-Season Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The Miami Heat have had fast starts and  
disappointing finishes under Pat Riley. Now, with the fourth 
quarter of the regular season under way, they're trying to come up 
with a new ending. 
</P>
<P>
	Until mid-March, the Heat looked like the team to beat in the  
Eastern Conference, but their 92-88 victory over the Pacers on 
Sunday left them just 8-8 over the past month. Despite weariness 
from the lockout-condensed schedule, Miami is looking for a 
late-season surge. 
</P>
<P>
	``For everybody in this league, there's a big drain mentally,''  
Riley said. ``Games are coming so quick, it's really difficult. 
It's hard to keep the guys excited, even though they know what's at 
stake. You have to find a way to dig down and conjure it up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The final 10 games of the regular season will determine the  
Heat's fate. They began the week with the second-best record in the 
East, two games behind Orlando and one game ahead of Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	If that's where the Heat finish, they would be a No. 2 seed in  
the playoffs and would probably have to face Indiana and Orlando to 
reach the NBA Finals -- a daunting prospect. 
</P>
<P>
	But if the Heat overtake Orlando to earn the No. 1 seed, they  
could avoid facing the Pacers or Magic until the conference finals, 
a much more inviting path. 
</P>
<P>
	``The three teams at the top right now are fighting for their  
lives,'' Miami center Alonzo Mourning said. ``It's up for grabs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Indiana game was the Heat's 18th in a row below 100 points,  
and there have been uncharacteristic defensive lapses, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't want to play the way we've been playing, or you'll  
end up with another first-round disappointment in the playoffs,'' 
forward P.J. Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, the Heat lost six of their final nine games,  
stumbled into the playoffs and were eliminated in the opening round 
by the New York Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami's encouraging win over the Pacers was the first of six  
consecutive games against probable playoff teams. That includes a 
showdown Thursday at Orlando. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers, who finished 2-2 against the Heat, expect to see  
Miami again in the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure we will,'' Indiana guard Reggie Miller said. ``You're  
going to have to go through Miami as well as Orlando to come out of 
the East.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the Heat are clicking, they still can look like the best  
team in the conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Mourning, a dominant defensive force and an improved player  
offensively, is being touted by teammates for consideration as the 
NBA MVP. Tim Hardaway remains one of the league's best clutch 
scorers, Brown has developed a reliable outside shot, and Jamal 
Mashburn and Terry Porter offer other offensive options. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing about the Heat is they play hard for 48 minutes,''  
Pacers swingman Antonio Davis said. ``That's one of the reasons 
they're so tough. If you have just a small lull, they're right 
there ready to jump on you.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
