<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Wants Money in Library Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- An Alaska man wants the city to pay for  
damage to his truck, which was briefly connected to last week's 
deadly shooting at the Mormon church's genealogical library. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Keith Coben Jr., 54, is seeking $5,000 in damages caused  
when the bomb squad blew a hole through his moving van and inserted 
a camera to look at the cargo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I gave them my keys, they didn't need to blow up my truck,''  
Coben told The Salt Lake Tribune in Sunday's editions. ``If the 
police would have either listened or bothered to listen to me they 
would have known in a few minutes that I was not involved in 
this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salt Lake City police Lt. Phil Kirk said officers were only  
acting with prudence during the chaotic hours after Thursday's 
shooting. Coben's yellow moving van was parked three blocks from 
the Family History Library when 71-year-old Sergei Babarin walked 
into the center and allegedly opened fire with a .22-caliber 
handgun, killing two and wounding four. He was killed by police. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers said there was a note pinned to the van reading, ``This  
is a dangerous vehicle because it has gas in it. Any questions and 
I will be up at the library.'' The van contained two 55-gallon 
drums of gasoline. 
</P>
<P>
	Coben -- whom police say argued with an employee at the library  
earlier that day -- was handcuffed and held at the police station 
for nearly seven hours while investigators verified that his truck 
was not connected with the shooting and not wired for explosives. 
</P>
<P>
	``Under the circumstances, which were extraordinary, we needed  
to question him because of a series of eerie coincidences,'' Kirk 
said. ``In order to rule him out, it required extensive 
interviewing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coben said he had the gas in the back of his truck because he  
needed the weight to drive on icy roads from his home in Wasilla, 
Alaska, and fuel is expensive and difficult to find in Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he stopped in to pick up a book at the library, but was  
not involved in a dispute. And he is upset that after the large 
hole was blown in the side of his vehicle, bomb squad members still 
cut the lock to the back door when they entered the van. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirk said officers acted appropriately during the potentially  
volatile situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``If, in fact, it was an explosive device in the vehicle, we  
were faced with the possibility of a booby trap. We had to take all 
the precautions we could,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirk apologized for causing the damage.  
</P>
<P>
	``We want to do our best to make it right,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Coben said his truck sustained about $2,700 in damage, and there  
was damage to $2,500 worth of equipment in the truck. His lawyers 
are scheduled to meet with city attorneys today to determine if he 
will be compensated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
