<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Chief Urges EU Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The head of the European Bank for Reconstruction  
and Development urged European Union members on Monday to reform 
their economies to help boost growth both at home and in the former 
Soviet bloc. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank will increase lending to countries in Eastern Europe  
and the former Soviet Union despite losing an estimated $261 
million as a result of the financial crisis in Russia, Horst 
Koehler told the bank's shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank, which aims to promote the transition to market  
economies, is the largest investor in the private sectors of 
formerly communist countries. Its shareholders are governments and 
international organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now is the time to strengthen economic growth in the EU  
through a new boost for structural reforms in its member states,'' 
Koehler said at the bank's annual meeting. ``It is also the time 
for pursuing enlargement of the European Union to the East still 
more energetically.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Koehler said the union also should strengthen its ties with the  
Commonwealth of Independent States -- the former members of the 
Soviet Union -- and urged the Russian government to improve 
conditions for investment in that country. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank has made a $550 million provision for a loss that  
Koehler blamed on Russia's devaluation of the ruble and the 
collapse of Russia's banking system last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Koehler said the bank had reviewed its business strategy in  
Eastern Europe and will focus on more limited objectives, including 
support for small- and medium-sized companies there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
