<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Daewoo Plans Draw Skepticism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Plans by the heavily indebted Daewoo  
Group to sell off its shipbuilding and other key businesses drew 
applause from the government but skepticism from economists and 
analysts Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Under mounting pressure from the government, Daewoo, the  
nation's second largest conglomerate, announced plans Monday to 
sell off at least 26 businesses by October to improve its financial 
position and focus on key industries. 
</P>
<P>
	That will reduce the number of Daewoo's subsidiaries to eight in  
the automobile, trading and finance sectors and help to 
substantially lessen its debt, company officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We decided to take drastic measures to strengthen key sectors  
and contribute to the nation's economic recovery,'' Daewoo chairman 
Kim Woo-joong said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, the plan calls for the sale of the  
shipbuilding division at Daewoo Heavy Industries Ltd., two 
Hilton-affiliated hotels and four electronics-related subsidiaries 
worth a total of $5.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The Daewoo chairman said the money to be raised will be  
reinvested in the automobile sector and used to pay off bank debts. 
Daewoo Motors Co., the nation's second largest car producer, is 
pushing to take over the industry's newcomer, Samsung Motors Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Daewoo told its creditor banks it will pay back $24  
billion in debts this year by selling off assets. At the end of 
1998, Daewoo had $63 billion in total assets and $50 billion in 
debts. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've made a really huge decision,'' Lee Hun-jae, head of  
the government's Financial Supervisory Commission, said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee said Daewoo set an example for other conglomerates which  
have been slow to slim their overextended business portfolios. 
</P>
<P>
	But many analysts expressed skepticism about the feasibility of  
Daewoo's plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are talking about selling a huge amount of assets. It is  
uncertain how they will find buyers for all that in such limited 
time,'' said Chun Joo-sung, an economics professor at Ewha Women's 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	Chun and many other analysts noted that past promises by the  
nation's top conglomerates to slim down by selling their 
subsidiaries mostly went unfulfilled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
