<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin To Meet Chechnya's President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin announced today he will  
meet the embattled leader of breakaway Chechnya and called for the 
republic to abandon its claim to independence. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting with Chechnya's President Aslan Maskhadov will be  
held in the Kremlin but no date has been set yet, Yeltsin was 
quoted as saying by the Interfax news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will talk about how to live on. What is important is that  
we gave (Chechnya) time to realize that the republic cannot live 
inside Russia without Russia,'' Yeltsin said. 
</P>
<P>
	No country has recognized Chechnya's independence claims. But  
the republic has been running its own affairs -- often openly 
defying Moscow -- since the end of the 1994-96 independence war. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Maskhadov said the Chechen president welcomed  
the opportunity to meet with Yeltsin, but would not give up the 
region's independence, Interfax reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chechnya is prepared for reasonable compromises that do not  
curb its independence,'' said the spokesman, Mairbek Vachagayev. 
</P>
<P>
	Maskhadov has been under pressure from Chechnya's warlords to  
adopt a tougher stance in dealing with Moscow and assert the 
republic's independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Several leading warlords are trying to oust Maskhadov, and there  
have been several attempts on his life in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin insisted Monday that Maskhadov was ``tuned to the  
wavelength'' of negotiating a compromise with Moscow, but hadn't 
yet done so because of strong opposition inside Chechnya, Interfax 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Maskhadov has been calling for a meeting with Yeltsin, but has  
given no indication publicly that he may be considering dropping 
independence claims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
