<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sheiks Enter Kentucky Derby Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Champion horses Aljabr and  
Worldly Manner boarded a flight Monday for the United States, where 
their Arab sheik owners are eyeing America's greatest racing title: 
the Kentucky Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	The chartered flight left Dubai and was to refuel in Shannon,  
Ireland, before heading to Kentucky, said Michael Osborne, chairman 
of the Emirates Racing Association. 
</P>
<P>
	The Al Maktoums, the rulers of the Gulf emirate and probably the  
richest and biggest horse racing owners in the world, have won just 
about every top race in Europe and Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Their bid for the May 1 Kentucky Derby is a shot at racing  
history: The Derby has never been won by an Arab owner. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our hope is to win the Kentucky Derby and show how the  
Emirates is training horses,'' said Sheik Hamdan bin Rashid Al 
Maktoum, deputy ruler of Dubai. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Aljabr, a 3-year-old colt with impeccable bloodlines, and  
Worldly Manner, a bay brown colt, race under the Godolphin banner 
that represents the Al Maktoums. 
</P>
<P>
	Worldly Manner was one of the most successful 2-year-olds in  
America last year before the sheiks bought him from his American 
owners for $5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kentucky Derby will be Worldly Manner's first start this  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The main force behind the Godolphin operations is Sheik Mohammed  
bin Rashid Al Maktoum, Dubai's feisty crown prince with a passion 
for race horses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether or not we succeed (in Kentucky) we will go back,  
because Godolphin is an international stable and we want go 
wherever we can,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheik Mohammed drew a few snickers when he first started buying  
horse races to train in Dubai's sweltering desert climate. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we started Godolphin, my friends and advisers asked me,  
'What are you going to feed them, sand?''' Sheik Muhammed said. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the five years since the Godolphin operations were set  
up, with stables in several countries, the Al Maktoum thoroughbreds 
have become a force in every major race in Europe and Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, in a bid to put Dubai firmly on the racing map, the Al  
Maktoums set up the Dubai World Cup, which attracts some of the 
world's best race horses. 
</P>
<P>
	They now plan to spend $15 million over three years for an  
annual ``World Series'' of nine thoroughbred competitions in eight 
countries, from Ascot to Hong Kong, finishing with the Dubai World 
Cup in March. 
</P>
<P>
	The great Cigar ran the inaugural World Cup. Last month, Silver  
Charm ran sixth in Dubai when Godolphin's own Almutawakel captured 
the $3 million first prize. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Derby, Godolphin will be trying to regroup after a recent  
setback. Prado's Landing, another Derby prospect who came over 
earlier, finished last in the Blue Grass Stakes in Lexington, Ky. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
