<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Seeks Money for Conflict  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today asked Congress for $6  
billion in emergency money for the Kosovo conflict -- with $5.1 
billion for the air campaign and the rest largely for refugee aid. 
The request touched off an immediate scramble as Republicans 
pledged to expand it to meet long-range Pentagon needs as well. 
Some even want to use the legislation to cover a 4.8 percent 
across-the-board pay increase for the military. Also today, 
administration officials proposed boarding and searching ships 
suspected of assisting Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's war 
effort against ethnic Albanians. And the United States sought NATO 
support to block oil from reaching Yugoslavia by sea. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO: We May Have Killed Civilians  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO showed dramatic aerial footage  
narrated by a U.S. Air Force general to explain how allied planes 
may have hit civilians during an airstrike in southwestern Kosovo. 
Despite Brig. Gen. Dan Leaf's detailed analysis and videotape of 
exploding vehicles, NATO said it may never know exactly what 
happened in raids on convoys last week. The attack has dogged 
NATO's air campaign for five days, but allied warplanes have 
continued airstrikes, striking today a government building in 
Serbia's second-largest city and a television transmitter in 
Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole Supports Ground Troops  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole, a Republican presidential  
hopeful fresh from her trip to Macedonia, said today that U.S.-led 
NATO ground troops should be ``pre-positioned in the theater'' and 
prepared to attack if necessary to end the purge of Kosovo. The 
former American Red Cross president said she was moved by her visit 
to refugee camps and by the harrowing stories of Serbian attacks in 
Kosovo. Mrs. Dole and a crowded field of GOP presidential 
candidates are eager to find a voice in the debate over the 
Yugoslavia conflict. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton Moves Closer to Run  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton, edging closer to running  
for the Senate, opened a campaign-style swing today declaring, ``I 
love New York.'' She also announced plans to travel to Albania and 
Macedonia ``as soon as I'm given the green light'' by humanitarian 
workers. This week, she scheduled scores of stops from Long Island 
to Niagara Falls. The latest Marist College poll shows Mrs. Clinton 
in a dead heat with probable Republican Senate nominee Rudolph 
Guiliani. 

</P>
<P>
	Fires Keep Florida's I-75 Closed  
</P>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- South Florida's main east-west  
highway was closed for a second day today as the area burned by a 
fire feeding on dry sawgrass in the Everglades grew to 90,000 
acres. There was no indication when smoke might lift off Interstate 
75. Officials expected erratic wind and dry, warm weather to 
continue for the next day or two, said Gene Madden, spokesman for 
the state Division of Forestry. 

</P>
<P>
	Nasdaq Off 138.43; Dow Off 53.36  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors dumped technology shares today,  
pummeling the Nasdaq Stock Market with its second-biggest point 
drop ever. The wave of selling also wiped out a 270-point gain in 
the Dow industrials. The Nasdaq dropped 138.43, or 5.6 percent, to 
2,345.61. The only time the index had a bigger one-day point drop 
was on Aug. 31, 1998, when it slid 140.43 points. The Dow closed 
down 53.36 at 10,440.53. On the NYSE, advancers led decliners 
1,933-1,195. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Upholds Anti-Smut E-Mail Law  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal law aimed at limiting e-mail smut  
does not violate free-speech rights, the Supreme Court ruled today. 
The court's unanimous decision rejected ApolloMedia Corp.'s 
argument that a portion of the Communications Decency Act of 1996 
threatens free-speech rights. ApolloMedia developed the 
``annoy.com'' World Wide Web site to let people anonymously 
communicate their opinions to public officials by using language 
some might consider indecent. 

</P>
<P>
	Push for Jet Ski Speed Limit  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government and the world's leading  
manufacturer of personal watercraft asked the industry today to 
limit the speed of so-called ``Jet Skis'' to a 65 mph. Bombardier 
Recreational Products, maker of Sea Doo models, announced voluntary 
compliance with the limit on 2000 year models, going on sale early 
next year. The Coast Guard welcomed the initiative. According to 
its records, 4,070 personal watercraft were involved in accidents 
in 1997. Of those, 84 involved drownings. 

</P>
<P>
	Chebet, Roba Win Boston Marathon  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Joseph Chebet pulled away today with about four  
miles left and became the ninth straight Kenyan to win the Boston 
Marathon. Chebet won in an official time of 2:09:52. Fatuma Roba of 
Ethiopia became the second woman to capture the woman's title for 
three straight years. She took the lead just past the midpoint and 
was timed at 2:23:25. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  
</P>
</TEXT>
